<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate Panel Contradicts Pentagon on Gulf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 1 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. Senate committee
said in a report released Tuesday that there was no evidence that
mysteriously ill U.S. soldiers who fought in the Gulf War were
exposed to nerve gas.
</P>
<P>
The Senate Veterans' Affairs Committee said that the Pentagon
was inaccurate to conclude that as many as 100,000 soldiers were
exposed to chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
The Pentagon said last year that up to 100,000 soldiers were
exposed to low doses of nerve gases released in the demolition of
an Iraqi ammunition depot in March 1991, days after the war had
ended.
</P>
<P>
"There is insufficient evidence at this time to prove or
disprove that there was actual low-level exposure of any troops to
chemical weapon nerve agents or that any of the health effects
some veterans are experiencing were caused by such exposure," said
the Senate panel report.
</P>
<P>
The Senate report argued there was no hard evidence to back the
report's conclusions. It said the Pentagon, working with the CIA,
relied on a flawed computer model to re-create the exposure levels
and assumed a worst-case scenario.
</P>
<P>
The Senate study backed up the Pentagon's original position
that U.S. troops were not exposed to chemical weapons during the
Gulf War, despite the mysterious illnesses many soldiers suffered.
</P>
<P>
After five years of denials, the Defense Department reported in
the summer of 1996 that Americans were exposed to chemical
fallout. Initially, the department estimated that 20,000 troops
were exposed, but it revised the figure later. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
