<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin, Clinton Review START Treaties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
and visiting U.S. President Bill Clinton reached broad
agreement on the START nuclear arms reduction treaties Tuesday,
the Kremlin said.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued after the first round of meeting between
Yeltsin and Clinton, the Kremlin said: "The two presidents
discussed matters linked to START I and II and the future START
III agreement."
</P>
<P>
"Concrete tasks were assigned to experts in particular on
defining the basic parameters of START III," it said.
</P>
<P>
Talks on START II, expected to be a major topic of the two-day
summit, has yet to be ratified by the Russian State Duma, (lower
house of the Russian parliament). Duma fears that the START II
treaty would give the United States a strategic advantage.
</P>
<P>
The START II treaty, which the U.S. Senate approved in 1996,
was concluded five years ago. The treaty would reduce the
U.S. arsenal of nuclear warheads to 3,500 and Russia's stock to
3,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
