<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Finland Launches Nationwide Survey on Anti-flood Capacity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Finland is carrying out a
nationwide survey on its flood-combating capacity, the Ministry of
Agriculture announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The survey, aimed at preparing the country for possible serious
floods, started in the wake of the exceptionally huge floods
ravaging central Europe in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The water resource department of the ministry originally drew a
one-year program for the survey. The time-consuming project,
however, has to continue till the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
Ministry officials also announced on Tuesday that the country's
first flood-relief exercise would be held along the Kimi river,
the largest in Finland, in the next year.
</P>
<P>
Finland, a reputed "country of lakes" because ten percent of
its territory is covered by water, was hit by a serious flood in
its eastern lake area in 1899.
</P>
<P>
The Finland people, worried by the frequent occurrence of
floods in some areas in recent years, have developed a strong
sense of combating floods. They demand the government to perfect
its anti-flood system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
