<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Metes Out Sanctions to Pyongyang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Japan decided Tuesday not to
resume normalization talks with the Democratic People's Republic
of Korea (DPRK) following Pyongyang's firing of a ballistic
missile into the Pacific, Kyodo News reported.
</P>
<P>
The decision was reached at a meeting by Japanese Prime
Minister Keizo Obuchi, Foreign Minister Masahiko Komura, Defense
Agency Chief Fukushiro Nukaga and Chief Cabinet Secretary Hiromo
Nonaka.
</P>
<P>
Japan offered to resume normalization talks with the DPRK
without conditions earlier, but abandoned the offer for the time
being, Kyodo quoted government officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese leaders agreed to suspend work on an international
project to build light-water reactors in the DPRK, adding that
they also agreed not to provide food aid to the DPRK for now.
</P>
<P>
The missile firing directly involves Japan's security and it is
an extremely regrettable situation, Nonaka said in a statement
issued after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
"The incident is also extremely deplorable in the viewpoint of
peace and stability in Northeast Asia and nonproliferation of
weapons of mass destruction," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese government would file protests to the DPRK at all
levels and urge the country to stop development and export of
missiles, it added.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK reportedly fired a newly developed, two-stage
ballistic missile Monday that passed over northeastern Japan and
fell into the Pacific Ocean. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
