<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAU Urged to Interfere in Angolan Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican President Joaquim
Chissano and his visiting Algerian counterpart Liamine Zeroural
suggested here Tuesday that the Organization of African Union
(OAU) should interfere in the Angolan peace process.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, the two presidents urged
countries and organizations concerned to double their efforts
in finding out solutions for the crisis in the peace process in
Angola.
</P>
<P>
Chissano and Zeroural also expressed their concern over
the military conflicts in Somalia, Eritrea and Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
"We find that the questions in Western Sahara are far from
being solved, so all parties involved should observe the U.N.
resolutions on issues in the region," Chissano said
</P>
<P>
On Mozambique's debt to Algeria, Chissano said that Algeria
would take a "sympathetic" attitude on the issue, considering
that Mozambique has no such ability to pay it back for the time
being.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique owes about 200 million U.S. Dollars to Algeria
when it imported oil from the northern African country in the
70s and 80s.
</P>
<P>
Zeroural arrived in Maputo Sunday and left for Durban, South
Africa Tuesday for the Non-Aligned Movement summit to be held
Wednesday and Thursday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
