<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Launches Diplomatic Campaign to Dismiss </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus said Tuesday that it
has started a diplomatic campaign aimed at disqualifying a
proposal by Turkish Cypriots on establishing a bi-communal
confederation on this divided island.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Christodoulos Christodoulou, who is also
acting Foreign Minister, told reporters here that President
Glafcos Clerides's reply to Denktash's proposal has been sent to
the United Nations Security Council and other U.N. members.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash proposed the
establishment of a "Cyprus Confederation" with "two sovereign
and equal states" on the island.
</P>
<P>
Clerides, in a written statement from Durban, South Africa,
where he is attending the Non-Aligned summit, stated that "under
no circumstances can Mr. Denktash's proposal form a basis for
talks as it is unacceptable right from the start."
</P>
<P>
He termed the proposal as being contrary to and contemptuous of
the concerned U.N. resolutions, the high-level agreements that
Denktash himself has signed and international law.
</P>
<P>
Christodoulou said instructions had also been given to the
heads of Cyprus' diplomatic missions abroad to make its position
known to the governments and international orgnizations they are
accredited to.
</P>
<P>
Two high-level agreements reached between the Greek and
Turkish Cypriot sides in 1977 and 1979, signed by Denktash
himself, envisaged the establishment of a bi-zonal, bi-communal
federation in Cyprus. This was also included in numerous
U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated
south and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when
Turkish troops took over the northern third of the island in the
wake of a failed coup by Greek Cypriots seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots declared unilaterally in 1983 a breakaway
Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus in the Turkish
Cypriot-controlled north, which was recognized only by Turkey.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
