<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan's top three trade partners in terms of its
exports in the first half of this year are Iraq, with export value
at 99 million U.S. dollars, Saudi Arabia and India, the official
news agency Petra reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Its first three largest trade partners in terms of imports are
Germany, with a volume of 191 million dollars, Iraq and the United
States.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The Agency for International Cooperation of Spain will
provide Jordan 260,000 dollars for an excavation project, the
Jordan Times daily reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement signed here on Monday, the aid will be used
to facilitate the third phase of the excavation and restoration of
the Umayyad Monuments and Amman Citadel.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Israeli Aircraft Industries company has
delivered a Boeing B747-200 to the world's largest
package-delivery firm, the United Parcel Service (UPS).
</P>
<P>
UPS will pay an estimated 1.7 million dollars to the Israeli
company, including the fee for its service to transform a
passenger plane into a cargo one.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Since 1997, some 1,200 small businesses in the
Haifa area in northern Israel have shut down due to a slowdown of
the economy.
</P>
<P>
The Haifa Area Association of Artisans and Industrialists said
that the businesses included those related to the fields of
electronics, metals, printing, furniture and food.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The United States Armed Forces have purchased
software produced by the Israeli Elron Software company for
chemical weapons decomposition facility.
</P>
<P>
The software will reportedly help the facility maximize
productivity and reduce the possibility of illegal usage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
