<DOCNO> XIE19980902.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The Jordanian government has allocated 22 million
Jordan dinars (31 million U.S. dollars) this year to help poor
people, the Jordan Times reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The National Aid Fund has distributed the money to more than
35,000 people in some 6,000 families for them to buy essential
needs, and pay for children's education.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The Jordanian Professional Placement Company will
begin operation late this year to help lower the country's soaring
unemployment and increase foreign currency earnings.
</P>
<P>
The company, Jordan's first state-owned service for labor
export, will help Jordanians find jobs in foreign countries,
especially in the Gulf Arab states, the Jordan Times daily
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Economists said the plan is a feasible way to help the
government tackle the rising joblessness, which is estimated at 15
percent by officials and 26 percent by independent sources.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The recent depreciation of the Israeli currency,
the shekel, will result in an annual increase of 0.8 percent in
inflation, now estimated to reached 4.8 percent for 1998.
</P>
<P>
According to an assessment by economists at the Israeli
Federation of Chambers of Commerce, the depreciation will also
result in price rise of consumer goods.
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- The first half of 1998 witnessed a decrease in
Cyprus' trade deficit by 1.2 percent compared to that of the same
period last year, report said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The report issued by the Statistics and Research Department
said that imports stood at 938.3 million Cyprus pounds (1,876.6
million dollars) from January to June of 1998, 600,000 pounds (1.2
million dollars) less than in the same period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The exports were 315.6 million pounds (631 million dollars) in
the first six months this year, compared to 308.5 million pounds
(617 million dollars) a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the trade deficit totaled 622.7 million pounds
(1,245.4 million dollars), 7.4 million pounds (14.8 million
dollars) less than that in the first half of 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
