<HEADLINE> 12th Macedonian Tomb Discovered in Northern Greece </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Greek archaeologists have
discovered the 12th tomb at Vergina, northern Greece, where the
tomb of Philip of Macedonia, father of Alexander the Great, was
located.
</P>
<P>
Archaeologists said Tuesday that the 12-square-meter tomb was
discovered during work to construct a protective covering over
the excavation sites and was located a short distance from the
first Macedonian tomb discovered in 1865.
</P>
<P>
The tomb, dated to the end of the 4th century B.C., had the
interior walls decorated with red, white and black paint.
</P>
<P>
They believe that the latest finding has fostered hopes that it
may lead to more finds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
