<DOCNO> XIE19980902.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Urges Trade Union to Restrain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu Tuesday called on the Histadrut (Trade Union)
to restrain its wage demand for sake of the nation.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference in his Jerusalem office, Netanyahu said
that the Histadrut and the striking teachers "should show
responsibility for the nation."
</P>
<P>
He also accused the former Labor government of leaving the
country with a huge deficit of 15 billion shekels (about 4.1
billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
But Netanyahu expressed confidence in stablizing the economy,
saying Israel is now "an island of economic stability in the
stormy sea of international crisis."
</P>
<P>
He noted that if he had not acted to cut the national
overdraft, Israel would have had the same fate as Russia, whim
was near bankrupt due to a worsening financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu made the remarks after the Histadrut warned Monday
that it would stage a general strike on Thursday if no progress
was made in the negotiations with the Finance Ministry on its
demand for a 8 percent wage hike for the public sector's workers.
</P>
<P>
But the Finance Ministry is offering only 1 percent increase
for the wage hike.
</P>
<P>
If staged, the nationwide strike would affect all government
offices, the health system, local authorities, universities and
government corporations.
</P>
<P>
Israeli teachers already began a strike on Tuesday morning,
delaying the opening of the new school year and forcing 1.2
million students to stay at home. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
