<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sinn Fein Says Violence "a Thing of the Past" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Sinn Fein, the political wing
of the Irish Republican Army, issued a statement Tuesday declaring
that violence is "a thing of the past -- over, done with, gone."
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams said in Belfast that everyone must
work to make sure last month's Omagh bombing -- which killed 28
people -- was "the last violent incident in our country" and that
Sinn Fein was committed to "making conflict a thing of the past."
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister Tony Blair's chief press spokesman
welcomed the move, calling the announcement "significant."
</P>
<P>
"It confirms the prime minister in his view that Sinn Fein
deserve to be taken seriously in their commitment to exclusively
peaceful means," the spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
Adams made clear he had condemned the Omagh bombing -- carried
out by the Real IRA -- "without equivocation." The Real IRA is a
splinter of the IRA and has declared a cease-fire after claiming
responsibility to the Omagh bombing on August 15.
</P>
<P>
"Sinn Fein has called for a complete halt to such actions and
has urged all armed groups to stop immediately," Adams said.
</P>
<P>
"Sinn Fein is committed to exclusively peaceful and democratic
means to achieve a way forward," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
David Trimble, the leader of the Ulster Unionist Party and the
first minister of the newly established Northern Ireland
parliament, gave the statement a cautious welcome.
</P>
<P>
"Carefully crafted words alone are not enough. The people of
Northern Ireland will now judge Sinn Fein on their actions over
the coming days," Trimble said.
</P>
<P>
"An end to the war means the weapons of terrorism must be
destroyed and all forms of paramilitary violence must cease for
good," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980902.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Chiefs Urged to Help Boost Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Traditional rulers in Zambia
are urged to play a major role in the development and marketing
of the country's tourism, the national tourist authorities said.
</P>
<P>
Angness Seen, Acting Chief Executive of the Zambia National
Tourist Board (ZNTB), said at the weekend that traditional rulers
and local administrations could come together and develop
bankable projects.
</P>
<P>
"Zambia's tourism will only make sense when traditional
rulers, other local authorities and key government departments
realize their major role in the development and marketing of the
industry," she said.
</P>
<P>
ZNTB and the Ministry of Tourism could advise on ideal tourist
facilities and activities in particular areas for inclusion in
the development plans, the acting chief suggested.
</P>
<P>
She said that attracting tourists to a particular area
depended much on accommodation, easy telecommunications and other
basic needs such as fresh water and food.
</P>
<P>
Despite various tourist attractions in Zambia which have
variety of offers, the inflow of tourists has been not very
encouraging.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that Zambia received 340,000
tourists and earned about 75.5 million U.S. Dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
This year, ZNTB expects 400,000 tourist arrivals and 100
million U.S. Dollars from the industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
