<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Says UNSCOM Affiliated to U.S. Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 1 (Xinhua) -- An Iraqi spokesman said on
Tuesday that the U.N. Special Commission for disarming Iraq
(UNSCOM) was not a U.N. organization, rather it was affiliated to
the U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
In an statement carried by the Iraqi News Agency, the unnamed
spokesman said U.S. Ambassador to U.N. Bill Richardson's comment
on the resignation of American weapons inspector Scott Ritter
proved Iraq's charges that UNSCOM is dominated by the U.S.
</P>
<P>
"Ritter's resignation and U.S. media coverage of his
connections with Zionist Mossad (security service) and of UNSCOM
administration's links with the U.S State department and Central
Intelligence Agency all proved Iraq's earlier and repeated
assertion that UNSCOM was not a U.N. organization," said the
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
"Rather," he added, "It is affiliated to the U.S government,
linked to the State Department and its espionage and terrorist
apparatus."
</P>
<P>
In a interview with CNN on Monday, Richardson praised Ritter,
who resigned from UNSCOM August 26 for what he called the
spinelessness of the U.N. Security Council and the U.S., saying
Ritter is a man of integrity, a great inspector, a good American
and a personal friend.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador also commended U.N. chief inspector Richard
Butler, and admitted he had discussed with him technical matters
concerning commission's inspection in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi spokesman said, "Richardson spoke in exceptional
praise of only one among tens of UNSCOM inspectors, describing him
in a manner worthy of only those who rendered greater service to
the U.S. government."
</P>
<P>
He cited as evidence Richardson's acknowledgement of
coordination with Butler even in technical matters.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the disclosure of such illegal connections
between a U.N. organization and the systems of a U.N. member
state made it incumbent on the U.N. secretary-general and the
Security Council to take necessary measures to straighten up the
situation of UNSCOM, break up its dubious links.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated Iraq's call for ending the eight-year sanctions
on the country following its 1990 invasion of Kuwait. The
sanctions-stricken country announced to suspend cooperation with
UNSCOM on August 5, triggering the current standoff with the U.N.
</P>
<P>
However, the crippling sanctions on Iraq cannot be lifted
unless UNSCOM certifies that it has been free of weapons of mass
destruction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
