<HEADLINE> AL Team to Visit Libya on Lockerbie Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League (AL) will
dispatch a high-level delegation to Libya Thursday to coordinate
the Arab stance on resolving the long-running Lockerbie crisis, a
senior Libyan diplomat said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The three-member delegation, headed by AL's Assistant
Secretary General Ahmad Adel, will submit a report to the AL
Secretary General Esmat Abdel Meguid upon its return, said
Libya's permanent delegate to the pan-Arab forum Salma Rashed.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain have recently agreed to try in the
Netherlands two Libyans suspected of blowing up a Pan Am airliner
over Lockerbie, Scotland, in 1988. The bombing killed 270 people.
</P>
<P>
Libya last Wednesday accepted the joint U.S.-British proposal
but asked for clarifications on it.
</P>
<P>
Emerging from a meeting Tuesday with Abdel Meguid, Rashed
reiterated her country's keenness to secure guarantees for the two
Libyans before, during and after the trial planned somewhere in
the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
She reaffirmed the Arab support for Libya's Lockerbie
stance. "The Arab position is backing that of Libya as well as the
Arab League proposal to allow the two suspects to go on trial in a
neutral country. This is the suggestion accepted by both Britain
and the U.S.," she added.
</P>
<P>
The Libyan diplomat said that Meguid had not yet received a
reply from the British government on the guarantees required for
the Libyan suspects.
</P>
<P>
But the AL underlines the necessity of giving Libya enough time
to study the proposal on settling the Lockerbie crisis.
</P>
<P>
Still, she expected a positive development in the U.S.-British
position, noting that her country's approach to the Lockerbie case
is "firm, flexible and logical."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council last Thursday unanimously approved to
lift the sanctions against Libya once it hands over the two
suspects for trial. The U.N. has been imposing air and arms
embargoes on Libya since 1992 to force it to turn over the
suspects in the Lockerbie bombing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
