<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Electoral Bill Passed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 1 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's National
Assembly Tuesday approved the Electoral Bill, which would
regulate next year's general election and all future polls in
South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The opposition National Party (NP) and Democratic Party (DP)
voted against the legislation, South African Press Association
reported.
</P>
<P>
Dene Smuts of the DP predicted that a constitutional crisis
would result from an inability of the Home Affairs Department to
deliver the bar-coded IDs, as required by the bill, to all
potential voters in time.
</P>
<P>
About five million South Africans are believed to be not in
possession of the bar-coded IDs.
</P>
<P>
The DP supported the Independent Electoral Commission's
proposal to recognize all existing IDs, so that the Home Affairs
Department could concentrate on the 2.5 million voters who have
no such documents.
</P>
<P>
Frik van Deventer of the NP said that his party had supported
the idea of only bar-coded IDs being valid, but now it appeared
that the incompetent Home Affairs Department wanted to, at this
late stage, assure parliament it could deliver the estimated five
million outstanding documents.
</P>
<P>
The NP had therefore changed its stance and decided to vote
against the bill, van Deventer said.
</P>
<P>
Desmond Lockey of the ruling African National Congress (ANC),
who is chairman of parliament's home affairs portfolio committee,
said that his party believes the bill would provide a framework
for an orderly, free and fair election.
</P>
<P>
The government had provided an extra 35.6 million Rand (5.5
million U.S. Dollars) for the issuing of the bar-coded IDs, and
he had no doubt that the Home Affairs Department would be able to
meet the target.
</P>
<P>
Home Affairs Director-General Albert Mokoena also assured
parliament members that his department has the necessary capacity
to deliver the new IDs.
</P>
<P>
The bill now has to be considered by the National Council of
Provinces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
