<HEADLINE> UN Wants All Foreign Troops Out of DRC: Annan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 1 (Xinhua) -- United Nations
Secretary-General Kofi Annan said Tuesday that the U.N. does not
support foreign intervention in the Democratic Republic of Congo
(DRC) and would like all foreign troops to withdraw from the
country.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief said that his organization, like the
Organization of African Unity (OAU), respected the territorial
integrity of its member states.
</P>
<P>
"We do not support governments getting engaged in problems in
neighboring countries," Annan told reporters in Johannesburg. "We
want to see all foreign forces withdrawn from the DRC."
</P>
<P>
The withdrawal of foreign troops should be followed by a
return to political dialog leading to elections in the war-torn
country, he said.
</P>
<P>
Annan was making a stop-over in Johannesburg on his way to
Durban for the 12th Non-Aligned Movement (NAM) summit, which
would begin Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He said during his stay in South Africa, he would try to get
all involved parties together to discuss the DRC issue in a bid
to find a peaceful solution.
</P>
<P>
Annan said he hoped to negotiate with the representatives of
various countries during the NAM summit about issues including
the DRC, Libya and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the U.N. stance on Sudan's insistence that the
recent United States bombing of a pharmaceutical plant be
investigated, Annan said that discussions were continuing before
the U.N. Security Council would decide on the matter.
</P>
<P>
He also said that he would make a statement regarding Africa's
international debt on Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
