<HEADLINE> Ugandan House Debates Cease-Fire Motion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan Parliament Tuesday
started debating a motion seeking to oblige the government and
rebels to a cease-fire and constitute a national compromise
commission.
</P>
<P>
The motion was tabled by Aggley Awoli, a member of parliament,
and seconded by some women MPs, Radio Uganda reported.
</P>
<P>
Aggley asserted that apart from poverty and ignorance, the
worst enemy to Ugandans since their independence is political
violence which has already claimed some two million lives.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that the country is spending about 25 million
Ugandan Shillings (20,000 U.S. Dollars) per day to sustain the
operations of the government army and has spent 55 million U.S.
Dollars to purchase the weapons it needs.
</P>
<P>
There are mainly two groups of rebels active in Uganda: the
Lord's Resistance Army in the north and the Allied Democratic
Forces in the west. Having havens in a third country, these
rebels often infiltrate into Uganda to abduct and loot.
</P>
<P>
They also carry out terrorist activities throughout the
country. At present, two of Uganda's four divisions are
stationed in the north and west to counteract the offensives by
the rebels there.
</P>
<P>
Children as young as less than 10 years old can be abducted by
the rebels to reinforce their diminishing military might.
Sometimes, the majority of the attackers are children.
</P>
<P>
Taking rebel activities as a major threat to President Yoweri
Museveni's administration, the Ugandan authorities have tried to
boost the morale and military strength of government troops by
raising their wages and purchasing weapons from other countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
