<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Promotes Small Loan Scheme for Poverty Reduction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Secretary-General Kofi
Annan has urged U.N. systems to promote a small loan program
called Microcredit to benefit some 1.3 billion people in their
efforts to get rid of poverty, said a U.N. report made available
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In his unprecedented report on the subject to the next U.N.
General Assembly one week away, Annan emphasized the
responsibilities of donor countries in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Some 3,000 microfinance institutions in developing countries
have been engaged in the project with the Grammeen Bank of
Bangladesh the most prominent, lending a cumulative 2.1 billion
U.S. dollars to over 2 million people.
</P>
<P>
Similar successful examples are known in Latin America and
Africa in providing loans, a few hundred dollars at most.
</P>
<P>
Women are a major beneficiary group and the destination of the
funds primarily includes agriculture, distribution, trading, small
craft and processing industries.
</P>
<P>
The report said the scheme has helped the poor to be more
self-reliant when they grasp employment opportunities. It also
supports small enterprise sector with some 500 million of the poor
employed in various countries.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank-led Consultative Group to Assist the Poorest has
allocated a portfolio of 218 million dollars for the coordination
of international Microcredit efforts.
</P>
<P>
The U.N., in its first Decade for the Eradication of Poverty
(1997-2006), sees the program as an effective tool in freeing
people from poverty and have helped to increase their
participation in the economic and political processes of society.
</P>
<P>
Donor countries agreed last year to a plan extending small
loans to 100 million poor households by 2005, counting on
additional outlays of 26 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Annan said donors have a special responsibility to ensure that
financial intermediation programs are soundly based, operate
through solid local entities and involve the public sector.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980902.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-01 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
