<HEADLINE> Iran Rejects Accusation of Interference in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Iran on Tuesday rejected the
accusation by Afghan Taliban militia of interfering in
Afghanistan's affairs by staging a massive military maneuver near
the border.
</P>
<P>
"We have never been involved in Afghanistan's internal
conflict and the Iranian consulates were busy with their routine
operations in the past few days in Herat and Jalalabad," Foreign
Ministry Spokesman Mahmoud Mohammadi said.
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi made the remarks in reaction to a statement by
Taliban leader Mullah Mohammad Omar claiming that he is holding 11
Iranian diplomats because 10,000 Afghan people were killed by
Iranian weapons.
</P>
<P>
Omar was apparently referring to Iran's support to the
anti-Taliban Northern Alliance led by ousted Afghan President
Burhanuddin Rabbani.
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi said that "we do not have prisoners of war in
Afghanistan and those taken captive by the Taliban are diplomats,
reporter, lorry drivers or relief workers."
</P>
<P>
He said that Iran would do what it deems necessary to secure
the safety and release of the Iranian diplomats and citizens held
by Taliban early last month after its conquer of Mazari Sharif, a
major stronghold of the Northern Alliance in northern Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
He warned of "grave consequences" if the Taliban refuses to
release the detained Iranians.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the Iranian military exercise along its eastern
borders with Afghanistan, Mohammadi said "it is a warning to those
who violate international regulations and try to damage the
national security and interest of Iran."
</P>
<P>
"Any hostile act against the Islamic Republic of Iran will be
responded strongly," he added. 
</P>
