<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Probe into Lesotho Polls Ended </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The three-nation
commission of inquiry assigned to investigate the alleged
election rigging in Lesotho's May general election completed its
work in capital Maseru Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the commission, Judge Pius Langa of South Africa's
Constitutional Court, said Tuesday that the commission had
completed investigations in 71 of the 80 constituencies.
</P>
<P>
He said the electoral documents have all been examined except
for documents relating to nine constituencies, which are still
the subject of election petition in the Lesotho high court.
</P>
<P>
He said the final report would be presented within days to the
chairman of the Southern African Development Community (SADC),
South African President Nelson Mandela.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho's opposition parties demand an annulment of the
results of the May election, in which the ruling Lesotho Congress
for Democracy (LCD) won 79 of the 80 seats in the parliament of
the tiny mountain kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Opposition parties said that the election was rigged and the
LCD used "ghost voters". Opposition supporters have been
protesting outside King Letsie III's palace for four weeks,
demanding the government be sacked.
</P>
<P>
The Lesotho authorities amended the electoral law last week to
enable the commission, which also includes members from Zimbabwe
and Botswana, and all parties concerned to have access to ballot
boxes and other election documents. The recounting was conducted
at the weekend.
</P>
<P>
During the first phase of its work, the commission of inquiry
talked to members of Lesotho opposition parties and the
government on the opposition's complaints of election
irregularities.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Lesotho Foreign Minister Tom Thabane met his South
African counterpart Alfred Nzo in Durban, South Africa, and
briefed the latter on the latest political developments in the
kingdom. The two foreign ministers also discussed about the
continuing protest by Lesotho opposition supporters. 
</P>
