<HEADLINE> DRC Demands Uganda, Rwanda Withdraw Troops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DURBAN, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Foreign Minister of the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) JC Okoto Tuesday demanded
Uganda and Rwanda withdraw their troops from the DRC territory.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference in Durban, Okoto said that his
government could not accept a cease-fire before Uganda and Rwanda
have withdrawn their troops from the DRC land.
</P>
<P>
Okoto, who is here to attend the 12th Non-Aligned Movement
(NAM) summit, said: "As we have never invited Ugandan and Rwandan
troops to our country, they should have left from our country."
</P>
<P>
Referring to the deployment of troops from Zimbabwe, Angola
and Namibia, Okoto insisted that the DRC government has the right
to ask friendly countries to provide necessary protection.
</P>
<P>
Following series of strong offensives by the rebel forces
against President Laurent Kabila's government, Zimbabwe, Angola
and Namibia sent their troops and arms to the DRC earlier last
month to support Kabila.
</P>
<P>
Okoto called on all the countries, including member states of
the Southern African Development Community (SADC) which are
interested in the DRC issues, to play positive roles in solving
the current crisis in the central African country.
</P>
<P>
On general election issue, Okoto said that the DRC government
never opposed democratic polls, but such election must be held in
accordance with the government's plan. 
</P>
