<HEADLINE> ECOMOG to Move Headquarters to Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The west African peacekeeping
force ECOMOG will soon move its headquarters from Monrovia in
Liberia to Sierra Leone, defense source said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Colonel Godwin Ugbo, acting spokesman of the Nigerian Defense
Headquarters told reporters at a news briefing that about 90
percent of ECOMOG forces are already in Sierra Leone, so it is
proper for the headquarters to be close to the troops.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that about 8,000 Nigerian soldiers in three
brigades are now in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG was formed in 1990 soon after the breakout of the
Liberian civil war and played a major role in ending the war in
1997.
</P>
<P>
Liberian President Charles Taylor, a former warlord who won
the elections monitored by the ECOMOG, has expressed
dissatisfaction with the continued presence of ECOMOG troops in
his country after the war.
</P>
<P>
The ECOMOG entered Sierra Leone soon after the May 1997 coup
of Major Koroma. Though the peacekeeping force drove out
Koroma's men from capital Freetown in February 1998, the junta
forces have managed to survive in the northeast border area.
</P>
<P>
Colonel Ugbo explained that it has been hard for the ECOMOG to
mop up the rebels because the latter are taking advantage of the
difficult terrains in the area and are used to jungle warfare.
</P>
</TEXT>
