<HEADLINE> French Scientists Find New HIV Strain in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 1 (Xinhua) -- French researchers said
that they have found a new HIV strain in a 40-year-old woman in
Cameroon, and they said that the new strain of HIV is genetically
close to a version that infects non-human primates such as
chimpanzees, the Washington Post reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to scientists, HIV constantly evolves into new
strains, even as researchers develop new combinations of therapies
to control its proliferation. In the past two years, new HIV
strains also have been discovered in Thailand and India.
</P>
<P>
The researchers said the genetic profile of the new strain is
closer to the genes of versions of the viruses found in
chimpanzees and other non-human primates. It is not certain how
the Cameroon woman contracted the strain, but the genetic profile
suggests it may have been transmitted from another species.
</P>
</TEXT>
