<HEADLINE> Chernomyrdin Calls for Urgent Measures to Build </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Russian Acting Prime Minister
Viktor Chernomyrdin Tuesday ordered the Central Bank, the Finance
Ministry and the Tax Service to come up with urgent measures to
boost people's confidence.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting of acting ministers, Chernomyrdin listed the
priorities as the insurance of people's deposits, restoration of
the foreign currency market, a balanced exchange rate policy,
preservation of the banking system, strengthening of banks'
liquidity and improved control over foreign currency operations.
</P>
<P>
"Pulling out of the crisis greatly depends today on restoring
confidence in authorities," the Itar-Tass news agency quoted him
as saying after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
"The government needs clear-cut, hard and understandable work.
The measures which we have to take should be convincing as we have
exhausted a limit of errors," he said.
</P>
<P>
Prices continued rising Tuesday as the official exchange rate
for the ruble dropped to 10.883 rubles to the dollar, breaking the
ceiling of the exchange corridor of 9.5 rubles to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
Fare for the Moscow metro system rose from two rubles to three
rubles as of Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin ordered Tax Service head Boris Fyodorov, acting
Finance Minister Mikhail Zadornov and Central Bank chairman Sergei
Dubinin to finalize their positions and "arrive at a set of
immediate joint measures by September 3."
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin demanded that a "practical consideration of
proposals on the tax reform" start immediately. "We would not
survive without a tax reform that would encourage production."
</P>
<P>
In addition, he instructed the Ministry of Fuel and Energy and
the Ministry of Finance to consider the excise issue by Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot be slow, especially in case of oil companies,"
Chernomyrdin said. "The limit of mistakes has been exhausted."
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin was making all the moves despite a vote Monday by
the State Duma, or lower house of parliament, to overwhelmingly
reject his nomination as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
President Boris Yeltsin has renominated him as premier, but the
defiant Duma is likely to block the nomination on the second round
of voting, possibly next Friday.
</P>
<P>
Under the Russian constitution, if the nomination is rejected
by Duma three times, the president will have to submit a new
nominee or dissolve the lower chamber. 
</P>
</TEXT>
