<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Urges Palestinians, Syria Resume Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu called on Palestinian and Syrian leaders
Tuesday to resume negotiations with his government, saying only
it can bring about peace.
</P>
<P>
In an address to a business forum in Tel Aviv, Netanyahu said
that Israel was "very close" to a deal on the next troop
withdrawal from the West Bank with the Palestinians two days ago,
but the Palestinians retreated.
</P>
<P>
"It is important that the Palestinians come back to the
table, and restore and move on the understandings we achieved
in the negotiations," he said.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations with the Palestinians over the long overdue
Israeli withdrawal from the West Bank remain deadlocked following
short-lived optimism late last month.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have rejected the latest Israeli proposal on
making changes to the U.S. initiative calling for a 13.1 percent
pullback. Israel wants to turn 3 percent of the West Bank into a
natural reserve, where it retains security control and the
Palestinians will not be allowed to build.
</P>
<P>
On another stalled track of peace process, Netanyahu renewed
his call for Syrian President Hafez Assad to resume negotiations
with Israel, which have been suspended since early 1996.
</P>
<P>
"I call on President Assad and Mr. Arafat to resume
negotiations for peace with security with the one government of
Israel that can deliver a peace that will be backed by the
entire people of Israel. They can not afford to miss this
opportunity," he said.
</P>
<P>
Israel and Syria have failed to resolve their disputes in the
last two years over how to restart the peace talks. Israel wanted
the talks to be resumed from scratch, but Syria insists they be
revived from where they were left off more than two years ago.
</P>
<P>
Syria said the former Israeli Labor government had agreed
in principle in the negotiations to withdraw from the Golan
Heights, seized by Israel in the 1967 Middle East war.
</P>
<P>
But Netanyahu-led government refuses to make such promise,
citing that the Golan Heights is vital to its strategic security.
</P>
<P>
Damascus has stated repeatedly that without an Israeli
commitment to withdrawal from the Golan, Syria will not agree to
come back to the negotiating table. 
</P>
</TEXT>
