<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Int'l Court Expects 1st Judgement on Crime of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The International
Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda (ICTR) will hand down the first ever
judgement on the crime of genocide by an international court and
pronounce in a separate case the first ever sentence for the 1994
Rwanda genocide.
</P>
<P>
In the dock now are Jean-Paul Akayesu, who was the mayor of
Rwanda's Taba District and whose verdict will be pronounced
Wednesday, and more significantly, Jean Kambanda, who was the
country's Prime Minister during the genocide, and has pleaded
guilty. Kambanda's sentence will be announced Friday.
</P>
<P>
According to a ICTR statement faxed to Xinhua, the trial and
judgement of Akayesu will be the first ever for the crime of
genocide by an international court.
</P>
<P>
Akayesu was indicted on 15 counts of genocide, crimes against
humanity, and violations of the Geneva convention, including
extermination, murder, torture, and rape, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Kambanda on May 1 this year became the first person to accept
culpability for genocide before an international court, it said,
adding that his sentence on Friday will be the first for
genocide.
</P>
<P>
Kambanda was accused of presiding over meetings of the Rwandan
Council of Ministers at which massacres against Tutsis were
discussed.
</P>
<P>
The ICTR is the first international body charged specifically
with prosecuting crimes of genocide. The maximum sentence the
tribunal can impose is life imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
The ICTR, based in Arusha, north Tanzania, was created by the
United Nations Security Council in November of 1994 after one of
the intense periods of mass exterminations in human history.
</P>
<P>
At least 500,000 people, primarily Tutsis and moderate Hutus,
were brutally massacred in just three months in the middle of
that year.
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan,
before leaving for the 12th Non-Aligned Summit in Durban, South
Africa on August 30, said that "the success of this court in
prosecuting genocide is a historic milestone and a defining
example of the ability of the United Nations to create
institutions which fulfill the highest aspirations of mankind."
</P>
<P>
The tribunal has in its custody a total of 26 indicted
Rwandans and five suspects.
</P>
<P>
All the 31 come from what Tribunal Registrar Agwu Okali calls
"the commanding heights" of Rwanda's governing elite during the
time the genocide took place. They were arrested by countries
across Africa and Europe and delivered to the tribunal in Arusha.
</P>
<P>
In addition, another accused, Elizaphan Ntakirutimana, a
Pastor, is being held in Texas in the United States. A U.S.
federal judge ordered his deportation to Arusha on August 5 but
he has one month in which to appeal.
</P>
<P>
The tribunal's next major challenge will be to find the
countries which will accept for incarceration those found guilty.
</P>
<P>
Norway and Denmark have definitively indicated their
willingness to take some of those convicted, and a number of
African states and others have opened negotiations with tribunal
officials as well.
</P>
<P>
However, the tribunal prefers that as many of the convicted as
possible be convicted within Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980902.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mandela, OAU Chief Meet over DRC Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DURBAN, September 1 (Xinhua) -- South African President Nelson
Mandela met Secretary-General of the Organization of African
Unity (OAU) Salim Ahmed Salim here Tuesday, exchanging views over
the Great Lakes crisis.
</P>
<P>
After his meeting with the OAU chief, Mandela told reporters
that they discussed a wide variety of issues, including the
situation in the Democratic Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
Asked for more details, Mandela said: "We are handling the
matter."
</P>
<P>
Salim is in South Africa for a mini-summit of southern African
leaders called by United Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan.
The meeting coincides with the 12th summit of the Non-Aligned
Movement (NAM).
</P>
<P>
Mandela also held talks with the outgoing NAM Chairman,
Colombian President Arrango Pastrana later in the same day.
</P>
<P>
The South African president is to assume the chairmanship of
NAM on Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
