<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Factory Orders Jump High in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. nationwide orders
to factories and plants jumped 1.2 percent in July, the best
performance since last November, the Commerce Department said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Orders totaled a seasonally adjusted 335.2 billion U.S.
dollars, according to the department.
</P>
<P>
July was the second month of recovery in factory orders from a
2.2 percent May drop that was the biggest in three years. In June,
orders picked up 0.3 percent, slightly more than originally
reported.
</P>
<P>
Reflecting the crisis in Asia, U.S. factory orders from April
to June were 0.7 percent below the first three months of this
year.
</P>
<P>
In July, orders for durable goods were up 1.9 percent to 186.4
billion dollars. This represented a slight downward revision from
a preliminary estimate of a 2.4 percent growth.
</P>
<P>
Orders for electronic equipment were up 10 percent in July, as
compared with a 12.8 percent drop in demand for communications
equipment.
</P>
<P>
Similarly, orders for industrial machinery took a strong 1.9
percent increase, led by gains in demand for engines, turbines and
metalworking machinery. However, orders for the category that
includes computers fell by 0.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
U.S. computer manufacturers have been among the hardest hit by
stiff competition from cheaper Asian products.
</P>
<P>
Car production also suffered this summer by a strike at General
Motors. In July, orders for cars and other automotive products
were down 2.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Orders for nondurable goods rose 0.4 percent in July to 148.8
billion dollars, led by books and textiles.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, shipments, a measure of current production, were
down 0.1 percent in July to 334.9 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The backlog of unfilled orders grew 0.1 percent, the first
increase since April, to 529.8 billion dollars. Inventories of
unsold goods were up 0.3 percent to 468.1 billion dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
