<HEADLINE> Foreign Banks Seek Approval to Handle Renminbi Transactions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Six foreign banks in Shenzhen,
a major city in south China, have submitted applications to the
People's Bank of China (PBOC) seeking approval to handle Renminbi
transactions, according to PBOC Vice-Governor Liu Mingkang.
</P>
<P>
Liu told Xinhua that the central bank will examine the
applications in accordance with related procedures and management
regulations.
</P>
<P>
Liu said the licenses "might be issued in the near future."
</P>
<P>
China granted nine foreign banks in Shanghai's New Pudong
Development Area approval to conduct Renminbi transactions in
December 1996. Said banks have since enjoyed smooth developments
in terms of related business activities.
</P>
<P>
The nine banks reported total assets of 1.16 billion yuan by
the end of June this year, with their total outstanding loans
approaching 603 million yuan and total deposits hitting 763
million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the PBOC granted Shenzhen approval as the second
locality to undertake experiments with foreign banks engaged in
Renminbi transactions, with the New Pudong Area receiving approval
to allow additional foreign banks to engage in related activities.
</P>
<P>
Liu said that allowing foreign banks to handle Renminbi
transactions has provided new opportunities for the institutions
to explore market potential and promote business development. The
practice has also provided valuable experience for opening China's
banking sector to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
"Expanding the scope of related experiments is a necessary part
of China's economic and financial development, and demonstrates
the Chinese government's firm commitment to further open the
financial sector," according to Liu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
