<DOCNO> XIE19980902.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profile: Sacked Malaysian Deputy PM Anwar Ibrahim </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Deputy Prime
Minister and Finance Minister Anwar Ibrahim was sacked with effect
from 5.30 p.m. Wednesday, as was officially announced Wednesday
evening.
</P>
<P>
Anwar has also been removed from all other positions held by
him in his capacity as deputy prime minister and minister of
finance, a short statement issued by the Prime Minister's
Department late Wednesday evening said.
</P>
<P>
Anwar, 51, was appointed deputy prime minister on December 1,
1993, succeeding Tun Ghafar Baba.
</P>
<P>
Anwar made a name for himself as a radical student leader in
the early 1970's.
</P>
<P>
He was brought into the government by Prime Minister Mahathir
Mohamad in 1982 when he was initially made a deputy minister in
the Prime Minister's Department.
</P>
<P>
He was later promoted to full minister, moving from the
portfolio of the then Culture, Youth and Sports Ministry in June
1983, the Agriculture Ministry (July 1984) and the Education
Ministry (May 1986) and he was appointed finance minister in March
1991.
</P>
<P>
Anwar also had a rise in the ruling United Malays National
Organization (UMNO). He joined the party in 1982 and became the
UMNO Youth leader in the year and retained the post at a
subsequent party election and went on to win one of the three
vice-president's posts in 1987.
</P>
<P>
He was re-elected vice-president with the highest number of
votes at the next party polls in 1990 and became deputy president
in 1993 when Ghafar Baba stepped down.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Anwar was again returned unopposed as UMNO's No. 2. He
was declared as successor of Mahathir who came to power in 1981.
</P>
<P>
Besides his government and political posts, Anwar also held
posts in several committees, clubs and associations. He was
chairman of the Cabinet Committee on Malpractices in the
government, deputy chairman of the National Information Technology
Council and deputy president of the National Telecommunication
Council. He was appointed earlier this year deputy chairman of the
National Economic Action Council.
</P>
<P>
Anwar was appointed chairman of the Development Council of the
World Bank/International Monetary Fund in April this year for a
two-year term.
</P>
<P>
Anwar is Member of Parliament for Permatang Pauh, a seat in
Pulau Pinang, a northern state in Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Anwar, a graduate from the University of Malaya, received his
secondary education at the Malay College Kuala Kangsar, an elite
school reputed for producing many of the country's leaders in
government and business.
</P>
<P>
Anwar was president of the Malaysian Youth Council (1972-76)
and president of the Malaysian Islamic Youth Movement (1974-1982).
</P>
<P>
He has been president of the International Islamic University
since 1988.
</P>
<P>
Anwar is married to Wan Azizah Wan Ismail and they have six
children. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980902.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albanian Premier Defines Two Main Tasks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- A new constitution and seeking
international support represent two overriding tasks for Albania
at present, Albanian Prime Minister Fatos Nano said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks at a meeting of the Presidium of the
Socialist Party, which focused on Albania's current situation and
the party's future work, the Voice of People newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
Successful completion of anyone of the tasks will greatly
enhance the function of the government and its image both among
the people and its foreign partners, he said.
</P>
<P>
More important, Nano said, completion of the tasks, one on law
and another on economy, will bring the Albanian people what they
are dreaming of.
</P>
<P>
He also urged all governmental departments and branches to poll
efforts in turning such a promising future into reality.
</P>
<P>
Albania's former Democratic Party administration drafted a
constitution which was turned down in a referendum last year.
</P>
<P>
The current People's Assembly, headed by the Socialist Party,
put the constitution-drawing on its agenda shortly after its
formation last year.
</P>
<P>
However, hindered by the opposition parties, the
constitution-drawing work is going forward very slowly.
</P>
<P>
Assistance from the international community also has been
suspended or postponed since the outbreak of a nationwide turmoil
last year.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister called for more efforts to strengthen
security at home, so as to create an environment favorable for
foreign investment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
