<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 14:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Warns to Take Actions Against Possible U.N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister
Tariq Aziz warned on Wednesday that Iraq will take further
decisive actions to protect its interests and security if the
U.N. Security Council adopts a hostile resolution against it.
</P>
<P>
Aziz was commenting in a statement on a draft resolution
submitted by the United States and Britain to the Security Council
proposing the council's review of sanctions on Iraq every 60 days
be suspended.
</P>
<P>
But he did not specify what steps Iraq would take if the
resolution is passed.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been under sweeping U.N. trade embargo since 1990 when
it invaded Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
"Suspending the review of sanctions, so far held for 40 times
with no result achieved, means nothing to Iraq other than
confirming the fact that continued dealing with UNSCOM is of no
use," Aziz said.
</P>
<P>
Iraq decided on August 5 to suspend cooperation with the
UNSCOM, the U.N. special commission charged with overseeing
disarmament of Iraq, accusing it of being dominated and used by
the U.S. as a tool to prolong the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said that the adoption of the draft resolution by the
Security Council would implicate that the council attaches no
seriousness to Iraq's legitimate demands, which he said should not
be ignored.
</P>
<P>
He cautioned that "he who imagines that Iraq could revoke,
under such pressures, threats or whatever, its decision of August
5, is only under a grand illusion."
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been calling for the lifting of U.N. sanctions,
arguing that it has fully cooperated with the UNSCOM and destroyed
all weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
The UNSCOM should issue a clean bill of health on Iraq before
the U.N. Security Council can lift the sanctions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980902.0054 </DOCNO>
