<HEADLINE> Mongolian President Calls for New Nominee for Premiership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Mongolian President
Nachagyn Bagabandy urged the ruling coalition on Wednesday to find
a new candidate for premiership within this week to end the
month-long political standoff.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to President of the Mongolian National Democratic
Party Tsakhiya Elbegdorj and Chairman of the Mongolian Social
Democratic Party Radnaasumberel Gonchigdorj, Bagabandy asked the
two partners of the ruling coalition to nominate a new candidate
for him to confirm.
</P>
<P>
The candidate should also be approved by the Great Hural (the
Mongolian parliament) after confirmation by the president.
</P>
<P>
The Great Hural on Wednesday rejected the candidacy of
R. Amarjargal, acting minister of external affairs, saying that no
minister of the former government should become new prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Under fire for a bank merger, Mongolia's three-month old
coalition government led by Elbegdorj was dismissed on July 24
after losing a vote of confidence in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
Afterward, the coalition repeatedly nominated Davaadorj
Ganbold, chairman of the Standing Committee of Economic Policy of
the Great Hural, who was turned down by the president five times.
</P>
<P>
Observers believe that the political crisis in Mongolia would
deepen amid the naming of a new prime minister.
</P>
<P>
As a matter of fact, the minority Mongolian People's
Revolutionary Party made a statement recently, saying that the
unicameral Great Hural should be dissolved if it fails to appoint
a prime minister in the near future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
