<DOCNO> XIE19980902.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Historians Create Complete Chronology for Chinese History (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A number of domestic and overseas historians claim the Xia
Dynasty quite likely originated from the late period of the
Longshan Culture. The small town found Yanshi could well be the
first Shang Dynasty town and indeed the beginning of the ancient
dynasty.
</P>
<P>
Li, the chief historian for the complicated studies, said the
team of experienced researchers selected 220 samples from more
than 100,000 unearthed bones and inscribed tortoise shells.
</P>
<P>
The team will accurately date the samples which date from the
reigns of King Wuding to King Zhou in the Shang
Dynasty. Researchers will consult ancient astronomical almanacs
which will provide an exact chronicle of the late period of the
dynasty, said Li.
</P>
<P>
Liu Ciyuan, a research fellow with Shaanxi Astronomical
Observatory, and his team observed the eclipse on March 9, 1997,
in Tacheng Prefecture in the westernmost section of the Xinjiang
Uygur Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The team was determined that the special record found in the
ancient version of the chronicle referred to a solar
eclipse. Careful calculations enabled astronomers to confirm
that the eclipse occurred on April 21, 899 B.C.
</P>
<P>
Historians also consulted a complete set of ancient documents
covering periods before the Tang Dynasty (618-907) and materials
for the period after the Song Dynasty (960-1279).
</P>
<P>
The research endeavor was initiated in May, 1996, and numerous
well-known historians have since worked on more than 30 specified
subjects.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
