<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Duma Urges Chernomyrdin to Give up Premiership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The Russian State Duma on
Wednesday passed a resolution to urge acting Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin to voluntarily reject the post of prime minister.
</P>
<P>
The resolution was passed 255-40 with no abstentions in the
lower house of parliament, the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"Your voluntary rejection of the position of prime minister
could significantly reduce the tension and lead to a search for a
compromise," the document says.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin was nominated by President Boris Yeltsin as prime
minister on August 25, but the nomination was rejected
overwhelmingly by the State Duma on Monday in the first round of
voting.
</P>
<P>
The Duma resolution, to be addressed to Chernomyrdin in the
form of a letter, said his nomination "has resulted in a tough
confrontation between branches of the authority."
</P>
<P>
"Continued attempts by President Yeltsin to force your
appointment through parliament are doomed," said the letter,
drafted by members of the Communist, Yabloko, Agrarian, Popular
Rule and Russian Regions groups, the Interfax news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Vladimir Zhirinovsky of the ultranationalist Liberal
Democratic Party, who on Monday named himself a candidate for the
premiership, changed sides on Wednesday, saying he supports
Chernomyrdin's nomination.
</P>
<P>
The State Duma is scheduled to hold a second round of voting on
Chernomyrdin's nomination on Friday. Most opposition parties have
indicated that they would vote against him.
</P>
<P>
Under Russian constitution, if the Duma blocks nomination of
the premiership three times, the president will have to either
name a new candidate or dissolve the lower chamber.
</P>
<P>
However, Wednesday's letter to Chernomyrdin says that "the
dissolution of the State Duma will not alleviate the
crisis. Rather, it will bring about irreconcilable political
confrontation."
</P>
<P>
"Chernomyrdin has found himself in the center of a conflict
and now has to make a decision which will shape the fate of the
entire country as well as his own," the document said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
