<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Historians Create Complete Chronology for Chinese History (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Chinese historians are
attempting to unravel the chronology of the nation's 5,000 years
of development.
</P>
<P>
The existing historical chronicle for China, one of the world's
four ancient civilized nations, begins in 841 B.C., with no
precise record for nearly half of the nation's remote history.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the government organized a project to determine
precise dates for the Xia, Shang and Zhou dynasties which featured
the spread of abundant legends and anecdotes. The major study
focuses on events some 2,800-4,000 years ago and in accurately
apportioned the lengths of the three dynasties.
</P>
<P>
The Henan Institute of Cultural Relics and Archeology recently
completed excavations at Wadian in Yuxian County, an area in the
central part of the province which experts surmise was the
residing place for ancient people in the Xia Dynasty (22-17 B.C.).
</P>
<P>
Researchers have ascertained that the Longshan Culture was
divided into three stages and five periods. Excavations of ruins
at Wangchenggang, near Dengfeng, verified the previous theory and
yielded well over 200 prime samples for extensive experiments.
</P>
<P>
"The fact that various layers at both sites dated to earlier
periods than those at sites for the Erlitou Culture suggest we
might find the origins of the Xia Dynasty," according to Li
Xueqin, director of the Institute of Archeology under the Chinese
Academy of Social Sciences (CASS).
</P>
<P>
The CASS obtained numerous samples containing adequate amounts
of carbon from Yanshi and were thus able to precisely date the
Erlitou sites.
</P>
<P>
They also unearthed the foundation for a three-story palace and
the ruins of the small town built long before larger towns in the
Shang Dynasty. The discovery enabled the researchers to establish a
timetable for the town's construction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980902.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodian King Decides to Hold Five-party Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, September 2 (Xinhua) -- King Norodom Sihanouk
