<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Joins Global Effort in Smashing Child Pornography Ring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Australian police Wednesday
played a key role in smashing an international child pornography
ring, Justice Minister Amanda Vanstone said.
</P>
<P>
Vanstone said Australian police were involved across two states
as part of a worldwide operation, coordinated by the National
Crime Squad of England and Wales, which had dismantled the ring.
</P>
<P>
In one of Australia's biggest law enforcement operations,
police from the states of Western Australia and New South Wales
took part, supported by the Australian Federal Police (AFP) and
Interpol.
</P>
<P>
In all, 15 countries were involved, including Germany, France,
Italy and the United States, with dozens of suspected paedophiles
believed to have been arrested in raids at more than 11 addresses,
including four in Australia.
</P>
<P>
Vanstone said the operation had recovered more than 100,000
indecent images of children.
</P>
<P>
"Crimes against children are amongst the most appalling in any
society and the AFP and the international law enforcement agencies
involved deserve strong praise for their efforts in bringing those
allegedly involved in this child pornography ring to justice," she
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
In London, one of the coordinators of the international police
operation said Australian officials had raided "about four"
properties as part of the worldwide swoop, the Australian
Associated Press (AAP) reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Detective Superintendent John Stewardson, of Britain's National
Crime Squad, said it was unclear at this stage whether anyone had
been producing child pornography in Australia or whether those
targeted had just been exchanging the images.
</P>
<P>
"They've been exchanging it - whether they've been producing it
as well in Australia we don't know at this stage," he told the
AAP.
</P>
<P>
He said it was also unclear whether any children had been
abused in Australia as part of the child porn Internet club, which
operated under the name of Wonderland.
</P>
<P>
Police in the state of West Australia raided two Perth homes as
part of the operation, with two men being interviewed, although no
charges had been laid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
