<BODY>
<HEADLINE> England to Ban Super League Players </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The Football Association (FA)
of England gave a stern warning on Wednesday that England players
whose clubs decide to break away into a European Super League
will be banned from the international game.
</P>
<P>
FA chairman Keith Wiseman's threat comes in the week that
Premier League chairmen meet to discuss the controversial plans.
</P>
<P>
Manchester United, Arsenal and Liverpool have already been
invited by the company behind the Super League plans, Media
Partners, to take part in a new structure outside the remit of FA
and UEFA.
</P>
<P>
Wiseman announced that all players with breakaway clubs would
be excluded from the England set-up, but he insisted the blanket
ban would only be considered in "an extreme situation".
</P>
<P>
He said: "I have every reason to believe the clubs will reach
accommodation with UEFA and the FA over the next couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
"But I think the point is that those seeking the breakaway
have not taken account of is they are talking about playing
unsanctioned football entirely outside the jurisdiction of the
whole football body.
</P>
<P>
"I think it logically follows from that they are not able to
play inside it as well."
</P>
<P>
Wiseman accepted there was an inexorable movement towards more
European games, but believed these can be accommodated within the
existing league arrangements.
</P>
<P>
"I think there will be a European League almost certainly
within the next few years, hopefully from under the structure of
the game and with consultation taking place with the major
leagues.
</P>
<P>
"I think the structure of the game will survive and I think it
is vital that it does. One only has to look at the problems a
sport like rugby union has at the moment to realise how difficult
it can be for everyone if there is no clear structure laid
down." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
