<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Majority of Nepali Population Below Age 14 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Children aged below 14 and
old people aged above 60 account for 41.27 percent and 5.49
percent respectively of the total population of 21.84 million in
Nepal, figures show.
</P>
<P>
Youth aged between 15 and 24 account for 19.15 percent of the
total population, according to figures available at a press
conference held here Wednesday for the United Nations Population
Fund to release the State of World Population 1998.
</P>
<P>
The male population and female population in Nepal stands
respectively at 10.903 million and 10.939 million, of which women
aged 15-49 account for 47.91 percent.
</P>
<P>
The total fertility rate for Nepalese women is 4.43 while child
mortality rate and infant mortality rate in the country were
43/1,000 and 79/1,000 respectively in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Birth not attended by health professionals is as high as 89.9
percent.
</P>
<P>
In Nepal, the adult literacy ratio in 1996 was 36.72 with those
for male and female at 54.32 and 21.33 respectively.
</P>
<P>
Mean age at first marriage here is 17.1.
</P>
<P>
Population density in the Himalayan kingdom is 148.41 per
square kilometer.
</P>
<P>
Releasing the world population report, Henning Karcher,
resident coordinator of the U.N. System's Operational Activities
for Development in Nepal, said that population is growing at an
alarming rate in Nepal.
</P>
<P>
He said that according to the Nepal Human Development Report
1998, population in Nepal doubled between 1961 and 1991, and at
the current growth rate of 2.5 percent, it is expected to reach
the 40 million mark by 2025.
</P>
<P>
"This is indeed a great challenge," he observed. "Not only does
the size of the population pose a serious threat to an already
impoverished state, but an ever-increasing proportion of over-65
population is likely to be a major issue in Nepal, especially in
the context of the virtual absence of satisfactory social security
systems and safety nets." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
