<HEADLINE> DPRK Breaks Silence over Missile Test, Attacking Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK) on Wednesday broke silence over the
missile test-firing by accusing Japan of making provocative
statements against it.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Korean Asia-pacific Peace Committee issued
a statement, urging Japan to stop making a fuss about the
ballistic missile test launch which "Japan says was carried out by
the DPRK."
</P>
<P>
The statement, released by the Korean Central News Agency, did
not mention whether the DPRK had test-fired a ballistic missile on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK reportedly fired a newly developed, two-stage
ballistic missile on Monday that overflew northeastern Japan and
fell into the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Foreign Minister Masahiko Komura told the House of
Representatives Foreign Affairs Committee on Wednesday Pyongyang's
missile firing was not only a serious threat to Japan's security,
but also a grave matter for the security, peace and stability in
Northeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK statement said, "It is imprudent for Japan to say this
or that, unaware of what the DPRK did, a missile test or anything
else."
</P>
<P>
It ridiculed that Japan is "zealously developing long-distance
vehicles and other up-to-date weapons and paving the way for
overseas aggression."
</P>
<P>
"Many countries around Japan possess or have deployed
missile. Japanese politicians, however, hurl mud only at the DPRK
while being unaware of the background," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
It asked Japan to pay for the 40 odd years of its occupation of
Korea and murder of Koreans and warned Japan to "face up to
reality, act with discretion and renounce its anachronistic
hostile policy toward the DPRK." 
</P>
</TEXT>
