holder Jonathan Edwards has admitted defeat in his battle to take
part in the World Cup in Johannesburg next week.
</P>
<P>
And he also decided not to compete again this season, after
failing to shake off an ankle injury.
</P>
<P>
The Briton will lose more than 60,000 pounds (about 100,000
U.S.dollars) for missing Saturday's IAAF Grand Prix final in
Moscow on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
But the newly-crowned European champion, who pulled out of
last Friday's Brussels Golden League meeting when the pain in his
left ankle became unbearable, is determined to have immediate
surgery on the problem.
</P>
<P>
"The selectors were keen for me to jump as they felt it would
make a difference between a maximum eight points or possibly just
one," said Edwards.
</P>
<P>
"But I tried to train and I just couldn't put any weight on my
foot.
</P>
<P>
"I hoped I might get one more competition before the end of
the season. When I got back from Brussels, I felt slightly better.
</P>
<P>
"But this convinced me it is just not possible. It is just not
going to happen that I compete again this year."
</P>
<P>
His absence from Johannesburg follows the withdrawal of
European 200m gold medallist Doug Walker, 400m hopeful Mark
Richardson and 1500m runner John Mayock.
</P>
<P>
Edwards has been replaced in the World Cup squad by reigning
Commonwealth champion Julian Golley. 
