<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu Tuesday proposed a freeze
in wage rises for top government officials.
</P>
<P>
He planned to set a example by forfeiting his upcoming monthly
pay rise of about 1,500 Shekels (about 410 U.S. dollars), and
urged teachers, the Labor Federation and other unions to follow
suit to try and maintain Israel as "an island of stability in the
heart of the international (economic) storm."
</P>
<P>
Haaretz:
</P>
<P>
-- Netanyahu said Tuesday that he regards the burgeoning
Turkish-Israeli military relationship as the basis for a regional
defense structure.
</P>
<P>
Syria, Egypt and Greece are all very sensitive to the subject
of the Turkish-Israeli military relationship, which has been
encouraged by the U.S..
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- Schools were expected to remain closed Wednesday morning
and the Labor Federation is likely to shut down most public
services after their respective talks with the Treasury over wage
rises resulted in no progress.
</P>
<P>
It is easy for Netanyahu to call for a freeze in wage rises for
senior officials but very difficult to implement it. 
</P>
