<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Turns Away Foreign Workers for Local </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Jordan is curtailing jobs for
foreigners so as to see more locals employed, the semi-official
Jordan Times reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Regulations have been adopted to bar guest workers from filling
15 kinds of positions like accountancy, teaching and office work,
Minister of Labor Mohammad Mahdi Farhan was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
In particular, the ministry has recently requested hotels and
other tourism businesses to refrain from employing non-Jordanians.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, job opportunities will be added for Jordanians in
the sectors that deny jobs to quest workers, especially tourism,
Farhan said.
</P>
<P>
By barring non-Jordanians from more occupations, the ministry
intends to make job vacancy and help the unemployed Jordanians
hired, he added.
</P>
<P>
Officials put the unemployment in locals at 100,000, but
independent sources placed it as high as 1.2 million, or 26
percent of the country's total population.
</P>
<P>
There are now 600,000 non-Jordanians working in the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Non-Jordanians find jobs more easily than Jordanians as they
get lower wages and ask no health insurance from employers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980902.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Demands Better Investment Structure in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank (WB) has
suggested Jordan to adjust investment structure and speed up
privatization so as to revive its national economy, said a Jordan
Businessmen Association (JBA) statement obtained here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The suggestion was made by John Page, the WB's chief economist
for the Middle East and North Africa Region, during a
JBA-sponsored meeting on Tuesday in Amman.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian government has to adjust the current investment
structure by directing the investors' priorities towards the
productive sector rather than building houses in order to create
"a balance between commercial and non-commercial investments,"
said Page.
</P>
<P>
A balanced investment structure, plus a healthy ratio of
investment to the gross domestic products (GDP), will contribute
much to reviving Jordan's economy, whose growth rates almost
grounded to zero in the past few years, said Page.
</P>
<P>
He added that Jordan's current ratio of investment to the GDP
stands at 23 to 24 percent, which is "satisfactory" in accordance
with regional standards.
</P>
<P>
The present investment structure in Jordan is not reasonable,
as most investors focus on house-building projects instead of
productive industrial ones due to a natural fear that any
investment in industry might be ruined as a result of the
unstable regional circumstance, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Page said, the Jordanian government needs to speed
up its privatization program in conjunction with the adjustment of
investment structure to revive the economic situation.
</P>
<P>
"Jordan needs to privatize its institutions, which will make
private sector investment more profitable" through fully
implementing the privatization program launched in early 1990s,
he said.
</P>
<P>
It will be beneficial to the government to give the private
sector the opportunity to play "a major role" in the economy,
said Page.
</P>
<P>
Page paid his visit to Jordan, at a time when the Jordanian
government asked the International Monetary Fund (IMF) to extend
for at least one more year the 1989-1999 economic restructuring
program co-sponsored by IMF and WB for the kingdom, in order to
enliven the economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980902.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran to Try German Firms for Exporting Weapons to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Iran announced on Wednesday to
put eight German companies on trial for exporting chemical
weapons to Iraq during the 1980-88 Iran-Iraq war.
</P>
<P>
Director general of Iran's judiciary public relations office
Fotovat Nassiri Savadkouhi said that the German companies would
go on trial in Tehran public court, the official news agency IRNA
reported.
</P>
<P>
Savadkouhi did not mention when the trial would start, but
stated the chemical weapons provided to Iraq by the German
companies caused 10,000 deaths and 50,000 injuries in Iran.
</P>
<P>
Because the crimes were committed in the territory under the
jurisdiction of Iranian judiciary, he said, according to the
international judicial laws, the cases can be taken up in the
Iranian courts.
</P>
<P>
Savadkouhi said so far 600 cases against the German firms have
been submitted to the court and the plaintiffs have asked for
compensation for damages ranging from 500,000 to 1,000,000 German
marks (278,000 to 555,500 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Iranian judicial official said that the eight German
companies provided the Iraqi government with basic material for
production of chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
He named the video-taped confessions of the captured Iraqi
commanders as evidence to confirm the German companies'
involvement in Iraq's chemical weapons program.
</P>
<P>
Various U.N. special commission reports, researches carried out
by Iran's defense and judiciary's civil departments and witnesses'
reports constitute more evidence in the case, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
