<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea Unveils Measures to Revitalize Domestic Demand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 2 (Xinhua) -- South Korea Wednesday announced
a package of monetary and fiscal measures to revitalize its
rapidly cooling domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
Those measures aim to keep the economy from slipping into
deeper recession, said Minister of Finance and Economy Lee Kyu-sung
</P>
<P>
The package includes taking a flexible approach toward money
supply, expanding credit guarantees for small- and medium-sized
enterprises, exporters and housing builders and increasing
consumer financing instruments for buyers of houses and other
durable goods.
</P>
<P>
The package apparently came in response to a mounting fear that
the economy was plunging deeper due to austere measures imposed by
the International Monetary Fund (IMF) last December when the
nation signed an agreement with it for a rescue loan of 58 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to help stimulate the domestic demand, all fiscal
measures will be mobilized at the expense of budget deficits, Lee
said.
</P>
<P>
The first phase of financial sector restructuring will be
completed by the end of September to remove economic uncertainties
which is alleged putting immense pressures on consumer sentiment,
he added.
</P>
<P>
Analysts attributed the slumping domestic demand to mass
layoffs and pay cuts.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the central Bank of Korea said the country's gross
domestic product (GDP) declined 6.6 percent in the second quarter
of this year, its worst performance in the past 18 years. The drop
followed a 3.9 percent contraction in the first quarter of this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
