<HEADLINE> Japan's New Party Sakigake to Be Virtually Dissolved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Japan's New Party Sakigake on
Wednesday announced that it will be virtually dissolved after the
current extraordinary Diet (parliament) session ends in early
October.
</P>
<P>
The party's leader, House of Representatives member Masayoshi
Takemura, and four other party members issued a statement at a
press conference, saying that the party will continue to legally
exist and simply be called "Sakigake."
</P>
<P>
Each party member will be free to join the renamed party, but
Takemura said only he and House of Councillors member Tenzo
Okumura will remain.
</P>
<P>
Three others of the party's five Diet members will become
independents.
</P>
<P>
Sakigake failed to gain a seat in the July 12 House of
Councillors (upper house) election, and many former Diet members,
fearing that they would not be able to win back their seats in the
next lower house election, called for the dissolution.
</P>
<P>
The New Party Sakigake was established in June 1993 by 10 Diet
members, mainly young former Liberal Democratic Party (LDP)
members, and had 27 Diet members in its heyday.
</P>
<P>
The party ended its four-year coalition with the ruling LDP
before the July upper house election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
