<HEADLINE> Indonesian Gov't Sets Up Crisis Center in Welfare Field </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government has
established a crisis center in the fields of people's welfare and
poverty eradication, an assistant to Coordinating Minister for
People's Welfare Sudjono told Antara News Agency Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The center was equipped with a computer network accessible from
every sub-district administration office in the country to keep
the public at large abreast of developments in both fields in
macro terms and about implementation of the government's social
welfare and poverty eradication programs.
</P>
<P>
He said that an important benefit of the system was that it
would enable the prevention of duplications or overlapping of
government activities in the distribution of basic necessaries,
scholarships and work capital among poor families.
</P>
<P>
Soedarmadi, secretary to the coordinating minister for people's
welfare and poverty eradication, told reporters that the number of
poor families in Indonesia had increased from 16.9 million in June
to 17.3 million in August this year.
</P>
<P>
Since last August, he said, the government had been subsidizing
a program to provide rice to 7.3 million poor families.
</P>
<P>
In another effort to fight poverty, the government had been
offering work capital assistance called Business Partnership
Development Credit of 50 million rupiah (5,000 U.S. dollars) at 12
percent interest per annum per package to poor families deemed
qualified to run a business in partnership with a cooperative or
medium-scale enterprise.
</P>
<P>
The government had set aside some 250 billion rupiah (25
million U.S. dollars) to back up the Business Partnership
Development Credit scheme nation-wide, but so far only 25 percent
of the amount had been spent for the purpose, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
