<HEADLINE> IOC Head Meets FIFA President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 2 (Xinhua) -- IOC president Juan Antonio
Samaranch met FIFA president Joseph Blatter for a working session
at the Olympic House in Lausanne, Switzerland, said an IOC press
release reaching here tonight.
</P>
<P>
The two world sports heads agreed on Monday evening to meet
regularly at presidential level and also expressed the wish to
strengthen contacts between the executive boards of their two
organizations.
</P>
<P>
The new FIFA president wants to see football given greater
prominence in the framework of the Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
For the 2000 Games in Sydney, all the arrangements have
already been made, but the file concerning the age limit on
players taking part (under 23) may be reopened.
</P>
<P>
At present, each team taking part in the Olympic men's
football tournament is allowed to include three players aged over
23, and this figure could be increased to five, the press release
said.
</P>
<P>
The fact remain that, to ensure that top players take part in
the Olympic football tournament, the competition dates are an
essential issue.
</P>
<P>
Lastly, for the Olympic Games in 2004, with a view to
improving the quality of play, among other things, there are
plans to increase the number of women's teams from eight to 12.
</P>
<P>
A study will be undertaken to examine how the Football
Arbitration Tribunal (TAF) could make use of the synergies of the
Court of Arbitration for Sports (CAS) while ensuring that the TAF
retains its independence.
</P>
<P>
On the subject of doping, FIFA supports the efforts of the
international sports community, and the IOC in particular, in
combating this scourge. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
