<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea's External Debts Slightly Down in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 2 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's total external
debts stood at 152.2 billion U.S. dollars in July, down 1.52
billion dollars from the previous month, the Ministry of Finance
and Economy said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The ministry attributed the decline largely to net payments of
mid- and long-term debt by financial institutions, which amounted
to 1.8 billion dollars in July.
</P>
<P>
The long-term debt went down slightly, from 11.54 billion
dollars in June to 11.39 billion dollars in July, representing
74.8 percent of the total foreign debts.
</P>
<P>
However, short-term debt with maturities of less than one year
edged up from 38.31 billion dollars in June to 38.35 billion
dollars in July, accounting for 25.2 percent of the total foreign
debts.
</P>
<P>
Foreign debts, especially the short-term ones, were one of the
key factors that dragged South Korea into the financial crisis
late last year, forcing it to borrow 57 billion dollars from the
International Monetary Fund last December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
