<HEADLINE> Localization of Civil Servants in Macao Makes New Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Lai Ieng Kit formally resumed office
here on Wednesday as director of the Identification Department of the
Macao government, indicating that the localization of civil servants
has scored new progress in Macao.
</P>
<P>
Lai, 41, began to work in the department in 1987 and served as its
deputy director for three years.
</P>
<P>
At the inaugural ceremony, the new director said that he would
strive to enhance contact between the department and Macao residents
and raise its efficiency.
</P>
<P>
In the transitional period of Macao, the department has some new
tasks, such as preparing for the issue of passports and travel
certificates in the future Macao Special Administrative Region (SAR)
and offering suggestions to the Macao SAR Preparatory Committee on the
definition of permanent Macao resident and permanent residence right,
he said.
</P>
<P>
On August 27, 42-year-old Chinese Ao Man Long resumed office as
director of the Macao Incineration and Sewage Treatment Office. And in
last November Fatima Choi became the first Chinese who was appointed
as department director in the Macao government.
</P>
<P>
Although the number of medium- and high-level officials in the
Macao government increased markedly this year, only three out of 59
officials at the level of department director are Chinese up to now.
</P>
<P>
In addition, 23 Chinese act as deputy department directors, who
make up 46 percent of all those at such posts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
