<HEADLINE> Malaysian Deputy Prime Minister Sacked </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Deputy Prime
Minister and Finance Minister Anwar Ibrahim was sacked with effect
from 5.30 p.m. Wednesday, the Prime Minister's Department
announced Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
The department said in a short statement issued late Wednesday
evening that the Yang di-Pertuan Agong (the Supreme Head of State
or the King) has been informed of Anwar's removal from the
Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
The statement said Anwar has also been removed from all other
positions held by him in his capacity as deputy prime minister and
minister of finance.
</P>
<P>
The letter of his sacking was believed to have been delivered
to Anwar at his house by a top government official at about 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
The statement did not give the reason why Anwar was sacked.
</P>
<P>
No immediate response could be obtained from Anwar who is also
deputy president of the United Malays National Organization (UMNO)
headed by Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad.
</P>
<P>
Anwar, 51, was appointed deputy prime minister on December 1,
1993, succeeding Tun Ghafar Baba, and has been assigned as the
successor of Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad who came to power in
1981. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980902.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton, Yeltsin Conclude Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The presidents of Russia and
the United States concluded their second round of meeting
Wednesday in what was described as "a very friendly atmosphere."
</P>
<P>
Aside from reiteration of strong support from Washington,
U.S. President Bill Clinton didn't offer any specific financial or
economic assistance to Russia, which was grappling with a
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
He said the West stands ready to provide financial help so
long as Russia stays on its chosen course embarked seven years
ago.
</P>
<P>
Russian President Boris Yeltsin, for his part, said his nation
has "a lot of tears and sweat" to expend on its struggle forward.
</P>
<P>
"There still is a lot of tears and sweat to spend before we
identify the forms of business cooperation which are worthy of the
two great nations," Yeltsin told a joint press conference.
</P>
<P>
Prior to that, the two presidents signed two security
agreements. One commits each country to ridding itself of 50 tons
of weapons-grade plutonium from old nuclear warheads. The other
calls for sharing information on missile launch warnings.
</P>
<P>
They also signed joint statements on control of biological
weapons and on the situation in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
While asserting "there were no differences" at the bilateral
front, Yeltsin blasted the use of force by Washington in
international affairs.
</P>
<P>
"Russia rejects in principle the use of force," Yeltsin
said. "There can be no military solutions to today's
conflicts. Whether it's Kosovo, the situation over Iraq,
Afghanistan or others."
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the U.S. bombing of the suspected terrorist sites
in Afghanistan and Sudan in August, Yeltsin said he was "outraged"
by the U.S. decision.
</P>
<P>
He also repeated his opposition to what he called "NATO
centrism," or the central military role the U.S.-led North
Atlantic Treaty Organization plays in Europe and beyond.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, who arrived here Tuesday morning, came at a
difficult time for Russia, which is confronting a full-blown
financial crisis and without a fully functioning government.
</P>
<P>
The State Duma, or lower house of parliament, on Monday
overwhelmingly rejected Yeltsin's nominee for premiership, Viktor
Chernomyrdin, in the first round of voting.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin has renominated Chernomyrdin, but the
opposition-dominated Duma will most likely shoot down the
nomination in the second round of balloting scheduled for Friday,
prolonging the country's political stand-off.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin was appointed acting prime minister August 24
when Yeltsin abruptly fired the four-month-old cabinet of Sergei
Kiriyenko, after an effective devaluation of the ruble and a de
facto default on Russia's foreign debts sent prices rocketing and
securities diving to record lows.
</P>
<P>
Later Wednesday, Clinton was scheduled to meet with other major
political players, including speakers of both houses of
parliament, Moscow mayor Yuri Luzhkov, Krasnoyarsk region governor
Alexander Lebed, Communist leader Gennady Zyuganov, Our Home is
Russia leader Alexander Shokin and Grigory Yavlinsky of Yabolo.
</P>
<P>
As Clinton and Yeltsin held their second round of talks at the
Kremlin, Communist leader Zyuganov bluntly summed up the high
stakes in this country's internal power struggle: "President
Yeltsin is pushing the nation to a civil war."
</P>
<P>
Under the Russian constitution, if the Duma blocks the
premier's nomination three times, the president will have to
select a new nominee or dissolve the lower chamber.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin has insisted he would not give up on democratic
reforms or on his appointment of Victor Chernomyrdin to return as
prime minister.
</P>
<P>
"The past two years in Russia's life have been full of stormy
political events, great laborious work on reforming the economy,"
Yeltsin said in dinner remarks Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Soon there were disappointments, too, and unfulfilled
hopes. But we've never lost the conviction in the necessity of
the transformations we're carrying out." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
