<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hosts Field Best Paddlers in Chinese GP, World Top Two Skip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By Sportswriter Wang Zijiang
</P>
<P>
JI'NAN, Shandong Province, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Olympic
champion Liu Guoliang and former world champion Kong Linghui will
anchor the Chinese team in the China Grand Prix table tennis
tournament to be started here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
However, world top two players, Vladimir Samsonov of Belarus
and Zoran Primorac of Croatia, will be absent from the four-day
meet.
</P>
<P>
Kong and Liu, who finished 1-2 in the men's singles and paired
up to win the doubles at the Australian Open last week, are
favored to lift the two titles again in the tournament which was
inaugurated in 1988.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Grand Prix has always been regarded as a home show
for the hosts paddlers rather than an international tourney
because only three titles were won by non-Chinese players since
1992.
</P>
<P>
World number five Liu, who shot to fame in the 1992 edition
after stunning all-time great Jan-ove Waldner of Sweden, was
expected to display brilliant performance in his favorite
tournament, which features men's and women's singles and doubles
events.
</P>
<P>
Waldner, the world's only male player who has won a grand slam
of the Olympic, World Cup and World Championships titles, did not
enter the tournament after flopping to world No. 40 Peter Fraz of
Germany in the second round of the Australian Open.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Grand Prix has always been Waldner's Waterloo. The
32-year-old Swede played twice in 1992 and 1993, but was
eliminated twice by unknown Chinese youngesters at the early
stages -- the first time losing to Liu and the second to Feng Zhe.
</P>
<P>
Representing Sweden this time are veterans Jorgen Persson,
Peter Karlsson and Fredrik Hakansson.
</P>
<P>
Persson, a main force of the Sweden's winning team in three
successive World Championships from 1989 to 1993 and world
singles champion in 1991, did not want to reveal why his
long-time teammate Waldner failed to play the Grand Prix.
</P>
<P>
"We come here directly from Australia," Persson said, "I don't
know why he has hasn't come."
</P>
<P>
Biro Cheav, head coach of France, said Waldner might have
flown home to ready himself for the European Masters
Championships in Germany next month since there is little hope to
overcome the Chinese players.
</P>
<P>
With the absence of Samsonov, defending champion Primorac and
Waldner, the 1995 world champion Jean-Phillippe Gatien was
expected to pose the Chinese the toughest tests though his coach
Cheav maintained a low profile.
</P>
<P>
"He is too old and has injuries around," Cheav said, "To reach
semifinals is not bad."
</P>
<P>
With three months to go before the 13th Asian Games in
Bangkok, Thailand, both China and its traditional Asian rival
South
Korea take this gathering as a warm-up for the more important
quadrennial Asian Games slated for December this year.
</P>
<P>
"The Asian Games is the most important for all of us," said
South Korea's head coach Lee Sang Kook, "The Chinese Grand Prix
is just a training ground for us. And I hope Kim Taek Soo will
reach the final."
</P>
<P>
The world No. 11 Kim, a lost finalist at the Australian Open
to Chinese Kong, said he was no match with the strong Chinese
counterparts.
</P>
<P>
"Kong has made a great improvement since last year," Kim said,
"His backhand, speed, topspin, all have been improved. He has a
better chance if we meet again in the final. And China has a lot
of promising young stars, so the gap between us is getting wider
and wider."
</P>
<P>
The women's competition will undoutedly be China's dominance
since the Chinese women have never let a single major
international title slip off their hands in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
The hosts will field all its best female players for the
tournament, also a major warm-up for the 45th World Championships
in Belgrade, Yugoslavia, from April 26 to May 9, 1999. They
include world No. 2 Li Ju, No. 3 Wang Nan and No. 4 Wang Chen.
</P>
<P>
Deng Yaping, who has been world No. 1 for six years, will not
play as she is studying in Qinghua University.
</P>
<P>
The 61,000 US dollars event, to run until Sunday, has
attracted 140 players from 25 countries and regions, all of them
inside the 100 rankings.
</P>
<P>
Winner of the men's singles event will get a prize money of
10,000 while the woman champion takes 8,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
