<HEADLINE> CPPCC Chairman Meets Lions Clubs International Delegation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Li Ruihuan, chairman of the
National Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference (CPPCC), met here today with a Lions Clubs International
(LCI) delegation led by Kajit Habanananda, LCI's president.
</P>
<P>
This charitable organization donated 15 million U.S. dollars to
China last year for Sightfirst China Action, the world's largest
joint program to combat blindness. The purpose of the program is
to finance 1.75 million cataract-removal operations,
organize 250 medical teams for remote and poor areas, and
recruit 11,000 eye doctors for hospitals at the county level in
China between 1997 and 2001.
</P>
<P>
Li Ruihuan, who is also honorary president of the the Chinese
Association for the Disabled (CAD), extended his personal
congratulations to Habanananda, LCI's first Asian president, and
expressed gratitude for LCI's support and assistance to disabled
Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
He said he hopes the two sides will ensure the success of
Sightfirst China Action by joint efforts and further cooperation
with other departments, with the program as a starting point.
</P>
<P>
Habanananda told Li that LCI has already formed good ties with
CAD and China's Ministry of Health. LCI has successfully carried
out operation Sightfirst China Action and is willing to establish
long-term partnerships with other departments, he said.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, LCI District 303 of Hong Kong and Macao
donated 250,000 U.S. dollars to China's flood-stricken areas for
post-flood reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
Habanananda and his party are visiting China at the invitation
of both the Ministry of Health and CAD to inspect the progress of
Sightfirst China Action. 
</P>
</TEXT>
