<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Files Formal Request to WTO on EC's Anti- </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The Pakistani government
filed a formal request with the World Trade Organization (WTO) for
consultation on anti-dumping duties imposed by the European
Commission (EC) on imports of unbleached cotton, the official
Associated Press of Pakistan (APP) said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Although Pakistan has filed the request about 10 days back, it
will take not less than 60 days for the WTO to arrange a
consultation of the counterparts in Geneva, textile industry
sources were quoted as saying by APP.
</P>
<P>
"The WTO will set up a panel of dispute settlement body if
talks fail," said the sources.
</P>
<P>
The EC had imposed definitive duties last month on unbleached
cotton fabric (grey cloth) of Pakistan, Indonesia, India, Egypt
and China. Duties imposed on Pakistan are lowest (9.5 percent) as
compared to other countries.
</P>
<P>
According to the textile industry sources, Pakistan's annual
exports of bleached, un-bleached and semi-bleached cotton fabrics
amount to 106 million U.S. dollars annually.
</P>
<P>
These definitive anti-dumping duties could be a permanent
feature if approved by the EC's Advisory Council which will hold a
meeting in this regard shortly in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan had initially entered into a price undertaking
discussion with the EC. However, not having been able to arrive at
a satisfactory arrangement, Pakistan discontinued these discussion
like India.
</P>
<P>
"On the advice of Ministry of Commerce, the discussions were
dropped by All Pakistan Textile Mills Association (APTMA)," the
industry sources added.
</P>
<P>
Chief Executive APMTA, Khalid Amin said Wednesday, Pakistan had
options to plead the case of anti-dumping duties jointly with
India, but Pakistan opted to fight the case alone.
</P>
<P>
He said that in any case, Pakistan's textile industry has to
face stiff competition in Europe which is the largest consumer of
textile product of the world.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan has negligible textile exports to Europe currently as
compared to other countries of the world, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
