<HEADLINE> HKU Professor Encourages Students To Be Optimistic Before Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Professor Y.C. Cheng,
vice-chancellor of the Hong Kong University (HKU), here Wednesday
encouraged his students to remain optimistic in the face of Asia's
economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Speaking during his welcoming address to new students, Cheng
stressed: "My message to you is -- and I hope you will take my
words to heart -- do not feel pessimistic or disheartened."
</P>
<P>
He called on the students to Look on the positive side. "While
all seems to be doom and gloom at the moment we can take heart
from the knowledge that this is only a temporary setback for us
and our city," he said.
</P>
<P>
Cheng said that Hong Kong has weathered many storms in the past
and it can and will weather this one.
</P>
<P>
"It is through suffering that individual human beings become
better and stronger; so it is with our city," he added.
</P>
<P>
Explaining reasons for his confidence, Cheng said that he based
his confidence in the future on two undeniable assets which will
help Hong Kong through our present crisis -- Hong Kong's special
relationship with China's mainland and Hong Kong's advantage of
human resources.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is not only part of China, it is also the gateway to
this prospering hinterland, Cheng said.
</P>
<P>
"We will take full advantage of this, making full use of
China's resources and striving to be of service to the mainland,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's greatest resource is its people, Cheng said. "This
human capital -- if developed and nurtured carefully and with
vision -- will be a sure source of our resurgence," he added.
</P>
<P>
Cheng encouraged the students to make full use of their time in
 the HKU as the university has reformed the curriculum this
year. The new curriculum is more flexible and broadened and will
help students prepare for flexibility and adaptation in later
life. 
</P>
</TEXT>
