<HEADLINE> Asia's Advertising Exhibition Opens in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 2 (Xinhua) -- MarComAsia'98, an exhibition
 reflecting the achievements of the developing media and promoting
 the exchange of ideas on advertising, opened here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This is the region's first multi-faceted event organized by the
 Hong Kong Trade Development council for the dynamic industries of
 advertising, marketing and communications.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 exhibitors from the region including about 60
from the Chinese mainland such as the Xinhua News Agency and the
China Central Television (CCTV) as well as national or regional
newspapers, magazines, radios and television stations participated
 in the exhibition.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony of the exhibition, Michael
Sze, executive director of the Hong Kong Trade Development
Council, said that one of the main features of MarComAsia'98 will
be the China Media Pavilion organized by Wen Wei Po, a major
Chinese language newspaper in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Another feature of the fair is the MarComAsia'98 conference
where industry experts will share their views on the industry
trends, challenges and opportunities in Asia, he said.
</P>
<P>
Philip Wong, vice-chairman of the Chinese General Chamber of
Commerce, noted that advertising is one of the fastest-growing
service industries in Hong Kong, with expenditures increasing in
1997 by 20 percent to more than 20.4 billion HK dollars (2.61
billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong also ranks the third in the world in terms of per
capita advertising expenditures and provides professional
advertising services and marketing support to the entire
Asia-Pacific, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said there are two great trends occurring right now that
define the advertising and marketing industry in the Asia-Pacific.
</P>
<P>
The first is the economic downturn affecting the region. The
second is the great opportunity represented by the Chinese market,
 he said.
</P>
<P>
The amount of money spent on advertising last year in the
Chinese mainland soared by 53 percent to more than 30.5 billion
RMB (3.8 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Wong quoted analysts as predicting that the mainland will
become the world's fourth largest advertising market in terms of
revenue by as early as 2003.
</P>
<P>
After the opening ceremony, Zhang Guoliang, leader of the
Xinhua News Agency delegation and Editor-in-Chief of the Xinhua
News Agency Hong Kong Branch, told local reporters: "This is our
largest exhibition in Hong Kong, which fully shows that the Xinhua
 News Agency attaches great importance to the MarComAsia'98."
</P>
<P>
Zhang said Xinhua releases various new stories and economic
information to China and other parts of the world around the clock
 everyday in seven languages in addition to more than 100 photo
negatives, totaling more than 1.5 million words. It also edits and
 publishes some 40 kinds of newspapers and periodicals.
</P>
<P>
"Our specially designed pavilion will give visitors an overall
image of Xinhua's development and reform for many years,
especially after China implemented the policy of reform and
opening to the outside world," he said.
</P>
<P>
Tan Xisong, director of Advertisement Economy and Information
Programs Center of the CCTV, said that she was very glad to note
that the opening of the exhibition coincided with the 40th
anniversary of the founding of the CCTV.
</P>
<P>
Through the exhibition, the CCTV will brief overseas audiences
on its eight channels, broadcasting 138 hours of programs daily
and on its advertising operation as well.
</P>
<P>
Many local exhibitors expressed the belief that the exhibition
will provide them a unique opportunity to meet their strategic
partners in expanding their business.
</P>
<P>
A conference and a seminar will also be held during the
three-day exhibition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
