<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Protection of Taiwan Investment Not Affected: Article </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 2 (Xinhua) -- An article in the September
issue of "Relations Across the Taiwan Straits" magazine says that
criminal deeds perpetrated by a small number of Taiwanese
businessmen will not affect the policy adopted by the Chinese
mainland to protect the legal rights and interests of the Taiwan
residents.
</P>
<P>
The article titled "Punish Taiwan Espionage Activities and
Protect Taiwan Investment" says that all sorts of unwise
commentaries and rumors involving the recent Taiwanese espionage
case should be put to a final end.
</P>
<P>
On August 13, 1998, the Beijing Municipal No.1 Intermediate
People's Court made a ruling of first instance in the case of four
Taiwanese who were found to be working for the Taiwan Military
Intelligence Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Municipal Higher People's Court Tuesday made the
decision to uphold the original judgement on the four Taiwanese
charged with espionage.
</P>
<P>
Kou Jianming was sentenced to four years imprisonment and
deprived of political rights for two years. The other three --
Chen Shaoyu, Han Yueting and Zhou Changming -- were also
identified as having engaged in the crime of espionage, but were
exempted from criminal punishment because they had performed
meritorious deeds.
</P>
<P>
The four frequently came to the Chinese mainland between June
1993 and March 1998, under the cover of the China Cross-Strait
Non-Governmental Exchange Association (CANEA), but they were
actually sent by Taiwan military intelligence Bureau to collect
political, economic, and military information.
</P>
<P>
These criminal activities were backed up by strong evidence and
were confessed to by the four themselves, the article says.
</P>
<P>
Although they called themselves businessmen, they were spies in
disguise. The third article of the Law on protecting investments
of Taiwan compatriots stipulates clearly that China must protect
Taiwan compatriots' investments in accordance with the law.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Taiwan compatriots must make investments in
accord with the country's laws and regulations.
</P>
<P>
People will be able to judge the case fairly if they
comprehensively and accurately understand these two-tiered
connotations of the law. It would be very unwise for anyone to
find an overly political meaning in this case, or mount pressure
on the other side.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980902.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fairly Strong Earthquake Hits Southern Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- A fairly strong earthquake with
a magnitude of 7.3 on the Richter Scale rocked the southern
Philippine island of Mindanao late Wednesday afternoon, the
seismology authorities said.
</P>
<P>
The epicenter of the quake, which struck at 4:38 p.m. local
time, was shallow under the sea, 140 kilometers southeast of Mati
city, Davao Oriental province, the Philippine Institute of
Volcanology and Seismology said in a bulletin.
</P>
<P>
The institute said it was not expecting any damage caused by
the tremor which was of tectonic origin. But it said some
aftershocks may follow.
</P>
<P>
There were no reports on damages, casualties or tsunami
resulting from the movement, according to the institute.
</P>
<P>
The earthquake was the second to hit the Philippines within two
days.
</P>
<P>
A moderate quake measuring 4.3 on the Richter Scale shook Metro
Manila and its nearby provinces.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines is located at what is known as the Pacific
"Ring of Fire" where powerful earthquakes and volcanic eruptions
are common. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
