<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State of World Population 1998 Released in Kathmandu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 2 (Xinhua) -- It will be a serious
challenge
to meet the increasing needs of both the young and the elderly in
the coming decades, the State of World Population 1998 released
here Wednesday cautioned.
</P>
<P>
The report was released by the United Nations Population Fund
under the theme of "the new generations."
</P>
<P>
It said that over one billion people aged between 15 and 24 are
entering their childbearing and working years, and at the same
time, the number and proportions of people aged above 65 are
increasing at an unprecedented rate.
</P>
<P>
The rapid growth of young and old "new generations" is
challenging societies' ability to provide education and health
care for the young, and social, medical and financial support for
the elderly, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It noted that today's largest-ever young generation will swell
the working-age population in many countries over the next two
decades. And if they find productive work, there will be a
one-time demographic bonus for development.
</P>
<P>
However, more than one billion jobs will need to be created to
accommodate these new workers and reduce unemployment, which
cannot be achieved without lowering birth rates and expanding
education programs, the report warned.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of the elderly, it projected that in the next 50
years, the proportion of people over age 65 will more than double,
which will severely test the ability of families and society to
provide with them the financial, medical and social support.
</P>
<P>
And even worse, there will be fewer children to support the
elderly parents in the next generation, calling for more formal
and informal support systems for the elderly, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It stated that thanks to unprecedented efforts over the last 30
years, the momentum of population growth has slowed, is slowing
and could slow still further in the coming decades.
</P>
<P>
But at the same time, the world population is still growing at
over 80 million a year, and will continue to grow at or near this
level for the next decade, so the population will only gradually
fall from this level, the report observed.
</P>
<P>
It said that the world population, 3 billion in 1960 and 5
billion in 1987, will pass 6 billion in mid-1999 and most likely
9.4 billion by 2050.
</P>
<P>
"Solutions lie in raising the age at first pregnancy and in
limitation of family size by enabling couples and individuals to
choose the size and spacing of their families," noted Henning
Karcher, resident coordinator of the U.N. System's Operational
Activities for Development in Nepal.
</P>
<P>
Women are having half as many children as their mothers'
generation, because they have more choices in education, marriage
and employment as well as in family size and spacing.
</P>
<P>
Extending these choices to all women will further slow them
momentum of population growth, the report stressed.
</P>
<P>
Releasing the report at a press conference, Karcher said,
according to the Nepal Human Development Report 1998, population
in Nepal, which stands at 21.8 million, doubled between 1961 and
1991, and at the current growth rate of 2.5 percent, it is
expected to reach the 40 million mark by 2025.
</P>
<P>
"This is indeed a great challenge," he said. "Not only does the
size of the population pose a serious threat to already
impoverished state, but an ever-increasing proportion of over-65
population is likely to be a major issue in Nepal, especially in
the context of the virtual absence of satisfactory social security
systems and safety nets." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980902.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Considers New Security Steps After DPRK Missile Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Japan has begun to consider
taking new security measures after the Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK) test fired a ballistic missile on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Foreign Minister Masahiko Komura told the House of
Representatives Foreign Affairs Committee on Wednesday Pyongyang's
missile firing was not only a serious threat to Japan's security,
but also a grave matter for the security, peace and stability in
Northeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK reportedly fired a newly developed, two-stage
ballistic missile on Monday that overflew northeastern Japan and
fell into the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
As measures to defend Japan from a possible missile attack,
Komura said he thinks "it is worth considering the promotion" of a
U.S.-proposed air defense system against ballistic missiles, known
as the theater missile defense (TMD) system.
</P>
<P>
Komura stressed Japan will take concerted steps with South
Korea and the United States to deal with the DPRK's development of
ballistic missiles.
</P>
<P>
"I want to deal with the problem in a way of letting Pyongyang
know it would not make any gains from the missile firing, but
rather it would suffer by conducting an internationally
unforgivable act," Komura said.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Chief Cabinet Secretary Hiromu Nonaka
told a news briefing that Japan is considering introducing an
intelligence satellite to cope swiftly and appropriately with a
"crisis" such as Monday's missile incident.
</P>
<P>
He said the incident showed Japan cannot get a grasp of
up-to-the-minute information over its territory through its own
satellites.
</P>
<P>
Calling an intelligence satellite "indispensable in view of
Japan's security," the top government spokesman said the
government would seek intense discussion on the issue and
conclusion on ways to get a satellite capable of transmitting
images to Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
