<DOCNO> XIE19980902.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inflation Up in Crisis-Hit Asian Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Inflation has been on the rise
in Asian countries hard hit by the regional financial crisis,
South Asia Monitor and China and North Asia Monitor said in a
report available here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The two groups have monitored the overall inflation of Asian
countries -- Thailand, Malaysia, the Philippines, Indonesia,
Singapore, South Korea and Japan since the crisis erupted in July
last year, and will continue to do so through the end of this
year.
</P>
<P>
The report said Indonesia's Consumer Price Index (CPI) will hit
the highest record of 23.4 percent in the region, followed by
Thailand where the CPI will rise to 10.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
South Korea and the Philippines will stay at the same rate of 8
percent, while the Philippines has changed the base year to
calculate CPI from 1988 to 1994 in order to cope with real costs.
</P>
<P>
Japan will be the best of all with a CPI of 0.7 percent. The
CPI of Singapore and Malaysia will be better than other members of
the Association of Southeast Asian Countries (ASEAN), at 3.5
percent and 3.9 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
The float of the Thai baht on July 2, 1997 and its subsequent
depreciation triggered a regional financial crisis which rocketed
the inflation rate in the countries concerned from levels seen in
the first half of 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
