<HEADLINE> HK Stocks Soar 4 percent Following Wall Street Gains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The key Hang Seng Index soared 293.20 points, or 4.15 percent,
to close at 7,355.67, after losing 2.9 percent in the previous
trading day.
</P>
<P>
Institutions that had short-sold blue chips in recent sessions
were seen buying heavily in the market to square out their
positions, said brokers.
</P>
<P>
Turnover amounted to 5,803 million HK dollars (744 million U.S.
dollars), down from the previous day's 6,205 million HK dollars
(796 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Following an overnight rally on Wall Street, the market opened
strongly with the key index gaining 317.63 points, or 4.5 percent,
at the finish of the morning session.
</P>
<P>
The gains were made as the Hong Kong government signaled its
continued determination to clamp down on speculators.
</P>
<P>
The Stock Exchange of Hong Kong said in a statement that it had
temporarily suspended the short-selling of three blue-chip shares
-- HSBC Holdings Plc., Hong Kong Telecommunications Ltd. and China
Telecom (Hong Kong) Ltd. with effect from Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Stock Exchange said: "The decision was taken after
settlement failures were reported by the Hong Kong Securities
Clearing Company on August 31 and September 1 for some
transactions in the three securities conducted on August 27 and
28."
</P>
<P>
The transactions had failed to meet the T+2 settlement
requirements "mainly due to the heavy selling on August 27 and
28," said the exchange.
</P>
<P>
As of September 1 unsettled short transactions involving the
three securities totaled 7.5 billion HK dollars (962 million U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
In order to maintain a fair and orderly market and manage the
settlement risk, the suspension will remain in force until
settlement backlogs of these shares are cleared, said the Stock
Exchange. 
</P>
</TEXT>
