<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korean Banks' Bad Loans Rise to 8.3 Billion Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The bad loans held by South
Korea's 22 banks totaled 10.8 trillion won (some 8.3 billion
U.S. dollars ) in June this year, up 21 percent from the 8.9
trillion won registered in 1997, the Banking Supervisory Authority
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The percentage of bad loans rose from the 2.5 percent of the
total credit registered at the end of 1997 to 3.2 percent at the
end of June this year.
</P>
<P>
A key reason behind the rise of banks' bad loans was a series
of corporate bankruptcies, involving 55 companies which faced exit
orders from the Financial Supervisory Commission in the second
quarter, a spokesman for the authority said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, non-performing loans, which add substandard loans to
bad loans, came to 29 trillion won in June, up 36.4 percent from
the 21.3 trillion won of last year.
</P>
<P>
The percentage of non-performing loans also snowballed from 5.8
percent of the total credit marked in 1997 to 8.6 percent in June
this year.
</P>
<P>
Out of the total bad loans, 14 commercial banks accounted for
8.6 trillion won in June, up from last year's 7.1 trillion won
while bad loans held by eight provincial-based banks went up from
1.8 trillion won to 2.2 trillion won.
</P>
<P>
Korea First Bank topped the list of bad loans with 1.5 trillion
won at the end of June, followed by Cho Hung Bank with 1.4
trillion won, Seoul Bank one trillion won, Korea Exchange Bank
864.9 billion won, and Hanil Bank 819.2 billion won.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's current financial crisis was caused by corporate
failures and bad loans of financial institutions late last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980902.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India to Become World's Most Populous Country in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 2 (Xinhua) -- India, with a higher birth
rate, would overtake China as the most populous country in the
world by 2050, United Nations Population Fund (UNPFA) said in its
latest report on the state of world population.
</P>
<P>
world population would pass 6 billion mark next year and its
size in the next decade would depend on the policies and efforts
of the developing countries like India, which contribute 90
percent of its current growth, UNPFA representative Wasim Zaman
said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Some 80 million people are being added to the world population
each year and India contributes about one-fifth of the growth,
zaman said while releasing the World Population Report for the
year 1998.
</P>
<P>
With approximately 30 people born every minute and 43,000 each
day on an average, India's population of over 980 million is
projected to reach 1,264 million by the year 2016, thus surpassing
China's present population of 1.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
With only 2.4 percent of the land area but 16 percent of the
population in the world, this mass of humanity in the South Asia
country has kept putting increasing pressure on its
infrastructure, economy, environment, education, primary health
care and nutrition.
</P>
<P>
India's population went up to 846 million in 1991 from 345
million at the time of independence in 1947 despite the fact that
the country formulated an official population policy as early as
in 1952.
</P>
<P>
With the growth of population, the UNFPA report said the world
will witness rapid growth of two generations -- of elderly persons
and young adolescents -- which will challenge societies' ability
to provide medical, social and financial care to them.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the efforts of the past 30 years, the report said,
the momentum of global population growth is slowing down.
</P>
<P>
But, it added, past high fertility rates have led to current
rapid increase in numbers, resulting in the largest ever
generation of young people in every continent except Europe,
totaling 1.05 billion between the ages of 15 and 24.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, older populations are expanding "at an
unprecedented rate" in both developed and developing countries due
to improved health care that has increased longevity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980902.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Largest NGO Distributes Micro-Credit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's largest
non-government organization has so far distributed nearly 10.56
billion taka (about 224.7 million U.S. dollars) as micro-credit
among the poor people in the country to help them engaged in
various activities upto June this year, an English daily reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Association for Social Advancement (ASA) disbursed the
money under a savings and credit program among its 14 million
members all over the country with the aim of making the poor
self-reliant economically as well as of attaining a respective
social standards, The Bangladesh Observer quoted an ASA official
as saying.
</P>
<P>
The 14 million members of ASA village organizations are engaged
in multi-dimensional development program in income generating
activities like rice husking, home-stead gardening, poultry,
livestock, vegetable growing, fish farming, small trade,
sericulture, etc, with many of them involving in non-traditional
activities like restaurants and grocery shops, he stated.
</P>
<P>
At present, the members' total savings stand at 835.5 million
taka (about 17.78 million U.S. dollars), he added.
</P>
<P>
The ASA has already extended it's program upto 13,172 villages
in 61 of the country's 64 districts.
</P>
<P>
According to impact assessment of the ASA, about 50 percent
borrowers are able to increase their income by 20 to 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
The ASA disbursed loans of 23.1 million taka (about 0.49
million dollars) to 15 partner organizations upto June 1998.
During the time, a total 22,818 members out of 28,094 received
loan of 82.9 million taka (about 1.76 million dollars) under 1,755
groups organized by the partners.
</P>
<P>
The ASA will continue to provide technical and financial
assistance to the small and local development organizations
through its partnership program, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the ASA distributed 420.2 million taka (about 8.94
million dollars) as loan to 40,679 borrowers under its small
entrepreneurship development program and 21.7 million taka (about
461,170 dollars) to 1,156 borrowers as individual credit.
</P>
<P>
The percentage of recovery of loan disbursed by the ASA is
99.94 percent.
</P>
<P>
The ASA took a plan to disburse loan of 4.72 billion taka
(about 100.4 million dollars) to general members, small traders,
farm owners and borrowers for sanitation in the current year.
</P>
<P>
The ASA's micro-credit model is being lauded as an effective
way for alleviating poverty in many countries. Cambodia adopted
the model of ASA in 1993, Afghanistan in 1995, Jordan and Ethiopia
in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
