<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 12th NAM Summit Opens in Durban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DURBAN, South Africa, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The 12th summit
of the Non-Aligned movement (NAM) opened here Wednesday morning
with 65 heads of state and government expected to focus their
attention on the economic and political issues facing them.
</P>
<P>
Colombian President Andres Pastrana, chairman of the last NAM
summit, declared the meeting open at the International Convention
Center in Durban, South Africa.
</P>
<P>
He reviewed the progress that the movement had achieved in the
past three years since the last summit was held in Cartagena,
Colombia, and expressed the hope that new vigor would be put into
the movement and more greater achievements would be attained in
the coming years.
</P>
<P>
Pastrana then handed over the NAM chairmanship to South
African President Nelson Mandela.
</P>
<P>
Address the opening ceremony, Mandela said development
and peace, which have been the central objectives of the movement
from its foundation, still remain its principal challenges.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the violence of war, whether in the Democratic
Republic of Congo or in Kosovo, and whether in Afghanistan or in
Sri Lanka, are destroying human life.
</P>
<P>
The critical question of nuclear disarmament must remain high
on the list of priorities of the movement and the NAM countries
will have to continue to address the issue to ensure actual
achievement in this regard, said Mandela.
</P>
<P>
On the economic difficulties facing the developing nations,
Mandela said: " One of the most immediate challenges that face
the developed countries is the need to remove the burden of the
unbearable debt. Much has been said about this, what is needed
is action by the developed countries and their partners in the
South."
</P>
<P>
There are resources within the world economy which could and
should be mobilized to address the development of the poor of the
world, he said.
</P>
<P>
Mandela called on the counterparts in the North to recognize
the door of enormous economic possibilities open toward the
achievement of a shared prosperity.
</P>
<P>
He also called for an African Renaissance in which the
continent will overcome a devastating past and ensure that it
also becomes a continent of democracy and peace, respect for
human rights, development and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
The greatest challenge the movement faces, is the obligation
to ensure that "the objective of the rebirth of the continent of
Africa should and must succeed", Mandela stressed.
</P>
<P>
The NAM, which emerged in the wake of the Cold War, was formed
in 1961 in Belgrade, capital of Yugoslavia, where its first
meeting was attended by representatives from 25 countries.
</P>
<P>
The movement which now has 113 member countries is the biggest
demonstration of unity of the world's nations and their on-going
struggle to restructure the world economy and assure their right
to social development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
