<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Agencies to Discuss Natural Disaster Warning Systems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The International Decade
(1990-2000) for Natural Disaster Reduction (IDNDR) will hold an
international conference in Postdam, Germany, on September 7-11 on
early warning systems for the reduction of natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
"The use of effective early warnings has enabled successful
evacuations of people from impending disasters in India, the
Philippines and Bangladesh among others," said the IDNDR in a
press release here Tuesday. "Timely action has saved thousands of
lives."
</P>
<P>
The participants at the Postdam meeting will discuss the latest
scientific and technical achievements and modeling scenarios, the
decision and formulation of warnings, and dissemination of data
and messages via communication systems.
</P>
<P>
They will also deliberate responses to such warnings and
related aspects of the early warning systems at different levels
of society.
</P>
<P>
Among the participants will be heads of a number of world
organizations and United Nations agencies on telecommunications,
weather, environment, development, agriculture and health.
</P>
<P>
Natural hazards such as tropical storms, earthquakes and
volcanic eruptions cannot be avoided but their negative effects on
vulnerable populations can be reduced by timely and effective
warning systems.
</P>
<P>
This requires that the potential risk of a hazardous phenomenon
and the vulnerability of the population involved is identified
accurately, and that the information is transmitted to the
individuals in sufficient time and clarity so that they can take
action.
</P>
<P>
Depending on the nature of the hazard, the location of
vulnerable people and assets, elements of warning systems may be
organized and implemented at local, national, regional or
international levels.
</P>
<P>
The outcome of the Postdam conference will be a critical
element in the concluding IDNDR recommendations, which will be
presented in the special session of the Economic and Social
Commission (ECOSOC) and at the IDNDR Program Forum, both scheduled
for July 1999 in Geneva. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
