<HEADLINE> American Fans Rush for "Titanic" Video </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Fans across the United
States lined early Tuesday morning to buy the two-tape set of
"Titanic," a film that won 11 Academy Awards, including best
picture.
</P>
<P>
Film industry analysts say that, with the release of video
tapes, there began a second wave of the "Titanic" craze.
</P>
<P>
Blockbuster Video, a chain of video shops, announced it had
pre-sold one million copies while Best Buy, a chain of stores that
also sell video tapes nationwide, said it sold 50,000 copies
during the first two hours of Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Video Store Magazine, a trade publication, estimated Paramount
had shipped out 24 million "Titanic" video, beating the previous
leader, "Jurassic Park," which holds the record among live-action
videos at 17 million copies sold.
</P>
<P>
The frenzy to buy the tape, which many stores are selling it
for 20 U.S. dollar or less, has led industry analysts to predict
"Titanic" will easily become the biggest-selling live-action video
of all time.
</P>
<P>
"Titanic was well on its way toward becoming the
biggest-selling live-action video in Hollywood history," one
analyst said.
</P>
<P>
The appeal of "Titanic" is so vast that, despite its impending
release on video, the film earned an additional 385,000
U.S. dollar at the box office over the weekend, becoming the first
film to take in more than 600 million U.S. dollar in North America
alone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
