<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xiamen, Taiwan Increase Economic Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Economic and trade cooperation
between this port city in east China's Fujian Province and the
opposite Taiwan region has continued to grow steadily this year,
official figures have indicated.
</P>
<P>
Xiamen has approved 1,548 projects funded by investors from
Taiwan since the mainland launched its market reform drive in the
late 1970s. Contracted and paid-in investment from Taiwan in these
projects totaled 3.22 billion U.S. dollars and 2.2 billion
U.S. dollars, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The number of projects funded by companies from Taiwan and the
value of contracted Taiwan investment accounted for 35 percent
and 23 percent, respectively, of Xiamen's total.
</P>
<P>
Besides, enterprises funded by investors from Taiwan now
account for 45 percent of Xiamen's industrial output value.
</P>
<P>
Investors from Taiwan mainly invest in industrial projects,
such as electronics, machinery, chemicals, light industry and
textiles and building materials, according to a city official.
</P>
<P>
He said that more than 80 percent of the production of the
enterprises is exported and 86 percent of the firms are profitable.
</P>
<P>
Over the years, trade between Xiamen and Taiwan has totaled
7.75 billion U.S. dollars, with imports from Taiwan hitting 7.05
billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of this year, imports and exports between
Xiamen and Taiwan reached 478 million U.S. dollars, up 8.1 percent
from the same period last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980902.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Defends Its Presence in Congo (K) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean Foreign Minister
Stan Mudenge has defended his country's military presence in the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
He also dismissed the charges by Rwandan Foreign Minister
Anastase Gasana, who said the Southern African Development
Community (SADC) has no security role in Congo (K), Zambia's
independent paper The Post reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Mudenge was speaking on his arrival Tuesday in the South
African city of Durban to attend a ministerial meeting of the
Non-Aligned Movement which opened Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He said Rwanda and Uganda must remove their forces from the
former Zaire and allow the Congolese people to find a peaceful
solution to their problems.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe, along with Angola and Namibia, has sent troops to
help the embattled government of President Laurent Kabila quash a
rebellion which began exactly one month ago.
</P>
<P>
Rwandan Foreign Minister Anastase Gasana criticized the SADC's
military presence in Congo at a news conference held earlier
Tuesday, saying the 14-member bloc does not understand the
situation in the Great Lakes area, which comprises Burundi,
Congo, Rwanda, Tanzania and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Both Rwanda and Uganda, which claimed they have security
interests in eastern Congo, have denied Kabila's accusations that
they are supporting the Congo rebels who are attempting to oust
his 15-month government.
</P>
<P>
Also on Monday, the U.N. called for an immediate cease-fire
and on all foreign forces to leave Congo.
</P>
<P>
The U.N Security Council urged a dialog to end the fighting in
the vast central African country and its transformation toward
democratic rule. 
</P>
</TEXT>
