<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State Development Bank Issues First Bonds by Public Bidding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The State Development Bank
(SDB) issued five billion yuan (604 million US dollars) in
one-year financial bonds today, the first batch of bonds the bank
has issued through public bidding.
</P>
<P>
Instead of being distributed by the central bank to other banks
and postal savings institutions as in the past, the bonds this
time will first go to underwriters through public bidding, and the
commercial banks and insurance companies will then buy the bonds
from the underwriters.
</P>
<P>
With an annual interest rate of 5.19 percent, the bonds are
expected to be traded on the national interbank money market after
receiving approval from the central bank.
</P>
<P>
SDB president Chen Yuan said the central bank will continue to
issue bonds this way, while keeping the past practice of issuing
bonds through designated subscription.
</P>
<P>
As one of China's three policy banks, the SDB issues financial
bonds to raise funds for loans, which are mainly used to support
the nation's basic industries and infrastructures.
</P>
<P>
By the end of June this year, the bank had raised 398.9 billion
yuan (48 billion US dollars) through issuing financial bonds,
accounting for more than 90 percent of the total funds. The
remainder comes from the government and overseas funding sources.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980902.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibet Plans First Railway Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, September 2 (Xinhua) -- China has completed a study on
the feasibility of building the first railway line in Tibet, a
project which would make Tibet the last region in China to have a
railroad.
</P>
<P>
An official with the Ministry of Railways said the
1,100-kilometer trans-Tibet railway line is expected to cost 13.92
billion yuan (about 1.7 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
He said the Golmud-Lhasa railway will be the shortest channel
linking Beijing, Shanghai and central China.
</P>
<P>
The Golmud-Lhasa railway will link Golmud in Qinghai Province
with Lhasa, capital of Tibet. This route has been an important
byway between Tibet and inland areas for at least 1,200 years.
</P>
<P>
Railway builders here say that after many years of research
they have discovered ways to deal with such geographical
difficulties as frozen soil and high altitudes during construction
of the railway.
</P>
<P>
Beginning in 1984, China has built up a 815-kilometer railway
from Golmud to Xining, provincial capital of Qinghai
Province.
</P>
<P>
Statistics indicate that at least 85 percent of the materials
transported to and from Tibet are conveyed via Golmud.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
