<DOCNO> XIE19980902.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mongolian Parliament Rejects Amarjargal's Nomination For PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The Great Hural
(parliament) of Mongolia on Wednesday vetoed the nomination of
Renchinnyamin Amarjargal as the country's prime minister.
</P>
<P>
The Great Hural then asked the ruling coalition of the National
Democratic Party and Social Democratic Party to submit a new
premier nominee to the parliament in 14 days, according to the
parliamentary press office.
</P>
<P>
Amarjargal, 36, who was a member of the Great Hural and acting
minister of external relations, was nominated for the premiership
by the ruling union on August 28 in a letter to the president.
</P>
<P>
After accepting the nomination on August 31, President
Bagabandy submitted it to the Great Hural for approval, a
presidential spokesman said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the president rejected five times the nomination of
Davaadorj Ganbold, who was chairman of the Standing Committee of
Economic Policy of the Great Hural.
</P>
<P>
President Bagabandy believed that Davaadorj was responsible
for the country's intensified banking crisis, which led to the
fall of the former cabinet in July.
</P>
<P>
Instead, President Bagabandy nominated Dogsomin Ganbold, a
member of the Great Hural and the Mongolian National Democratic
Party, for the post. But the ruling union did not agree with the
president's proposal.
</P>
<P>
The ex-government led by Prime Minister Tsakhya Elbegdorj was
dismissed on July 24 as a result of its decision in May to merge
the state-owned Renovation Bank with the private Golomt Bank.
</P>
<P>
Under Mongolia's law, the ruling parties' parliamentary group
should discuss the prime minister nominee with the president, who
in turn submits the nomination to the Great Hural for approval.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980902.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
