<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Universities Attract More Overseas Students </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 2 (Xinhua)-- The number of overseas
students studying at universities in Shanghai has increased year
by year since the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Some 2,598 such students from 101 countries and regions such as
the United States, Japan, Germany, Canada, Poland, India, Argentina
and Cuba are currently studying in 22 local universities,
including Fudan University and Tongji University.
</P>
<P>
More than half of the overseas students specialize in the
Chinese language and traditional Chinese subjects such as
acupuncture, massage and architecture.
</P>
<P>
The universities have provided good study environments and
living conditions for the students. For example, the International
Culture Exchange College at Fudan University offers 10-odd majors
to the 730 students from 52 countries.
</P>
<P>
Many of the students have played important roles after
returning home. Last July, five Malaysian students earned bachelor
degrees from the Shanghai Traditional Chinese Medicine University
and six months later opened four traditional Chinese medicine
clinics in their hometowns.
</P>
<P>
One education expert notes that Shanghai has a long history of
cultural and educational exchanges between East and West. He said
the city's status as the nation's economic, finance and trade
center has attracted an increasing number of overseas students in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
Overseas students can easily find jobs in Shanghai's numerous
joint ventures and overseas-funded companies after graduation,
according to the expert.
</P>
<P>
A total of 20,000 overseas students will have studied in
Shanghai by the end of this century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
