<HEADLINE> PLA Men in Inner Mongolia Return to Bases After Victory over Floods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, September 2 (Xinhua) -- More than 6,000 officers and
men of the Chinese People's Liberation Army (PLA) have returned to
their barracks after winning victory over the floods in north
China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
However, the historic, devastating flooding which began in
early July has left 370,000 people homeless in the autonomous
region. Local governments are now organizing large-scale
rehabilitation efforts, with the priority of helping the flood
victims tide it over the coming winter.
</P>
<P>
Flooding along the Nenjiang River pushed more than 20 of its
tributaries to overflow at some 800 spots, affecting some six
million people, destroying nearly 500,000 room-units and damaging
370,000 others, leaving 354,000 head of livestock dead, and
inundating two million hectares of crops.
</P>
<P>
Soldiers from the Beijing, Shenyang, and Inner Mongolia
military command areas and six helicopters were sent to combat the
flooding. The Inner Mongolia Military Command Area also aroused
1,530 militia companies to participate in the effort.
</P>
<P>
All the breaches and danger spots along the river now have been
properly dealt with, sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
