<DOCNO> XIE19980902.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overseas Reporters Gather in Ningxia for Founding Anniversary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Several hundred Chinese and
overseas reporters have gathered in Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region,
China's smallest autonomous region (province) as the 40th
anniversary of the Region's founding approaches.
</P>
<P>
Two reporters from Japan's Asahi and Yomiuri daily newspapers,
who visited Ningxia 10 years ago, said they seemed to come to a
totally unfamiliar place this time and that all the changes in the
region themselves are news stories.
</P>
<P>
Northwest China's Ningxia comprises only 66,400 square
kilometers. Half a century ago, the region only had 19 motor
vehicles, a power generator, a 100-line telephone exchange, and
one 714-kilometer long-distance telephone line.
</P>
<P>
By 1997, the region's gross domestic product reached 21 billion
yuan (about 2.5 billion U.S. dollars), hundreds of kilometers of
railroad lines have been built, the regional airport receives 40
flights each week, and there are 370,000 telephone subscribers.
</P>
<P>
Ma Qizhi, Chairman of Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region, said very
few overseas reporters came to his region decades ago because of
its backward economy and lack of communications.
</P>
<P>
With the stress of the economic construction in northwest China
in the past few years, the region has begun attracting more
overseas media attention.
</P>
<P>
Among the overseas reporters here are representatives from the
U.S. Wall Street Journal, the BBC and Japan's Tokyo Daily, all of
whom are interested in China's aid-the-poor operation in Ningxia's
southern mountainous areas, one of the poorest areas in China.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Datukabu Bakar A. Harmid, head of the
Malaysian National News Agency and Hussein Ismail, a reporter from
Egypt, both from Muslim countries, focus on the daily and
religious life of Muslims in the region.
</P>
<P>
Over 3,000 mosques have been built in this smallest of China's
autonomous regions, and on average there is one mosque for every
500 Muslims in the region.
</P>
<P>
Finish television and Hong Kong-based Asia TV are interested
in the region's desert control, a big problem for many countries.
</P>
<P>
A large delegation of 12 major Hong Kong newspapers and
television reporters will visit the region, and additional
correspondents from the United States, Britain, Germany and
Australia will cover the 40th founding anniversary celebrations in
Ningxia in late September.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
