<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inflation, Bank Rates Lower in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Inflation eased and interest
rates dropped in Kenya in August, as the Shilling showed signs of
weakening during the week to September, according to the weekly
report by the Central Bank of Kenya (CBK).
</P>
<P>
But the general and underlying rates of inflation eased
following the sustained slowdown in the expansion of money supply
and stability of the Shillings, coupled with improved supplies of
basic food items, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Liquidity in the domestic money market eased during the week
to September, following the reduction of commercial banks'
statutory cash ratio requirement.
</P>
<P>
The average interbank borrowing interest rates declined to
24.32 percent during the week to August 28, from 24.97 percent
the previous week, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The Shilling began to weaken against major trading currencies
during the week to September exchanging on average at 59.56
Shillings to the U.S. Dollar, and 98.65 Shillings to the Sterling
Pound, compared to 59.52 Shillings and 96.98 Shillings
respectively in the previous week.
</P>
<P>
In the equity market Tuesday, the Nairobi Stock Exchange (NSE)
recorded heavy trading with a total of 513,350 shares changing
hands, at a value of 31.3 million Shillings, compared to 313,700
shares valued at 18 million Shillings Monday.
</P>
<P>
The number of deals stood at 282 from 271, whereas the NSE
20-share index slipped by 7.16 points or 0.25 percent to close at
2,855.50.
</P>
<P>
In the bonds market, the CBK Treasury bond Issue 1/98 was
heavily traded, with bonds worth 112.8 million Shillings sold at
prices ranging between 102.4 percent and 102.9879 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
