<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Population to Hit 180 Million in 2017 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's population would
reach 108 million this year, and 180 million by the year 2017, if
the current 3.2 percent growth rate is unchecked, according to a
health official.
</P>
<P>
Alhaji Tukur Mani, Permanent Secretary for the Ministry of
Health, made the statement at a symposium on "Day of Six Billion"
to round off the World Population Day celebration in Lagos, the
Daily Times reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The nation's fertility rate of about six was relatively high
compared to what obtained in developed countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Our population is a youthful one and the percentage of those
below age 15 is 48 percent with the resultant heavy dependency
ratio and its far-reaching consequences on available resources
and development efforts," Mani noted.
</P>
<P>
The official called for the education of the girl children and
the elimination of all forms of discrimination against them,
adding that one of the measures to eliminate harmful cultural
practice to girl children was the regular dissemination of
information through the mass media.
</P>
<P>
Mani appealed to Nigerians to have the number of children they
could cater for in relation to the provision of basic needs of
life in order to improve the quality of life. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
