<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brutal Heat Wave Brings out Pests in California </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Residents in Southern
California are busy calling fire departments for help to remove
snakes, spiders, rodents, coyotes and other animals driven into
their homes by wildfires and a brutal heat wave.
</P>
<P>
A college student in Ventura County, northwest of Los Angeles
Country, called for help when she came face-to-face with a
rattlesnake in her bathroom. Ventura County firefighters rushed in
and decapitated the snake with a shovel.
</P>
<P>
"We are averaging between two to eight calls a day for snakes,
usually in areas that interface with wildlands. There is
tarantulas around, too," fire spokeswoman Sandi Wells said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Temperatures have been around 40 centigrade degree during most
daytimes of this summer across the Southern California. Lightning
touched off dozens of wildfires in the region Monday night and
Tuesday morning, destroying nearly 30,000 acres of brush and
timber.
</P>
<P>
Local officials say that it was the brutal heat and wildfires
that brought the pests inside homes. They also blamed El Nino
earlier this year for dumping heavy winter rain that caused more
vegetation and burgeoning pest population.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980902.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibet Rebuilding National Highways after Flood Damage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- National highways which were
destroyed during the floods have been rebuilt in southwest China's
Tibet Autonomous Region and traffic has returned to normal,
according to regional officials.
</P>
<P>
The heavy flooding in Tibet this year has caused several routes
to be discontinued and destroyed several bridges. According to the
statistics of the Tibet Communications Bureau, the roads that were
destroyed by the flooding added up to 2,125 kilometers, one-tenth
of all Tibetan roads. And all the national highways and local
ones were damaged to some degree.
</P>
<P>
The traffic disruptions, which inconvenienced the Tibetan
people and hindered the flood fight, are expected to have a direct
effect on economic development in Tibet
</P>
<P>
Several Tibetan emergency groups made up of specialists in
the fields of water conservation and transportation patrolled the
main roads day and night to check conditions and speed up repairs.
</P>
<P>
The Tibet Autonomous Region has put more than 13 million yuan
into rebuilding its highways; and nearly 100 dangerous sections
have been repaired.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, No.108 and No.109 national highways have returned to
normal, officials said.
</P>
<P>
The Tibetan Transportation Bureau reportedly raised another 5
million yuan to ensure the smooth transportation of the national
highways between Qinghai and Tibet, and Sichuan and Tibet.
</P>
<P>
More heavy rain is predicted for September in Tibet, which
could cause more problems for local government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
