<HEADLINE> Indian Missile Testing Provokes New Arms Race: Pak Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan warned on Wednesday
that India's development of short and medium range missiles would
"provoke a new arms race in South Asia."
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan has repeatedly drawn international attention to the
security implications of the Indian missile program," a Foreign
Office spokesman said in a statement, referring to India's testing
of a surface-to-air missile on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He called on the international community to "persuade India to
refrain from provoking a new arms race in South Asia."
</P>
<P>
"The development and deployment by India of short and medium
range missiles directly affected regional security, which had
already been undermined by Indian nuclear tests and escalation in
Indian firing along the Line of Control in Kashmir," he said.
</P>
<P>
India tested its surface-to-air missile for the second time
this year on Tuesday. The 650-kilogram "Akash" (sky) missile,
with a range of 25 kilometers, is capable of carrying a
50-kilogram payload. 
</P>
