<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Population Growth Rate Falls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's population growth
rate, one of the highest in Africa in the late 1980s and early
1990s, has decreased dramatically and now is among the lowest in
the continent, a U.N. agency report said.
</P>
<P>
The 1998 U.N. Population Fund report noted that this east
African country saw population growth levels fall to only 2.2
percent in 1995, thanks to a successful family life education
program.
</P>
<P>
This indicates a slowing down in Kenya's population which
currently stands at about 29 million. It also means that the
country is set to reach more than 50 million people by the year
2025, said the annual report issued Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
However, this is a dramatic improvement on population reports
in the early 1990s which predicted that Kenya's population levels
could surpass 70 million after 2015.
</P>
<P>
The report added that the average life expectancy of Kenya men
will only reach 52 while Kenyan women can live until 55.
</P>
<P>
The main reason for the low life expectancy levels in Kenya is
the crisis caused by AIDS. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980902.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Has 3rd Warmest Winter in Over 140 years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- This year's winter was the
third warmest in New Zealand since records began in 1853,
according to a national climate survey.
</P>
<P>
The Dominion, A Wellington-based paper, Wednesday quoted
spokesman of the National Institute of Water and Atmospheric
Research of New Zealand as saying that the country's average
temperature in this winter was 9.1 degrees Celsius. The two warmer
winters were in 1971 (9.2C) and 1984 (9.4C).
</P>
<P>
The survey said that in Northland, Auckland, Waikato and
coastal Bay of Plenty temperatures were much higher, ranging
between 1.5C and 2C above average.
</P>
<P>
In Nelson and Marlborough and the rest of the North Island
temperatures ranged between 1C and 1.5C above average. In central
Otago temperatures were 0.5C below average.
</P>
<P>
Rainfall was well below average in many eastern areas.
</P>
<P>
From Wairarapa to eastern Southland dry conditions continued
from summer and rainfall was less than 80 percent of normal, the
survey said.
</P>
<P>
However, In Auckland, Coromandel, Bay of Plenty, Taupo,
Marlborough and Nelson rainfall increased up to 50 per cent.
</P>
<P>
The winter was cloudier than usual in much of the North Island,
 the survey said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
