<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Economic Review: China Looks to Deficit Policy to Stimulate Economy -1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
by Xinhua Writer Xu Xingtang
</P>
<P>
BEIJING, September 2 (Xinhua) -- China announced recently that
it will issue 100 billion yuan in long-term treasury bonds to
support infrastructure construction, indicating that China is
trying to stimulate the economy through debt and deficit policies.
</P>
<P>
The bonds will be listed in the state budget in the next two
years, 50 billion yuan of which will be listed in this year's
budget, expanding this year's financial deficit from the original
46 billion yuan to 96 billion yuan, considerably exceeding the
debt and deficit ceilings ratified by the first plenary session of
the Ninth National People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
Chinese economists hold that under the present conditions of
deflation, increased net withdrawal of money from circulation, and
a serious insufficiency of capital for construction projects, it's
both necessary and feasible for the government to increase input
in infrastructure projects through deficit expenditures.
</P>
<P>
China has set this year's economic growth target at eight
percent, though in the first half of this year the growth rate was
only seven percent. With exports negatively impacted by the Asian
financial crisis, the government has defined increased investment
as a major contributor to reaching the goal of eight percent
growth.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Finance Xiang Huaicheng said that increasing
fiscal expenditure not only can directly promote social demand,
but also can stimulate individual consumption and enterprise
investment through increased wages and profits, thereby indirectly
increasing social demand.
</P>
<P>
He said that when the economy is slowing down, the stimulating
effect of monetary policy is comparatively slow, while fiscal
policies can directly expand social demand and can quickly boost
up the economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
