<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Int'l Tribunal for Rwanda Hands Down First </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The International
Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda (ICTR) based in Arusha, Tanzania
will hand down Wednesday the first judgement on the crime of
genocide ever to be decided by an international court.
</P>
<P>
A press release issued here Wednesday by the United Nations
Economic Commission for Africa (ECA) said the tribunal will
pronounce, in a separate case, the first ever sentence for
genocide two days later.
</P>
<P>
"These landmark decisions will be the first to breathe life
into the genocide convention, which was adopted 50 years ago in
the wake of the holocaust of the Second World War," the press
release added.
</P>
<P>
The ICTR was established by the United Nations Security
Council in November 1994 following the massacre of at least
500,000 people, mainly Tutsis and moderate Hutus in a period of
just three months.
</P>
<P>
The tribunal has the mandate to prosecute persons responsible
for genocide and other serious violations of international
humanitarian law committed in the territory of Rwanda and Rwandan
citizens responsible for such violations committed in the
territory of neighboring states between January 1, 1994 and
December 31, 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
