<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's terms of trade fell by 1.3 percent in the
second quarter of this year due to a seasonal drop in the prices
of agricultural exports.
</P>
<P>
According to latest official statistics, both the import and
export prices declined in the second quarter. But export prices
dropped more than import prices did, causing the country's terms
of trade to worsen by 1.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Thomson Bankwatch, the International Rating Agency,
has said that Lebanese economy has improved thanks to the reduced
fiscal deficit and inflation rate, the Daily Star reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Kamal Shehadi, one of the managers of the agency, said that
Thomson Bankwatch has upgraded its view of Lebanese economy given
its successful issue of 1 billion U.S. dollars worth of Eurobond
in April, the renewed interest from Arab tourists and investors,
and the increased foreign exchange reserves.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- The six-day "Made in Bahrain" exhibition opened on
Tuesday at the Forum de Beyrouth in Beirut.
</P>
<P>
More than 55 Bahraini companies took part in the fair, which
featured aluminium, gold, jewellery, electric appliances,
furniture and medical equipment.
</P>
<P>
Bahrain, the leading aluminium producers and the banking
center of the Gulf, hopes the exhibition will pave the way for
more trade with Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- The International Financial Corporation (IFC), the
World Bank's investment arm, is planning to finance tourism,
agricultural and housing projects in Lebanon, the Daily Star
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The move is in line with a World Bank decision to increase the
proportion of credit facilities to Lebanon's private sector from
1.5 percent to 3 percent of the loan budget.
</P>
<P>
So far, the IFC has granted the private sector 442 million
U.S. dollars in short and medium-term loans, creating over 6,000
jobs in Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
