<HEADLINE> Bomb Imported into Kenya as Relief Food Aid: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 2 (Xinhua) -- A key suspect in the deadly
August 7 Nairobi bombing has confessed here that materials for
making the bomb were brought into Kenya as part of relief food
consignments, a national newspaper said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Suspect Khalid Salim, also known as Mohamed Rashed Daoud
Al-Owhali, was quoted as saying that the materials were hidden
mainly in consignments of rice that came into Kenya through an
unregistered non-governmental organization (NGO).
</P>
<P>
The East African Standard report also claimed that a Kenyan
expert has identified the vehicle used in the bombing was a
Toyota Dyna, a three-ton pick-up manufactured 10 to 13 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The report, quoting Salim, said the bombers started their
planning in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Investigators believe the terrorist squad had organized
themselves into a bogus NGO and, through relief operations, they
gathered the necessary ingredients used to make the bomb which
finally killed 253 people and wounded over 5,000 others, said the
report.
</P>
<P>
The explosion leveled a five-storey commercial building and
extensively damaged the U.S. embassy and adjacent Cooperative
Bank House in the downtown area of the Kenyan capital.
</P>
<P>
Khalid, said to be a Yemeni, was the man who allegedly hurled
a grenade at the U.S. embassy moments before the bomb blast. His
confessions were made in Nairobi before the U.S. and Kenyan
investigators.
</P>
<P>
Khalid and another key suspect Mohammed Saddiq Howaida, were
transferred to the United States last week for trial on charge of
murder. 
</P>
</TEXT>
