<DOCNO> XIE19980902.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Economic Review: China Looks to Deficit Policy to Stimulate Economy -2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
by Xinhua Writer Xu Xingtang
</P>
<P>
At present, China's fiscal deficit accounts for about 2.2
percent of its gross domestic product (GDP), lower than the
internationally recognized warning line of three percent; while
the outstanding amount of government debt is expected to be 10.3
percent of the GDP by the end of this year, this is also lower
than that of most other countries.
</P>
<P>
"There is still much room for the government to expand the
scale of treasury bonds," Xiang said.
</P>
<P>
Some economists hold that, with the recovering of the economy
and the deepening of economic reforms, the government will
gradually build its fiscal strength, and its ability to repay will
be constantly improved, so there should be no government debt
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Wang Binsheng, a noted economist from the China Academy of
Social Sciences, said that although China issues more than 250
billion yuan in treasury bonds annually, and the outstanding
amount of treasury bonds exceeded 400 billion yuan by the end of
1997, it's still feasible for the government to appropriately
increase the issuance of treasury bonds, considering the endurance
of the national economy and the amount of personal savings.
</P>
<P>
He said that with the present stable market prices, low
interest rates and increased investment consciousness, treasury
bonds will be well received with its comparatively higher interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
Well-known economist Zhang Liqun said that from the long-term
point of view, the present deficit policy does not contradict the
state's long-term target of gradually reducing the deficit. Economic
growth is a prerequisite for fiscal income growth, using fiscal
policies to improve economic growth creates sources of fiscal
income growth and enables deficit reduction in the long term.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Minister of Finance Lou Jiwei said that the 100 billion
yuan in treasury bonds will be coordinated by banks with about the
same amount of loans, which together will contribute more than two
percentage points to the GDP, giving a big boost to this year's
economic growth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
