<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hke090221 -UNFPA Issues State of World Population Report in Dhaka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The representative of the United
Nations Population Fund (UNFPA) in Bangladesh issued the State of
World Population Report 1998 here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference held at the National Press Club, Alain P.
Mouchiroud, the representative of the UNFPA in Bangladesh, said
the country has made success in its population program by reducing
the growth rate of 3.0 percent in 1973 to 1.7 percent in 1997 with
a population of 124 million.
</P>
<P>
However, as the population in Bangladesh is very young with 43
percent below 15 years of age, the potential for future growth is
tremendous, he said.
</P>
<P>
Under the more optimistic assumption, he said, the level of
replacement (two children per couple) would be reached in
Bangladesh by 2005, and in that case, the population would not be
able to be stabilized before 40 to 50 years, at a size of about
170 million.
</P>
<P>
A more realistic scenario shows that the population of the
Bangladesh could reach 200-250 million, and would stabilize
sometimes around the middle of the next century, according to
Mouchiroud.
</P>
<P>
Adolescents aged 10-19 years in the country represent a little
more than one-fifth of the total population at present, and would
rise to 22 percent in 2000 and 2005, and the youth, aged 15-29,
increased from 22 percent in 1974 to 15.7 percent in 1995 and
would further grow to 28.3 percent in 2010, he said.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the country would face challenges in providing
education, nutrition, employment and health to the young
population, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
With regard to the issue of the elderly, Mouchiroud said the
elderly has been largely overlooked, as not much has been done in
Bangladesh as in many other countries.
</P>
<P>
To call for more concern about the elderly, the United Nations
has declared 1999 as "The International Year of Older Persons," he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
