<HEADLINE> Indonesia Has No Pressing Need for Fighter Planes: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia at the moment has no
pressing need for new Russian Sukhois or U.S. F-16s, Chief of
Staff of the Indonesian Air Force Rear Marshall Hanafi Asnan was
quoted by Antara News Agency Wednesday as saying.
</P>
<P>
"We do not need these fighters now, maybe within 10 years. What
we have at present are enough," he told reporters in the country's
second largest city of Surabaya Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He said the air force will just maximize the use of its F-16s
and British Aerospace Sky Hawks.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia has 10 F-16s and 24 units of British Aerospace Sky
Hawk 100 and 200.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia planned to purchase F-16s from the U.S. a few years
ago, Asnan said, but when this was blocked by the U.S. Congress,
Indonesia opted to buy Sukhois instead, which were cheaper.
</P>
<P>
Following the onslaught of the regional economic crisis,
Indonesia had to postpone its plan to purchase Sukhois, Asnan
added. 
