<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heat Wave Sparks Power Emergency in California </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Californian authorities
Monday twice declared emergency after the power use neared record
levels, due to Southern California's current heat wave, according
to reports released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Independent System Operator (ISO), which operates California's
electric power grid, declared a "stage one" emergency Monday
morning, in which utilities urge customers to conserve power.
</P>
<P>
Later in the day, the ISO declared a "stage two" emergency
after power use neared record levels and caused intermittent power
outages in the region.
</P>
<P>
Industry sources said the emergency escalated to stage two when
the ISO determined that operating reserves had dipped below 5
percent. Utilities were then allowed to interrupt power to large
commercial and industrial customers with whom they have
prearranged agreements.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the California Energy Commission said the demand
for electricity in the state outstripped supply twice this summer,
as 33 million residents turned on their air-conditioners when
temperatures reached around 40 centigrade during most daytimes.
</P>
<P>
Temperatures, which reached record high during the past week,
showed no sign of decrease.
</P>
<P>
The sources say the worst kind of emergency is a "stage three,"
in which the state's electricity system is within 1.5 percent of
failure and utilities are allowed to begin rolling blackout.
</P>
<P>
But so far, California has never experienced a stage three
power emergency, they added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
