<HEADLINE> hke090227 -Asian Crisis Forces Australia to Lower Growth Forecast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Australia revised down its
economic growth forecasts for the current financial year
Wednesday, blaming global financial turmoil and the downturn in
Asia.
</P>
<P>
Australian Treasurer Peter Costello said the nation's gross
domestic product (GDP) growth for 1998-99, which ends on June 30,
1999, was expected to come in at 2.75 percent rather than the 3
percent forecast by the government three months ago, but insisted
the economy remained strong.
</P>
<P>
"Treasury's economic forecasts for 1998-99 show that the
Australian economy continues to record solid growth and low
inflation in the face of the sharp slowdown in the Asian region
and a highly uncertain international environment," he said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
Gareth Evans, Australian shadow treasurer, rejected the
government's forecast as too optimistic, saying even the
downgraded figure was unlikely to be achievable, due to global
economic turmoil sparked by the tumbling Russian currency.
</P>
<P>
"We think 2.75 (percent growth) too optimistic for this
(financial) year," he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"When the United States catches cold Australia is one of those
many economies around that will catch pneumonia. That's the
outlook for the period ahead, and as a result these projections
and forecasts are simply, in our forecasts, much too optimistic,"
Evans said.
</P>
<P>
Despite its close economic ties with Asia, which buys
two-thirds of all the goods and services Australia exports, the
Australian economy did quite well in the past financial year
ending on June 30.
</P>
<P>
Figures released Wednesday by the Australian Bureau of
Statistics show the economy grew by 3.9 percent over the past
year.
</P>
<P>
Some economists, however, warn that the worst is yet to come in
this financial year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
