<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lightening Touches off Wildfires in California </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Lightning touched off
dozens of wildfires across Southern California early Tuesday
morning, destroying at least 100 structures, including 26 houses
or mobile homes, burning 30,000 acres of brush and timber, local
authorities reported.
</P>
<P>
The most destructive blaze was in Riverside County's Juniper
Flats, an area of dry, dense brush 85 miles southeast of Los
Angeles, where at least 36 structures, including 26 homes were
destroyed.
</P>
<P>
At least five other blazes burned east of Los Angeles,
according to Bill Peters, a spokesman for the California
Department of Forestry.
</P>
<P>
Firefighters also battled blazes around San Diego in the south,
and around San Francisco in the north, even in other Western
states, including Washington, Montana, Nevada and Idaho.
</P>
<P>
An inmate firefighter was killed and 11 others injured when a
truck headed for the front lines flipped.
</P>
<P>
High temperatures, heat, thunderstorms were blamed for the
destructive wildfires. Temperatures have reached record high in
most areas in Southern California during the past few days. On
Tuesday, thermometers once again reached above 40 centigrade in
most parts of the region.
</P>
<P>
The National Weather Service warned that the risk of fire will
continue to climb, with high temperatures and thunderstorms
expected to continue through this week in Southern California.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
