<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Residents Return to Border Town in West China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Farmer Luo Zhengxi, 37, has
returned to his hometown of Qingshuihe in the Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region, only 28 kilometer from China's western border
with the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
"Had there not been the frontier trade, the town would not have
developed so rapidly and I would not have come back here to make a
living," said Luo, who is taking up private transportation as his
new field.
</P>
<P>
China implemented a policy of opening up its border areas in
the 1990s, which has stimulated frontier trade in such places as
Qingshuihe. These small towns, which had once been inhabited by
Chinese troops, have become a thriving location for both local and
foreign traders.
</P>
<P>
More than 10,000 people have moved to the town in the past six
years. But, when China had strained relations with the Soviet
Union in the late 1950s to the 1970s, most of its residents --
including Luo -- left their hometown because of the military
buildup.
</P>
<P>
When Luo was six years old, conflicts arose at the border in
the late 1950s with the former Soviet Union. His mother took her
nine children huddled together on a train 80 kilometers inland
from the border.
</P>
<P>
In 1979, the Luo family had to move again when a counterattack
at the border with Vietnam, put the western areas on alert. In a
packed truck, Luo -- then 16 -- saw military vehicles, tanks, and
artillery moving forward to the border.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980902.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Residents Return to Border Town in West China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hotels and other large commercial buildings now stand in
Qingshuihe where military vehicles once were stationed. Many local
people are now doing business with traders from the Commonwealth
of Independent States, which formerly was part of the former Soviet
Union.
</P>
<P>
Though bargaining is part of the trading process, most traders
are satisfied with the end result. Fully loaded trucks fill the
40-meter-wide state highway connecting the town with the border.
</P>
<P>
Xu Jie, head of the town's economic and technical development
zone which was set up in 1992, said the town had almost no
infrastructure before the 1980s. But, since 1992, the government
has allocated 620 million yuan (about 75.6 million U.S. dollars)
to build up the infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
"Now its special geographic position has become an advantage
for the town's development," said Xu, 35, the former top official
in Qingshuihe who recently concluded trade talks in
Kazakhstan.
</P>
<P>
The town has absorbed more than 600 million yuan of investment
from other parts of China and from abroad. The town government
plans to set up a foreign trade market for shoes with the
cooperation of traders from Kazakhstan.
</P>
<P>
"When I saw President Jiang Zemin shaking hands with leaders of
four countries sharing the western border with China on TV, I knew
I would never have to relocate my home," Luo said.
</P>
<P>
In early July this year, Jiang met with leaders of Kazakhstan,
Kyrghyzstan, Russia and Tadzhikistan in Alma-Ata, capital of
Kazakhstan. One of the results of the meeting was the resolution
of all problems along the 1,700-kilometer border with Kazakhstan.
</P>
<P>
"The living experience in the border area tells me that a
single person's destiny is tightly connected with the country's
international standing and its policies," said Xu, adding that
the frontier trade will continue to be vigorous.  
</P>
</TEXT>
