<HEADLINE> Cambodian Students Protest Against Election Results </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, September 2 (Xinhua) -- About 10,000 Cambodian
students and supporters of the opposition parties held a large
demonstration Wednesday here to protest against the election
results released Tuesday by the National Election Committee.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators gathered at the front of the Royal Palace and
marched by the Independence Monument to the European Union office
here, shouting slogans against Second Prime Minister Hun Sen and
Vietnam, and saying that they would never accept the results as
announced by the NEC.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday official election results were released, showing
Second Prime Minister Hun Sen-led Cambodian People's Party (CPP)
winner of the election. The announcement came a day after the
Constitutional Council completed deliberations on the opposition's
appeals alleging election irregularities.
</P>
<P>
The two opposition political parties, the FUNCINPEC and the Sam
Rainsy Party, immediately rejected the results and vowed to keep
up their struggle by organizing another mass demonstration.
</P>
<P>
The sit-in protest in front of the National Assembly entered
its 10th day Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Prince Norodom Ranariddh, leader of the FUNCINPEC, reiterated
Wednesday to his supporters at his party headquarters the four-
point joint statement made by him and Sam Rainsy Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
The two opposition parties vowed not to participate in the new
parliament until their election fraud complaints are addressed and
an earlier seat allocation formula is adopted.
</P>
<P>
Second Prime Minister Hun Sen is expected to fly to Siem Reap
Thursday to discuss the deadlock with King Norodom Sihanouk.
</P>
<P>
He will most likely put forward his idea of getting the
Assembly members to amend the constitution so that the CPP could
form a government with only a simple majority, rather than
two-thirds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
