<HEADLINE> Chinese President Meets Israeli Defense Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Contacts between the Chinese
and Israeli armies have been on the rise as relations between the
two countries grow, President Jiang Zemin told visiting Israeli
Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai today.
</P>
<P>
Jiang, also Chairman of the Central Military Commission, said
he hopes to further promote friendly cooperative ties between the
two armies.
</P>
<P>
He said that since China and Israel forged diplomatic ties,
friendly bilateral relations have developed continuously and
steadily, and bilateral cooperation has been fruitful.
</P>
<P>
The exchanges of visit between various sectors at all levels
have served to deepen mutual understanding and friendship between
the two peoples, Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
On the Middle East, Jiang said the Chinese government has all
along been very concerned with the peace process and the situation
in that region.
</P>
<P>
He said it is a wise decision for Israel and all other
concerned parties to comply with the historic trends and seek to
settle disputes through peaceful negotiations, as this is not only
in the practical and long-term interests of both sides, but also
beneficial to world peace and development.
</P>
<P>
"We consider that relevant U.N. resolutions and the
land-for-peace principle set at the Madrid peace conference are
the basis for the Middle East peace talks and the basic terms to
guarantee the security and stability of relevant countries," Jiang
said.
</P>
<P>
"We sincerely hope the Middle East peace gets out of the
deadlock at an early date and scores effective results," the
Chinese president added.
</P>
<P>
Jiang also briefed his Israeli guests on the recent flood
control efforts in China. He thanked Mordechai for donating
medicines to the disaster-ravaged people.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai expressed his sympathy and solicitude for the people
in the flood-hit regions and donated, on behalf of his government,
55,000 U.S. dollars worth of medicine.
</P>
<P>
He stated that he is glad to visit China and exchange views
with Chinese leaders on issues of common concern. Mordechai said
he hopes his current visit would serve to further the friendly
cooperative relations between the two nations and the two
armies.
</P>
<P>
The minister also briefed Jiang on the current Middle East
situation.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai arrived in Beijing Monday for a four-day official
visit as guest of his Chinese counterpart, Chi Haotian, who is
also vice-chairman of the Central Military Commission and State
Councillor.
</P>
<P>
Chi was present at today's meeting. The two defense ministers
are scheduled to hold talks later today.  
</P>
</TEXT>
