<HEADLINE> Technical Correspondence School Helps Farmers Escape Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Lu Xiumei, a 42-year-old
farmer, had never thought of being a technician before she was
enrolled for a certificate program sponsored by the Zhejiang
Provincial Department of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
After graduating from a technical correspondence school five
years ago, Lu, a villager at Wenling City in east China's Zhejiang
Province, has successfully improved the standard of living for
herself and her disabled husband.
</P>
<P>
While receiving correspondence lessons on sea farming, she
started to cultivate various marine products by taking advantage
of aquatic agricultural techniques, and is now able to earn an
annual income of more than 200,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
"The great changes in my life can be attributed to the Rural
Technical Correspondence School," Lu said.
</P>
<P>
The school, led by China's Association for Science and
Technology, was established in 1985 with its purpose to teach
farmers applied technology for helping them rise above the poverty
level.
</P>
<P>
There are 88 branch schools in Zhejiang and various guidance
organizations in its 900 towns, said Wang Yangjie, an official
with Zhejiang's Association for Science and Technology.
</P>
<P>
Wang said that Zhejiang is launching a program to popularize
new technology among female villagers. At present, more than 60
percent of rural laborers in Zhejiang are women.
</P>
<P>
He said that 14,000 out of 60,000 female farmer trainees have
received the "Farming Technician Certificate."
</P>
<P>
A total of 500 training classes have been opened especially for
female villagers in Zhejiang since 1994, including the growing of
flowers and plants, aquatic farming, English and computer
applications. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
