<HEADLINE> Israeli Teachers' Strike Enters Second Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 2 (Xinhua) -- After the breakdown of
over-night negotiations with the Treasury, Israeli teachers'
unions declared on Wednesday that they will continue the strike.
</P>
<P>
The strike will keep the nation's 1.2 million students at home
for the second day after the new school year did not open as
scheduled on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Teachers' representatives for the negotiations said they had
heard no new proposals from the Treasury, noting that such talks
were a waste of time.
</P>
<P>
But Treasury wage director Yossi Kucik said he hoped the
teachers unions would "come to their senses and agree to a
reasonable wage agreement."
</P>
<P>
Treasury officials said that teachers are demanding an 8
percent salary increase, while they will agree only to a 5
percent increase.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Education Minister Yitzhak Levy said that he would
ask Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu to intervene and convene a
special cabinet session to resolve the issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
