<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Calls for More Donations for Children in Flood Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 2 (Xinhua) -- A spokesman for the Chinese
Ministry of Education is calling for an emergency donation from
China and abroad for solving the difficulties facing the children
in the country's flood-ravaged areas.
</P>
<P>
He said that one of the critical issues is helping children
return to schools and avoid diseases at the current stage of the
flooding fighting.
</P>
<P>
"Quite a number of children are still living in temporary
houses on dikes waiting for the reopening of schools, and some of
them are facing living difficulties," he said.
</P>
<P>
Although the educational departments have taken many methods to
solve the problems, he said, "the lack of money is the biggest
problem."
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that some 44,000 school buildings were
destroyed by flooding this summer, which brought problems to 8.47
million primary and secondary students and caused losses of 7.6
billion yuan (about 900 million U.S. dollars) in the educational
sector.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has set a goal to ensure all the
flood-affected schools to reopen in the autumn, when the new
semester begins.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that the Ministry of Education and China
Central Television (CCTV) will hold a charity show to raise
money on Sept. 10, which is the country's Teacher's Day.
</P>
<P>
The theatrical performance with the theme of "Helping Children
in Flood-Affected Areas" is expected to attract worldwide
attention, he said.
</P>
<P>
The money raised at the evening party will be directly used for
rebuilding schools and aiding poverty-stricken families of
students, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
