<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Inflation Registers Mild Rises in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Thai consumer prices rose 7.6
percent year-on-year in August, while wholesale prices jumped 12.9
percent in a significant moderation of the country's inflation
rate.
</P>
<P>
The Thai Commerce Ministry said in a statement available here
Wednesday that the Consumer Price Index (CPI) rose to 129.4, up
0.4 percent from July. In July the index was up 10 percent
year-on-year, while the wholesale price index shot up 19.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
Inflation as measured by the CPI has eased from a peak in June
of 10.7 percent year-on-year, the biggest increase in the decade.
</P>
<P>
The float of the baht on July 2, 1997, and its subsequent
depreciation by more than 36 percent has doubled the inflation
rate from levels seen in the first half of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund (IMF) has set a 9.2 percent
target for the CPI increase in 1998 as a condition for promising
Thailand a 17.2-billion-U.S. dollar economic rescue package.
</P>
<P>
In the first eight months of the year, consumer prices rose 9.5
percent from the same period last year, while wholesale prices
were up 18.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Karun Kittiaporn, director general of the ministry's Business
Economics Department, said the rate of increase in consumer prices
has begun to fall due to a decline in the inflation rate for food
and beverage prices.
</P>
<P>
Food and beverage prices were up 0.7 percent from July, but the
year-on-year increase in August was 7.4 percent, down from 11.8
percent in July.
</P>
<P>
Food prices account for 35.28 percent of the consumer index.
Eggs and dairy products accounted for the biggest jump in the
category, rising 18.3 percent year-on-year, and 0.2 percent
month-on-month. Rice and starch products rose 15.3 percent
year-on-year.
</P>
<P>
Non-food prices rose 8.2 percent year-on-year in August, and
0.2 percent from July. Tobacco and alcoholic beverages accounted
for the biggest increase in the category, rising 22.5 percent
year-on-year, and 0.4 percent month-on-month.
</P>
<P>
Prices of agricultural and food products in the wholesale index
rose 15.6 percent year-on-year. In the manufacturing sector,
wholesale prices were up 11.1 percent year-on-year in August, but
dropped 0.6 percent on July.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said monthly year-on-year figures should continue to
decline in the second half of 1998 as the comparisons will be
against the months in 1997 after the float of the baht, when
prices had already begun to rise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
