<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian Minister of Housing and Urban Communities
Ibrahim Soleiman said the final phase of the 200 kilometers long
Alexandria-Dumyat coastal road would be built by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The road estimated to cost 1.5 billion Egypt pounds (442 million
U.S. dollars) forms part of the 1,200-kilometer-long highway from
Rafah in the east to Salloum in the west along the Mediterranean
coast, connecting Egypt's northern governorates, said the Arab
daily Al Hayat on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Soleiman said the highway would promote development in the
regions along it by developing tourist resorts, implementing land
reclamation, setting up industrial zones, exploiting fisheries and
enhancing internal and international trade.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Chairman of Egypt's Cotton Exporters Federation Saeed
Haggas has said the export prices of cotton have dropped by 5 to
10 percent from the 1997-98 season, the Egyptian Alam Al Yom daily
reported on Tuesday
</P>
<P>
Nearly 90 million kilograms of Egyptian cotton is expected to
be exported in the 1998-99 season, Haggas said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Egyptian Minister of Trade and Supply Ahmed Goweili
has said the prospects for cotton export this year are good.
</P>
<P>
Goweili anticipated that Egypt's cotton production will reach
283 million kilograms, besides the 71.88 million kilograms left
over from last year.
</P>
<P>
TUNIS -- The Tunisian Chamber of Commerce and Industry is to
establish a data bank to serve national and foreign businessmen
and foundations, the Tunisian daily Al Sabah reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The bank will extend economic information, partnership
prospects and trade exchanges to industrialists and traders and
their foreign counterparts.
</P>
<P>
The bank will be linked with world and regional information
networks of the chambers of commerce and industry in Mediterranean
countries.
</P>
<P>
TUNIS -- More than 1.9 million tourists visited Tunisia in the
first half of this year, increasing by 6.3 percent from the figure
in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The Tunisian Tourism Ministry attributed the rise to a soar in
the number of tourists from the Arab Maghreb states, particularly
Libya.
</P>
<P>
About 78,000 Libyans traveled to Tunisia in the first six
months of this year, 30 percent more than the number in the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the number of French tourists increased by 16 percent
to about 348,000 people and Germans to about 366,000 tourists with
an increase of 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan and Switzerland signed an agreement here
Tuesday on professional training, Jordan`s official news agency
Petra reported.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the Swiss government will finance the
training of 90 Jordanians in the field of hotel service. 
</P>
</TEXT>
