<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crop Damages by Flood in Bangladesh Worse Than 1988 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The damage of crops by
devastating flood this year is feared to be at least three times
more than that caused by the 1988 floods since the duration of
flood this year has crossed all previous records, according to
experts.
</P>
<P>
Though the flood-affected area this year is smaller than that
of 1988, the crop loss is much bigger than in 1988.
</P>
<P>
A total of 60,000 square-kilometer area has been submerged by
floods this year, compared to 90,000 square kilometers in 1988,
The Daily Star newspaper Wednesday quoted experts in the
Meteorological Department as saying.
</P>
<P>
The flood water has this year been above the danger level for
about one month and a half since July 10 while it was only for 15
days in 1988, they noted.
</P>
<P>
The three major rivers -- Brahmaputra, Ganges and Meghna --
have been flowing above their respective danger marks since July
10 this year, but the rivers crossed their red marks on September
1 in 1988, they added.
</P>
<P>
Though the flood water had started receding, the rate of
recession was very slow and the process might take another 10 days
to be faster, they observed.
</P>
<P>
Crop loss might stand at three million tons this year, compared
to some one million tons in 1988, since 60 percent of rice crop
had been seriously affected by flood, an expert said.
</P>
<P>
In 1988, except some low-lying areas, rice crop withstood the
flood water because of its late advent and short duration, but
this year, the flood hit early and peasants in most of flood-hit
areas even could not plant rice seedlings because seed beds had
been damaged, he stated.
</P>
<P>
Crop on more than 214,000 hectares have been damaged and washed
away by nearly two-month-long devastating flood, with an estimated
crop loss amounting to 14.22 billion taka (302.6 million U.S.
dollars), the Ministry of Agriculture said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
