<HEADLINE> Rafter Survives, Graf Wins in U.S. Open First Round </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Defending champion Patrick
Rafter of Australia was almost crushed by an underdog from
Morocco in the first round of the U.S. Open tennis championships
tonight.
</P>
<P>
Third seed Rafter came back from two sets down to edge Hicham
Arazi 4-6, 4-6, 6-3, 6-3, 6-1 to survive an astonishing defeat.
Five time champion Steffi Graf of Germany battled past promising
American Corna Morariu 6-2, 3-6, 6-1 in a first round women's
match.
</P>
<P>
Never has a defending singles champion at the U.S. Open lost
in the first round, but the Australian almost made a history
tonight.It was the fourth time Rafter has rallied from a two-set
deficit to win and his ninth straight five-set win. He is 10-2
overall in five-setters.
</P>
<P>
Arazi appeared to be in control of what would have been by far
the biggest upset of the tournament's first two days, up two sets
and two points away from a 3-1 lead in the third.
</P>
<P>
But he came unglued after a line call went against him at that
point and argued repeately with umpire the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
Rafter, the ponytailed third best in the world, hurt himself
with mistakes in the first two sets but steadied as Arazi
unraveled.
</P>
<P>
"I hate umpires, guys in the chair, I hate them!" Arazi
screamed.
</P>
<P>
"Down 2-0 I figured I had a fine vacation coming, be able to
watch Pearl Jam," said Rafter, "But I hung in there and came
back."
</P>
<P>
Greg Rusedski, last year's runner-up and the sixth seed this
time, also survived a five-set battle with Wayne Ferreira 4-6,
7-6(7-2), 5-7, 7-6 (9-7), 6-4.
</P>
<P>
Today's action featured several top women players. Second
seed Lindsay Davenport of the United States routed Catalina
Cristea of Romania 6-0, 6-2. Jana Novotna, the Wimbledon champion
who is seeded third, fought off Jennifer Capriati of the United
States 6-4, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
Fourth seed Arantx Sanchez Vicario of Spain, the reigning
French Open champion, swept past Kristina Brandi of the United
States 6-2,6-2.
</P>
<P>
Fifth seed American Venus Williams, a finalist here last
year,became the last of the 16 seeded women to advance to the
second round as she breezed past Germany's Elena Wagner 6-1, 6-0.
</P>
<P>
Seventh seed Conchita Martinez of Spain ousted Miriam Oremans
of the Netherlans 6-1, 6-2; 10th seed Nathalie Tauziat of French
downed Flora Perfetti of Italy 6-3, 6-2; and 12th seed Mary
Pierce of France held off Meike Babel of Germany 6-1, 4-6, 6-2.
Anna Lournikova of Russia also sailed into the second round.
</P>
<P>
However, there was one seed ousted in the men's action today
when Oliver Gross of Germany outdueled No. 16 Albert Costa of
Spain 2-6, 4-6, 7-5, 6-2, 6-4. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
