<HEADLINE> New Zealand Sharemarket Bounces Back </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand sharemarket
 bounced back Wednesday after Tuesday's dramatic falls, with
investors rushing to take advantage of cheap prices of stocks.
</P>
<P>
According to the New Zealand Press Association (NZPA), the key
NZSE40 Capital Index gained 2.9 percent this morning, with early
trading dominated by price rises.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday, the NZSE40 Capital Index dropped 4 percent, with a
total of more than 1.5 billion New Zealand dollars (750 million
U.S. dollars) wiped off the value of New Zealand shares.
</P>
<P>
Today's boost for the New Zealand Sharemarket did not help
troubled Brierley Investments. The company's share price slumped
to a record low of 61 cents this morning from uncertainty about
the leadership and direction of the company, the NZPA reported.
</P>
<P>
But, the prices of most other leading stocks, including
Telecom, Colonial, Telstra, Air New Zealand, AMP and National
Mutual, rose this morning.
</P>
<P>
Auckland Airport's better-than-forecast profit result also gave
 its share price a boost.
</P>
<P>
But brokers remained nervous, saying markets were volatile and
volumes were light, the NZPA said.
</P>
<P>
It added that the performance of the New Zealand dollar and
interest rates was also good. This morning, the New Zealand dollar
was trading at 50.38 cents of the U.S. dollar, while wholesale
interest rates were hovering above six percent.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the New Zealand dollar hit 12-year lows, trading at
prices of slightly over 48 cents of the U.S. dollar. 
</P>
