<HEADLINE> Air Canada Pilots On Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The last-ditch talks between
Air Canada and its pilots failed at midnight Tuesday and the
pilots are officially on strike, local TV stations reported.
</P>
<P>
"Air Canada is forcing the 2,100 pilots on strike because of
the question of money," said Jean-Marc Belanger, chairman of the
Air Canada Pilots Association.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of Canada's largest airline and its pilots had
been staying up in a Toronto hotel Tuesday night to try to break
the impasse.
</P>
<P>
The pilots are demanding substantial pay increases and improved
working conditions. Air Canada has refused to make concessions.
</P>
<P>
"Flights are canceled until we are able to negotiate a
settlement and we can get the pilots back to work," said a
spokesperson of Air Canada.
</P>
<P>
The strike at the Montreal-based airline would ground its 166
planes and send many of its 22,000 employees home. It would also
disrupt traveling plans of many Canadians.
</P>
<P>
The airline is reported to have made arrangements with 15 other
air carriers around the world to take its passengers in the event
of a strike. 
</P>
</TEXT>
