<HEADLINE> Thai Cabinet Endorses Plans to Address Social Woes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Realizing the deteriorating
social problems, the Thai cabinet Tuesday approved the resolutions
proposed by the National Social Policy Committee to address the
social woes of the country, a government press release available
Wednesday said.
</P>
<P>
Under the proposed plan, one-stop service will be set up to
solve problems of people suffering from economic crisis at
provinces nationwide.
</P>
<P>
Priority will be given to badly-needed people such as
laid-offs, uneducated labor, aging women workers, and over one
year unemployed graduated.
</P>
<P>
The government also plans to speed up the business recovery
plan of the Small and Medium Enterprises at the provincial level
by assigning the Ministries of Commerce and Industry to consult
and coordinate with the Thai Chamber of Commerce, the Federation
of Industry of Thailand, and the Bank Association of Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet also approved to review the tax system in order to
reduce social gap of wealth distribution and to promote the
sufficiency consumption.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry is assigned to study the amendment of tax
system.
</P>
<P>
Unexploited land, inheritance, luxury goods, cigarettes, liquor
and lottery tickets may be more heavily taxed, while value-added
tax on necessary goods for the poors, elderly, underprivileged and
children, such as medicines, powdered milk, food produced by
farmer groups and local community organizations, will be reduced.
</P>
</TEXT>
