<HEADLINE> Kazakh President Names Security Chief to Combat Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Kazakh President Nursultan
Nazarbayev Tuesday appointed his chief adviser as the new security
chief in an effort to strengthen the ongoing national campaign
against corruption.
</P>
<P>
Nurtay Abykaev, 51, was appointed chairman of the State
Committee for National Security (SCNS) of Kazakhstan to replace
Alnur Mucaev, who was demoted to the rank of SCNS vice chairman,
the Kazakhstan Telegraph Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Nurtay Abykaev graduated from the Ural Institute of Political
Science and the Alma Ata Communist Party School, earning a
doctorate in economics. He served as the chief adviser to
President Nazarbayev before the appointment.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the appointment, Nazarbayev said the personnel
change was designed to strengthen the political force of the SCNS
to meet the needs of the ongoing anti-corruption campaign in the
country.
</P>
<P>
According to local media reports, there is widespread
corruption, including graft and bribery, in various fields in the
country. The issue of corruption reportedly presents a serious
problem to the national economy.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of this year, President Nazarbayev has
repeatedly emphasized the importance of the fight against
corruption and signed the Anti-Corruption Law. 
</P>
