<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT September 2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- The Economic Commission for Latin America and the
Caribbean (ECLA) Tuesday praised regional countries for keeping
inflation at a rate of about 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
In a report entitled "Economic Study of Latin America and the
Caribbean 1997-1998," the ECLA pointed out that the stability of
pricing was one of the regional countries' main economic
achievements.
</P>
<P>
It said that on an average, regional inflation fell from 18
percent in 1996, to about 10 percent in 1997, the second lowest in
half a century. (LATAM-Inflation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- The economies of Latin America and the Caribbean
will grow by nearly three percent in 1998, the Economic Commission
for Latin America and the Caribbean (ECLA) said in a report.
</P>
<P>
The report, entitled "Economic Study of Latin American and the
Caribbean," was issued Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
It said that 1997 was a very successful year for many economies
in the region, with 5.3 percent growth.
</P>
<P>
But external events, including the El Nino weather phenomenon
and the Asian financial crisis, may prevent the region's economies
from growing that rapidly this year, said the
report. (LATAM-Economic Growth)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LOS ANGELES -- Boeing announced Tuesday that it had ousted the
chief of its commercial airplane operation who failed to meet the
company's expectations.
</P>
<P>
"We have experienced unsatisfactory financial performance with
our commercial airplane operations," Boeing chairman and CEO Phil
Condit said in a statement. "Our expectations are that commercial
airplane operations produce significant, double-digit operating
margins. We conclude there must be significant changes in the
composition of the management team at this time."
</P>
<P>
Ron Woodard, 55, the president of Boeing's beleaguered
Commercial Airplane Group, has been replaced by Alan Mulally, the
53-year-old chief of Boeing's defense and space group.
</P>
<P>
The dramatic move was the first time in recent memory that an
airplane-division president has been removed at the 82-year-old
company. (Boeing-Sack)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russia will continue to build a market economy, but
could reimpose state control on the economy to lessen its
financial crisis, Russian President Boris Yeltsin said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Interfax news agency, quoting Kremlin sources, said Yeltsin
made the remark during his meeting with visiting U.S. President
Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, who is in Moscow for a two-day summit with Yeltsin,
said the United States would continue to support Russia as long as
it continues its reforms.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin assured Clinton that his country will not step back
from reforms despite the grave economic situation, Interfax
reported. (Russia-Economy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Transactions in the Russian stock market tapered to
almost zero Tuesday as traders try to come to terms with the
country's political uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
No deals were made on the Russian Trading System early Tuesday
as President Boris Yeltsin resubmitted his nomination of Viktor
Chernomyrdin as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
But Gennady Seleznyov, speaker of the State Duma, or lower
house of parliament, said the nomination would be shot down in the
second round of voting.
</P>
<P>
Quotations for leading stocks shed 15 percent to 30 percent in
the first 20 minutes, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The RTS-Interfax Composite Index in rubles, however, actually
rose by 12.55 percent to 23.6 by 11:25 local time (07:25 GMT), as
exchange rate for the ruble against foreign currencies further
plummeted. (Russia-Stocks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR -- Malaysia's ringgit will be pegged by Bank
Negara (State Bank) to a fixed rate very soon, Malaysian Prime
Minister Mahathir Mohamad said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
With a fixed rate, people will know the real value of the
ringgit and "once we regain control of our exchange rate, we can
lower our interest rates and nobody else control our interest
rates," Mahathir said during a special interview on the country's
economic situation over radio and television which was telecast
live.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said a fixed ringgit might affect transaction costs
but with fixed rates, there was no need to hedge while the
transaction cost will not be subject to devaluation or revaluation
if paid at a later date, and also it would enable interest rates
to be lowered.
</P>
<P>
But the rate will be decided by market forces for the time
being, he said. (Malaysia-Currency) 
</P>
</TEXT>
