<HEADLINE> Bulgaria's Lev Up Further </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The Bulgarian lev edged up
further to 1,738-1,739 to the U.S. dollar on Tuesday, up from
Monday's 1,757-1,758 lev to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
The increasing demand for foreign exchange caused by the rise
of lev has pushed up the Deutsch mark against the lev to one for
996.50-995.50, said a dealer.
</P>
<P>
The lev may strengthen to 1,720-1,730 if the dollar continues
to drop against the mark, while the level of one mark to 997 levs
was impossible, a Raiffeisenbank dealer said.
</P>
<P>
An ING bank dealer said that even financial experts could not
understand events in the markets because the volatile situation in
Russia made any forecasts impossible.
</P>
<P>
Bulgarian Brady bonds partially reclaimed their positions in
the international markets Tuesday though their price rose seven to
eight percentage points from Monday, said a Bulbank dealer.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Tuesday the governor of the central bank Svetoslav
Gavriiski refused to comment on the possibility of Bulgaria
repaying a share of its external debt while the Brady bonds were
low.
</P>
<P>
He also refused to reveal whether Bulgarian banks in Russia had
been hit by the crisis there.
</P>
<P>
A Bulgarian-Russian Investment Bank official was quoted by the
Bulgarian Telegraph Agency as saying: "We have become very careful
and minimized our activity in the Russian market."  
</P>
