<DOCNO> XIE19980902.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Cabinet Okays Plan on State Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The Thai cabinet Tuesday
approved a master plan to streamline the process of privatization
of state-owned enterprises, a government press release available
Wednesday said.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, one panel under the prime minister would take
over all charge of the selling-off of state enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The State Enterprise Policy Committee is presently chaired by
Supachai Panitchpakdi, deputy prime minister, while new State
Enterprise Reform Committee would soon be established.
</P>
<P>
According to the press release, the goal of the master plan is
"to increase the efficiency of the economy, to provide a basis
from which Thai companies can compete internationally, and to
ensure quality goods and services are available to the Thai public
at the least cost."
</P>
<P>
Under the master plan, the state will look to "exit" from
enterprise operations.
</P>
<P>
"The state's role will primarily be as policy maker and
regulator, ensuring public goods and services are properly
delivered, protecting consumers, and providing a level playing
field for active competition between private sector entities," the
press release said.
</P>
<P>
However, the state will maintain its role in investment related
to national development such as in public health and education.
</P>
<P>
A wide variety of methods of privatization may be used by
enterprises and the state to accomplish the reform objectives.
This includes divestiture, deregulation, and licensing of private
sector participants.
</P>
<P>
Private parties wishing to invest in state enterprises would be
required to negotiate with the appropriate ministry or the State
Enterprise Office.
</P>
<P>
The government also plans to legislate to ensure smooth
implementation for fear that existing laws would complicate the
process and amendments would cause delays.
</P>
<P>
The proceeds of the privatization would be split equally, with
the first half being used to fund needed social services such as
education, public health, labor welfare and agriculture, and the
other half for repayment of loans to Financial Institutions
Development Fund.
</P>
<P>
There are 59 state enterprises in Thailand, which can be
broadly categorized into five major sectors: telecommunication,
water, energy, transport and others.
</P>
<P>
The total number of state owned enterprise employees currently
stands at about 320,000, with the top ten largest entities
employing over 226,000 individuals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980902.0257 </DOCNO>
