<HEADLINE> Education for All Programme Carried out in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar has been carrying out
Education for All Programme laid down by the World Education
Conference held in Thailand in 1990, a senior Myanmar official
said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The programme is being implemented in the country as a national
task with the aims of providing education for all, Myanmar Deputy
Minister for Education Brigadier-General Soe Win Maung said on
Tuesday at a Non-formal Education Work Committee meeting under the
Education for All Programme, the official newspaper New Light of
Myanmar reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He stated that Myanmar aims at ensuring 80 per cent of the
people complete the primary education and reducing the adult
illiteracy rate from 22 per cent to 11 by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Non-formal education is extensive since it involves vocational
programmes and income generation for adults in addition to
literacy work, and follow-up programmes for neo-literates are to
be undertaken, Soe Win Maung stressed.
</P>
<P>
A total of 180,035 persons are attending 12,674 classes in 104
townships under Non-formal Education Programme in the whole
country.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar's adult illiteracy rate has been gradually brought down
to 29 per cent in 1973 and further to the present 22 per cent
thanks to a literacy drive launched in the country in 1964.
</P>
<P>
The national literacy rate of women has gone up to 71.3 percent
in the past ten years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
