<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Opinion Poll Confirms Tight Election Race in Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Results of a new poll
released here Wednesday confirmed that the two main Australian
parties were running a tight race for voter support even before
the election campaign began this week.
</P>
<P>
The results of the poll published by Bulletin, the nation's
weekly news magazine, shows that 40 percent of voters favored the
Australian Labor Party, with 36 percent voters favored the ruling
coalition and six percent undecided.
</P>
<P>
The ruling coalition consists of the Australian Liberal Party,
which represents the nation's industrial and business groups, and
the Australian National Party that represents Australian farmers.
</P>
<P>
But the Bulletin said it had adopted a new style of opinion
testing for the election campaign that showed the coalition could
pick up more votes than Labor from undecided voters.
</P>
<P>
About a third of the undecided voters described themselves as
leaning towards the Liberal Party while 15 percent favored the
Labor Party.
</P>
<P>
The poll gave five percent of the primary vote to One Nation
Party with only three percent of undecided voters saying they
could support it.
</P>
<P>
The Bulletin poll contrasts with a Newspoll conducted for The
Australian, the nation's leading newspaper, also taken at the
weekend, that showed the coalition and the Labor Party both
enjoyed the support from 40 percent of the voters polled, with 10
percent voters for the One Nation Party founded last year by
racist MP Pauline Hanson.
</P>
<P>
It is feared Pauline Hanson's party may hold the balance of
power in parliament to be elected, which would enable the party to
exert substantial influence on Australia's politics.
</P>
<P>
Australian Prime Minister John Howard announced on August 30
that a federal election would be held on October 3.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
