<HEADLINE> Venezuelan Doctors Start Strike for Higher Pay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Over 2,000 doctors in public
institutions in the Venezuelan capital of Caracas went on strike
for higher pay on Tuesday morning, stopping services in least 20
hospitals and more than 600 clinics.
</P>
<P>
The doctors are calling for a basic wage of 600,000 bolivares
(some 1,050 U.S. dollars) and urging the government to block the
health and social security law and to keep open the Venezuelan
Institute of Social Security.
</P>
<P>
The doctors also complained about a lack of hospital materials
and the scarcity of medicines.
</P>
<P>
The Venezuelan government dismissed their complaints as
senseless. Labor Minister Maria Bernardoni warned that if
emergency cases were not attended to during the strike, the
government might issue a compulsory order for all doctors to
return to work.
</P>
<P>
The medical strike is expected to spread to other states,
including Lara, Sucre, Zulia, Tachira, Yaracuy and Miranda,
according to local media reports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
