<DOCNO> XIE19980902.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECLA: Latin American Economies to Grow 3 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The economies of Latin
America and the Caribbean will grow by nearly three percent in
1998, the Economic Commission for Latin America and the Caribbean
(ECLA) said in a report.
</P>
<P>
The report, entitled "Economic Study of Latin American and the
Caribbean," was issued Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
It said that 1997 was a very successful year for many economies
in the region, with 5.3 percent growth.
</P>
<P>
But external events, including the El Nino weather phenomenon
and the Asian financial crisis, may prevent the region's economies
from growing that rapidly this year, said the report.
</P>
<P>
It predicted that unemployment in the region may increase and
inflation, which dropped in 1997, will rise to 10.9 percent by the
end of the year.
</P>
<P>
Deficits are expected to grow to a total of 75 billion
U.S. dollars, which represents 3.7 percent of gross domestic
products (GDP), compared to 3.2 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
El Nino has caused catastrophic floods and droughts in the
region, damaging agricultural products as well as fishing
production.
</P>
<P>
It also resulted in low economic growth rates, higher inflation
and pressures on the balance of payments, due to export
contractions and the import growth, added the report.
</P>
<P>
Asia's financial crisis is having another negative impact on
the region's economy. It has caused a reduction in foreign trade
volume and a fall in export prices.
</P>
<P>
The region's finances have been also affected by speculation on
the money and stock exchanges.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the rapid and vigorous reaction from the regional
governments, the impacts on the region have been "relatively
moderate."
</P>
<P>
But the report warned countries in the region to maintain a
cautious attitude toward their economies as the Asian crisis could
last longer than expected and new problems such as in Russia could
appear. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
