<HEADLINE> Venezuelan Oil Company Cuts Investment to Shore Up Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Venezuela's oil company, the
PDVSA, has decided to cut 10 billion U.S. dollars in investments
from its expansion plan in an effort to shore up dwindling oil
prices on the international market, the local press reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A company source told the local media that original projections
were calculated at 65 billion U.S. dollars, but were revised
downward to 55 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The PDVSA's expansion plan is based on a 10-year schedule,
which starts in 1999 and ends in 2008. Its objective is to create
new market opportunities via production.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2001, it expects to raise oil production between
4.4 to 4.7 million barrels per day. By the year 2008, this amount
will increase to 5.5 to 6.4 million barrels per day.
</P>
<P>
Investment reduction, originally drafted in the expansion plan
of PDVSA, is one of the consequences of the government's decision
to cut oil production by 525,000 barrels per day to 2.8 million
barrels per day.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of this strategy, agreed upon at the Organization
of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC), is to stabilize oil
prices in the international marketplace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
