<HEADLINE> Beijing's Foreign Trade Thrives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Beijing's imports and exports
reached 3.46 billion US dollars in January-June, increasing by 13
percent over that of the first seven months of 1997, today's
"China Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
The paper cited satistics from Beijing Customs as that exports
jumped 20.7 percent to 1.6 billion US dollars and imports went up
by 7.3 percent to reach 1.86 billion US dollars in the first seven
months.
</P>
<P>
Statistics showed that State-owned enterprises have occupied a
leading role in the city's exports, and foreign-funded firms'
exports showed increasing potential.
</P>
<P>
Beijing's export commodities structure has been optimized in
the first seven months. Primary product exports went down by 10.3
percent to 105 million US dollars, which industrial product
exports jumped by 23.8 percent to reach 1.49 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Due to the Asian financial turmoil, Beijing's exports to Asean
countries dipped by 13.8 percent to 79.45 million US
dollars. Meanwhile, the city is actively making contact with other
markets to achieve a sustained growth of its exports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
