<HEADLINE> Strong German Team to Compete at Athletics World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Eight European champions
form the nucleus of a powerful German team at the athletics World
Cup tournament in Johannesburg next week, South African Press
Association reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Germany, which won the lion's share of 23 medals at the recent
European Championships, sends a team including some of the
greatest athletes of all time to the eighth International Amateur
Athletic Federation (IAAF) World Cup from September 11 to 13.
</P>
<P>
Among the team are Tanja Damaske, a 70m women's javelin
thrower,Tim Lobringer, who has cleared 6m in the pole vault, Lars
Riedel, a legend discus thrower and Heike Drechsler, one of the
world's best women long jumpers.
</P>
<P>
Riedel has claimed an Olympic gold medal and four world titles
in the discus. The 31-year-old, whose personal best is 71.50m,
rose to the occasion once again at the European Championships
with a winning throw of 67.07m.
</P>
<P>
Drechsler, who has a personal best of 7.48m, is the only
athlete at the World Cup with the ability to give sprint
sensation Marion Jones of the United States a go in the long jump.
</P>
<P>
Jones, who has run the world's fastest 10.71 seconds in the
100m this year, is building up to an assault on the world record
of 10.49 seconds on the fast high altitude track when she
competes in the 100m on September 12.
</P>
<P>
Other German athletes who struck gold at the European
Championships and will participate in the South African World Cup
are Nils Schumann(800m in 1:44.89), Damien Kallabis (3000m
steeplechase in 8:13.10),Grit Breuer (400m in 49.93 seconds and
member of the German 4x400m relay team), and Franka Dietsch
(women's discus). 
</P>
