<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Big Merger Reported in China's Liqueur-Producing Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Two major liqueur producers in
southwest China's Guizhou Province, the China Guizhou Maotai
Liqueur (Group) Co. Ltd. and the Guizhou Xijiu Liqueur
Association, merged here recently.
</P>
<P>
Maotai, known as China's "national liqueur", has remained
popular among consumers. However, the Maotai Group has for quite a
long time failed to produce the liqueur in large  quantities to
meet the demands of domestic and overseas customers.
</P>
<P>
The Guizhou association has been operating at a loss for years
with some 600 million yuan worth of facilities lying idle.
</P>
<P>
At the request of the local government, the Maotai Group sent
10 managers to the Xijiu association and invested 4.5 million yuan
in the nearby firm, which helped improve its management and
enlarge the consumer market in the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
Yuan Renguo, general manager of the Maotai Group, said the
merger increases the Maotai Group's total asset value to 2.34
billion yuan, up from 1.74 billion yuan, and its annual production
capacity is expected to jump to 20,000 tons, up from the present
4,000 tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980902.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Rules to Cut Car Emissions in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 2 (Xinhua) -- A new set of standards for
vehicle emissions will be implemented in Beijing next year, aiming
to cut 80 percent of the main pollutants in new cars' exhaust
fumes.
</P>
<P>
Today's China Daily quoted Yu Xiaoxuan, deputy-director of the
Beijing Environmental Protection Bureau, as saying that this set
of standards would be the strictest local emission regulations in
the country.
</P>
<P>
If the new cars do not meet the new standards, they would not
be allowed to be sold or licensed in the city, according to the
newspaper. Every year more than 100,000 new vehicles hit the
roads in the city.
</P>
<P>
An official with the Beijing Environmental Protection Bureau
said current emission standards were at about the same level as
those in Europe during the 1970s. The new standards would match
European ones from around 1992.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that 74 percent of hydrocarbons, 63 percent of
carbon monoxide and 37 percent of the nitrogen oxides in the
city's air come from vehicle exhaust.
</P>
<P>
Yu said emissions became a problem because the current
standards on car exhausts were not strict enough, allowing a
single car to discharge more pollutants than it should, because
automobiles on the road lacked maintenance, and road conditions
lag behind the rapid increase in automobile numbers.
</P>
<P>
To enforce the new standards, cars will have environmental
equipment that includes electronically controlled ignitions and
catalytic converters, said Yu.
</P>
<P>
At present, only unleaded petroleum is being sold in
Beijing. According to statistics from the State Environmental
Protection Administration, by June of 1998, a total of 17
provinces and cities adopted unleaded petroleum regulations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
