<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Published Japanese Photos Illustrate War Crimes in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, September 2 (Xinhua) -- A recently discovered
collection of photos published by Japan 60 years ago provides
additional evidence of crimes committed by Japanese invaders
against China in the late 1930s.
</P>
<P>
Xu Li, a retired cadre in his 70s, bought a Japan-published
album half a century ago. He recently donated the rare document to
the archives museum in Yangzhou, east China's Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
With a brown hard cover, the album includes more than 200
pictures taken by Japanese war correspondents showing collapsed
city walls, destroyed houses and buildings, and demolished streets.
</P>
<P>
The photo collection was published in 1938 when Japan conquered
several major Chinese cities, including Shanghai, Suzhou, Nanjing
and Wuhan.
</P>
<P>
"Japanese militarists hoped to make a show of its armed forces
by publishing such a collection," said an expert in the Nanjing
Museum.
</P>
<P>
He mentioned that the collection has a Japan-made Chinese map,
on which Japan divided the northern parts of northwest China's
Shaanxi Province and Ningxia region out of China and labeled
"leased territories" on Taiwan and Hong Kong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980902.0283 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhejiang's Electronic Information Industry Grows Rapidly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The electronic information
industry of east China's Zhejiang Province maintained rapid
growth in the first half of this year, official figures indicate.
</P>
<P>
The industry generated 13.69 billion yuan of output value in
the period, up 22.66 percent from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Early this year, Zhejiang said it will complete an effort
to restructure the product mix of its electronic information
industry and digitalize these products in about three years.
</P>
<P>
An official source said Zhejiang will invest 908.5 million yuan
this year in 98 key technical research and development projects
focused on electronic digitalization and networking.
</P>
<P>
Despite the mounting impact of the Asian financial crisis,
Zhejiang's electronic enterprises delivered 2.83 billion yuan in
exports and reported a sales volume of 9.23 billion yuan in the
first half of this year, up 25.6 percent and 15.7 percent,
respectively, from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
This sector's profits for the six-month period totaled 729
million yuan, roughly the same as that of last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
