<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lions Clubs Aid China's Blind with Eye Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Lions Clubs International
(LCI) yesterday celebrated the first anniversary of Sight First
China Action, its ambitious cooperative program with the Chinese
government to restore eyesight to 1.75 million Chinese and assist
Chinese eye clinics, according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Club President Kajit Habanananda presented a check of four
million US dollars to Wang Longde, vice-minister of health and
Deng Pufang, chairman of the China Disabled Person's Federation as
the second installment of the organization's contribution of 15.3
million US dollars for the five-year Sight First China Action
project.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government and the LCI signed a ground-breaking
agreement in August 1997, making Lions Clubs the first
international service organization to work in cooperation with
China on a nationwide program.
</P>
<P>
Wang Longde said 24 medical teams have been sent to 172
poverty-stricken counties in 19 provinces to do cataract
surgeries. And 348,000 cases of sight-restoring surgery have been
conducted around the country since the launch of the project last
September.
</P>
<P>
The project will dispatch a total of 250 medical teams to
rural, remote and poverty-stricken areas to conduct cataract
surgery. Also, 4,000 ophthalmologists and 7,000 clinical
assistants will be trained, according to Wang. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
