<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Garuda Indonesia to lay off 3,000 Employees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 2 (Xinhua) -- Troubled national flag carrier
Garuda Indonesia will lay off at least 3,000 of its nearly 13,000
employees as early as next month as part of a massive
restructuring program, the airline's president, Robby Djohan, said
here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The dismissals, starting in early October, would be just one of
several moves designed to enable the airline to survive the
deepening crisis, the Jakarta Post daily Wednesday quoted Robby as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Garuda is one of the East Asian airlines that are suffering
from weak sales and ballooning costs denominated in foreign
currencies. Indonesia's economic crisis and the collapse of the
rupiah currency has hurt the airline badly.
</P>
<P>
As of last July, Garuda had a total of 12,732 employees,
including 709 pilots.
</P>
<P>
Robby said last Friday that Garuda current ratio of employees
to aircraft was 273 to one -- much higher than the ideal ratio of
167 to each airplane. Garuda currently operates 50 aircraft.
</P>
<P>
He said the airline needed at least 100 million U.S. dollars in
financing to help the company move forward with its restructuring
plans.
</P>
<P>
The airline also plans to switch to Boeing 737-300 planes from
other aircraft now being used for domestic routes to improve
efficiency and cut costs, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
