<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Finnish Government Unveils 1999 Draft Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The Finnish government
presented its draft 1999 budget, which aims to get the country out
of the red for the first time in a decade, to parliament on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The budget forecasts 187.1 billion Finnish marks (34.56 billion
U.S. dollars) in state revenue and 186.83 billion marks (34.6
billion dollars) in expenditure, with a small favorable balance of
270 million marks (50 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The government's retrenchment measures include trimming the
state-subsidized housing program, putting off certain public
infrastructure projects and cutting back administration and
defense expenditures.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the government is committed to increasing
investment in scientific research and personnel training.
</P>
<P>
The 1999 budget is mainly focussed on ensuring sustained
economic growth and creating jobs, the government stressed.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Paavo Lipponen said the new budget would be
historic, as he expected it to put an end to Finland's ever
increasing debts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
