<HEADLINE> China to Send Young Soccer Team for Asian Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 2 (Xinhua) -- China is set to send its
under-23 soccer side to compete at this year's Asian Games in
Thailand, national team boss Bob Houghton said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Football Association (CFA) has yet to confirm the
news but said the formal announcement would come shortly.
</P>
<P>
The forthcoming decision will be welcomed by the Asian
Football Confederation (AFC), who is recommending an under-23
rule on the soccer tournament of the Asian Games.
</P>
<P>
AFC secretary general Peter Velappan said in July that the
event should be a showcase for the continent's young talents but
added that the final decision rests with each nation's soccer
association.
</P>
<P>
It would be a fitting move given both Japan and South Korea,
the main contenders for the Games soccer title, had announced to
field an under-23 Olympic side for the tournament, Houghton said
at the national team's training camp in the northeastern Chinese
city Dalian.
</P>
<P>
Also, the Bangkok Games, slated from September 6 to 20, will
provide useful competitive chances to the young side before they
kick off their 2000 Olympics soccer qualifying campaign, the
Englishman said. 
</P>
