<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy's Education Expenditures Rank Lowest in Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Italy's education expenditures,
which is reportedly the lowest amount in its national budget,
ranks last among the European countries, press reports said on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The reports said Italy's expenditure in public education has
fallen from 67.882 trillion lire (39 billion U.S. dollars) in 1993
to 59.594 trillion lire (35 billion dollars) in 1997, which
accounts for 3.4 percent of its total gross national product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
The fall was the fastest and greatest among European
countries. Few countries in Europe cut their money in public
education on so great a scale as Italy, while most increased their
spending.
</P>
<P>
Finland's public education expenditure, which was the greatest
amount in its budget, amounted to about 7.9 percent of the GDP and
first place in Europe. It was followed by Sweden, 6.8 percent,
Denmark, 6.7 percent, France, 5.9 percent, Germany, 4.9 percent
and Britain, 4.1 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980902.0296 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rufer voted Oceania's Player of the Century </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Former New Zealand striker
Wynton Rufer has been voted Oceania's player of the century in a
poll of the region's soccer writers and experts.
</P>
<P>
Rufer played for New Zealand in the 1982 World Cup finals in
Spain and won domestic titles in Germany, Switzerland and Japan.
</P>
<P>
He helped Germany's Werder Bremen win the European Cup
Winners' Cup in 1982 and was voted Oceania's player of the year
three times.
</P>
<P>
The poll by the International Federation of Football History
and Statistics gave Rufer a commanding lead over his nearest
challenger, 1980s Australian striker Frank Farina. 
</P>
</TEXT>
