<HEADLINE> Edwards Aims for World Cup Spot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Triple jump world
record-holder Jonathan Edwards of Britain still has a slim chance
of making the World Cup team, according to the Britain's
athletics association on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The European gold medallist said last week he would not jump
again this season after picking up an ankle injury.
</P>
<P>
But he was not replaced when the selectors named the men's
team for the one-man per event championship in Johannesburg
between September 11-13.
</P>
<P>
"Jonathan wants to give himself every chance of competing in
South Africa," said British athletics spokeswoman Jayne Pearce.
"We will just have to see what happens."
</P>
<P>
But reigning Commonwealth champion Julian Golley has been
placed on stand-by for the competition.
</P>
<P>
And it would be a major surprise if Edwards is fit enough for
either the World Cup or the Commonwealth Games in Kuala Lumpur a
few days later.
</P>
<P>
Two withdrawals were confirmed by the selectors, however.
</P>
<P>
John Mayock and Mark Richardson pulled out of the 1,500m and
4x400m relay respectively, with both opting to concentrate on the
Commonwealth Games instead.
</P>
<P>
Mayock's place goes to Tony Whiteman, who switches from the
3,000m and is replaced by Neil Caddy, while Richardson's berth
will not be filled.
</P>
<P>
The only other change sees European 200m silver medallist Doug
Turner replace Doug Walker, who underwent knee surgery after
winning the Budapest title. 
</P>
</TEXT>
