<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Company to Explore Wind-Power Resources in Xinjiang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The Tang Energy Group, Ltd. of
the United States will invest some 40 million U.S. dollars to
build two wind-power generating fields in northwest China's
Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region in cooperation with a local
wind-power company.
</P>
<P>
According to an agreement signed recently between the two
companies, the projected wind-power generating fields, each with
an installed capacity of 20,000 kw, will use 600-kw wind-driven
generators developed by the Xinjiang Wind Power Company and
already in use for wind-driven power generation in some areas of
the region.
</P>
<P>
The Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region abounds in wind-power
resources with nine major wind zones with a combined area of more
than 150,000 sq km. These zones have the potential of producing a
over 800 billion kw/hours of electricity annually.
</P>
<P>
The Xinjiang Wind Power Company is engaged in high-tech
research, and last year signed a contract with the Jacobs Company
of Germany for the transfer of technology and spare parts to build
600-kw wind-driven generators.
</P>
<P>
The Tang Energy Group is mainly engaged in the petroleum and
natural gas industries. The jointly invested wind-power generating
fields will be the company's first investment project in
wind-power generation.
</P>
<P>
E. Patrick Jenevein III, president of the Texas-based Tang
Energy Group, said there are broad prospects for exploring and
utilizing wind-power resources in Xinjiang with the strong support
of state policies governing wind-power exploration in China.
</P>
<P>
He said he hopes to build more new wind-power generating fields
in other places in China on the basis of this cooperation with
Xinjiang. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
