<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PFA Supports Adams in Book Row </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The Professional
Footballers'Association (PFA) has given its hands to support Tony
Adams over the Arsenal captain's criticism of Glenn Hoddle in his
new book.
</P>
<P>
Adams, former England captain, accused the England coach in
his book of making mistakes during the World Cup and treating the
players"like kids".
</P>
<P>
But PFA deputy chief executive Brendan Batson said Adams was
entitled to give his side of the story -- particularly after
Hoddle had himself published a "kick-and-tell" book.
</P>
<P>
"After Glenn's book it is now open season," said Batson.
</P>
<P>
"I understand that Tony is just expressing his own opinions
and that he has not revealed anything of a confidential nature
between the manager and the players."
</P>
<P>
Former England manager Bobby Robson agreed players and
managers should be allowed to publish books -- but he warned they
should be wary about being too controversial.
</P>
<P>
"I believe Glenn Hoddle has the right to write a book if he
wants," Robson said.
</P>
<P>
"But he must be very careful what he says because he has to
stand or fall on what he writes. The same is true of Tony Adams,"
</P>
<P>
In his book, Addicted, Adams also criticises Hoddle for
picking Alan Shearer ahead of him as captain; humiliating David
Beckham in front of players at training and encouraging Paul
Gascoigne to drink the night before he was axed from the England
squad.
</P>
<P>
Adams also revealed in the book his fight with alcohol and his
spell in prison for drink-driving.
</P>
<P>
According to local reports on Tuesday, the publication of the
book would not harm the relationship between Adams and Hoddle,
who is now preparing for a European Championship qualifier
against Sweden on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Hoddle has already said that whatever appeared in print would
not affect his belief that Adams will remain a key player in the
England set-up for years yet.
</P>
<P>
"I'm really not worried about it," insisted Hoddle last week.
</P>
<P>
The Football Association also insisted there is "no
problem"between Hoddle and Adams. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
