<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing Sacks Commercial Airplane Group Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Boeing announced Tuesday
that it had ousted the chief of its commercial airplane operation
who failed to meet the company's expectations.
</P>
<P>
"We have experienced unsatisfactory financial performance with
our commercial airplane operations," Boeing chairman and CEO Phil
Condit said in a statement. "Our expectations are that commercial
airplane operations produce significant, double-digit operating
margins. We conclude there must be significant changes in the
composition of the management team at this time."
</P>
<P>
Ron Woodard, 55, the president of Boeing's beleaguered
Commercial Airplane Group, has been replaced by Alan Mulally, the
53-year-old chief of Boeing's defense and space group.
</P>
<P>
The dramatic move was the first time in recent memory that an
airplane-division president has been removed at the 82-year-old
company.
</P>
<P>
According to Seattle Times, the action comes as Condit faces
tremendous pressure from directors and shareholders angry about
the company's plummeting stock price and weak performance. Despite
a record boom in airplane orders and production rates, the world's
largest aircraft manufacturer reported a loss of 178 million U.S.
dollars last year because of production problems and excessive
costs. Boeing's stock has plummeted by almost 20 dollars a share
from its trading high point in mid-July, costing investors more
than 19.4 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Woodard joined Boeing in 1966 as a research chemist and was
named president of the Commercial Airplane Group in 1993. He has
been viewed as an aggressive, competitive manager, openly hungry
for risk.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
