<HEADLINE> Air Canada, Pilots Continue Talks to Avert Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Air Canada and its pilots
continued their last-ditch talks, trying to avert a crippling
strike scheduled at midnight Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of Canada's largest airline and its 2,100
pilots gathered in a Toronto hotel Tuesday afternoon to try to
break the impasse.
</P>
<P>
The pilots are demanding substantial pay increases and improved
working conditions. Air Canada has refused to cave in.
</P>
<P>
A strike at the Montreal-based airline would ground its 166
planes and send many of its 22,000 employees home. It would also
disrupt travelling plans of many Canadians.
</P>
<P>
The airline was reported to be preparing to cancel flights, but
no decisions about cancellations have yet been made by Tuesday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
It had made arrangements with 15 other air carriers around the
world to take its passengers in the event of a strike, the reports
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
