<HEADLINE> Experts Stress Prevention, Intervention to Combat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Law enforcement and
criminal justice experts told a U.S. Senate panel Tuesday that
reducing youth violence will require both tough punishment and
prevention and intervention programs.
</P>
<P>
David E. Grossman, presiding administrative judge in Hamilton
County, Ohio, said many courts could do better if they had trained
staff, improved facilities and more resources. Many cannot assess
the youth crime problem in their areas because data isn't
available, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Early intervention. Absolutely," Grossman told the Senate
Judiciary's youth violence subcommittee. "But in order to do that,
we need the resources to accomplish it."
</P>
<P>
Harry Shorstein, a Jacksonville, Florida, state attorney,
advocated a two-pronged approach involving incarceration for
serious teen offenders and early intervention for youngsters
before, and after, they show tendencies of heading toward a life
of crime.
</P>
<P>
Shorstein has assigned prosecutors to each of the 22 middle
schools in his jurisdiction, prosecutes "serious habitual"
juvenile offenders as adults and fights truancy by targeting
parents who don't send their kids to school.
</P>
<P>
"It is not punishment or prevention," said Shorstein, whose
efforts have received national attention. "The answer is
punishment and prevention, early intervention working together."
</P>
<P>
A juvenile crime bill passed by the House of Representatives in
1997 would toughen federal laws dealing with teen crime, including
trying many offenders as adults, and provide strong incentives for
states to do the same. A companion bill, however, has stalled in
the Senate.
</P>
<P>
Senator Jeff Sessions, the Republican chairman of the
subcommittee chairman, said the government spends four billion
dollars a year on prevention programs, some of which aren't
producing results.
</P>
<P>
He said "the most effective way to prevent serious juvenile
crime is to focus on the juvenile who has committed his first
delinquent act."
</P>
<P>
But he also said "the debate we are facing in Congress today is
whether to dedicate any money to juvenile intervention and law
enforcement." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
