<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Russia to Stay on Reform Course </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Visiting U.S. President Bill
Clinton said Tuesday that Washington will stick with Russians if
they continue on the reform course.
</P>
<P>
"Today's financial crisis does not require you to abandon your
march toward freedom and free markets," Clinton said in a speech
delivered at the Moscow Institute of Foreign Relations, Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
He said Russia must bring to completion the changes it started
seven years ago.
</P>
<P>
"Every choice Russia makes today may have consequences for
years and years to come," Clinton told the Russians, who witnessed
their national currency devaluation, prices shot-up and inflation
soar in the past few weeks.
</P>
<P>
However, he urged the Russians not to retreat from their chosen
course.
</P>
<P>
He urged the Russian government to pursue stable revenues
through a healthy taxation system, and to refrain from printing
more money to pay the bills and bail out the banks.
</P>
<P>
He also called for equal treatment in the country's efforts to
help people tide over the difficulties, both to its own citizens
and foreign creditors.
</P>
<P>
"The people who loan money into this country must be treated
fairly if you want them to be loaning money into this nation four
years, five years, ten years hence."
</P>
<P>
Prior to the speech, Clinton met with Russian President Boris
Yeltsin in the Kremlin, their first full-scale summit since March
1997.
</P>
<P>
He is scheduled to have more talks with Yeltsin as well as
leaders of the country's political parties and movements
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Despite his reiteration of "unconditional support" for Russia,
Clinton did not speak about any specific forms of financial and
economic assistance.
</P>
<P>
Clinton is scheduled to leave Russia Thursday and fly on to
Ireland and the British province of Northern Ireland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
