<HEADLINE> Millennium Bug to Slow down World Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The millennium bug will slow
down significantly the growth of the British and world economy,
UK's NatWest Group warned.
</P>
<P>
NatWest has cut its growth forecast for the UK and the rest of
the world saying that Russia, already buffeted by economic
turmoil, will be among the worst affected by the date transfer
problem.
</P>
<P>
The bug will cut the growth of the UK economy by 0.5 percent
points to 1.9 percent in the year 2000, according to the forecast
by David Kern, chief economist at NatWest's market intelligence
group.
</P>
<P>
The damage of the bug will be more severe in other areas with
growth in Asia, Russia and other former Soviet countries down 0.9
percent and growth in Eastern Europe, Latin America and the
Pacific countries down 0.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Kern warned that if the millennium bug coincided with further
economic downturn in Russia and other developing markets, the
situation could be "much worse than currently envisaged".
</P>
<P>
Although governments and business worldwide are spending
billions to solve the problem, Kern warned that the bug will cause
enough glitches in computer systems, which will result in
inefficiency of the economy.
</P>
<P>
"This is not just a computer problem, it is a macro-economic
problem as well." he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
