<DOCNO> XIE19980902.0319 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Stock Markets Close Mixed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Battered European shares were
pulled in both directions when Wall Street gyrated wildly in its
first hour of business on Tuesday, but as the Dow Jones settled
down, the European bourses managed to regain some ground.
</P>
<P>
London shares recovered in afternoon trading to end just 1.5
percent down, with the FTSE closing down 80.3 points at 5169.1.
But it could have been a lot worse in another volatile day's
trading, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
At one point the FTSE index of leading shares had tumbled more
than 170 points as fears grew that the Russian financial crisis
would drag Western economies into recession. But shares recovered
as New York stocks rallied after a dreadful day on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Dealers remain nervous as they digest the implications of the
political and economic crisis that has swept through emerging
markets.
</P>
<P>
The Russian political crisis has deepened since London stocks
were traded last week. The country now goes into its second week
without a government.
</P>
<P>
The Russian concerns and fears that Latin American economies
will be the next to hit Wall Street's Dow Jones were the prime
drag on the FTSE early on, according to analysts.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, German share prices fell sharply following a big
drop on Wall Street but rebounded to close higher as the US market
bounced back.
</P>
<P>
With the market turning its attention from Russia to Wall
Street, the blue chip Xetra Dax index was off by nearly 3 percent
in afternoon trading. But it regained ground and closed at
4,855.9, up 44.62 or 0.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Traders said sharp sell-offs did not materialize as expected
after the Dow Jones Industrial average made its second-largest
point drop ever on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Of course, Russia is still present in our minds, but Wall
Street is now the determining factor," Deutsche Bank dealer
Andreas Kehl was quoted by local media as saying.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, the Cac-40 index in Paris see-sawed all day, but
closed only 0.15 percent lower at 3,646.29 points.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said gains on Wall Street prompted late-session buying
and outweighed concerns about Russia's political and economic
outlook.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
