<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Toughens Regulations for Taxi Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 1 (Xinhua) -- Greece waged Tuesday a
stepped-up struggle against increasingly overcharging and poor
service by taxi drivers throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
Greek Transport and Communications Ministry warned Tuesday that
anyone caught overcharging passengers would have their vehicles
taken off the roads.
</P>
<P>
Minister Tassos Mandelis also sent a letter to prefectural
authorities asking for them to step up checks on taxis and to
implement the measures as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Taxi drivers reportedly might also be grounded and face fines
if they act inappropriately at airport, port and bus and railway
station pick-up points, refuse to take passengers or were
selective in who they pick up.
</P>
<P>
Greece's Consumer Protection Organization (CPO) said it has
received far more calls this year from people complaining about
the services offered, or not offered, by taxi drivers.
</P>
<P>
According to the CPO, overcharging, dirty cabs, doubling-up
fares, being selective about routes and destinations were just
some of the most frequently reported complaints.
</P>
<P>
Some 21 taxi drivers have been arrested for overcharging this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
